Event was "Partial collapse at end of eruption"
Explosions with ash emissions up to 3 km altitude.
Three lahars went down from the vent area of the middle venting site, one trending S, the other two roughly SW.
In the latter half of 16 June the group on Skala Dlinnaya Island heard booming noises. The sounds occurred 8-10 times in a time interval lasting 30-40 minutes.
Explosions produced ash plumes that rose to an altitude of 1.8 km (5,900 ft) a.s.l. and drifted SSE
Scientists reported a small plume that rose 400-500 m above the crater and areas of recently deposited ash on the S flank.

Volcanic tremor began to increase slightly on 6 June. Tremor increased gradually during the next few days. By 12 June, tremor had risen to several times background values and remained elevated through the end of July 2010.
An ash plume rose 1.2 km and caused ashfall in Goryachiye Klyuchi (9 km W) and Kurilsk (25 km away).
Based on analyses of satellite imagery, SVERT reported that a gas-and-ash plume rose 500 m above Grozny Group and drifted 15 km NE.
Based on visual observations and analyses of satellite imagery, SVERT reported that fumarolic activity at Grozny Group was elevated.
Based on visual observations, SVERT reported that an ash-and-gas plume from Grozny Group rose to 3 km altitude.
INGEOMINAS reported that ash emissions originating from an area N and W of the cone within Galeras's main crater rose 200 m above the crater rim.
Based on information from CVGHM, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes from Gamalama rose to altitudes of 2.4-3.0 km and drifted SE.

According to news articles, at least three people were killed and 1,000-2,600 more from several villages were displaced by lahars. The lahars destroyed many homes in the Tubo and Tofure villages and along the Togorara and Marikurubu rivers.
According to news articles, at least three people were killed and 1,000-2,600 more from several villages were displaced by lahars.
According to news articles, lahars destroyed many homes in the Tubo and Tofure villages and along the Togorara and Marikurubu rivers.
A phreatic eruption at 2027 produced ashfall in Ternate.
An eruption at 1415 was accompanied by rumbling sounds. A plume rose 1 km and drifted SE and S, producing ashfall at the Gamalama observation post five minutes later.
Observers watching the volcano from 15-22 June reported that a new bocca vent, about 20 m in diameter, had formed at the base of the NE wall of the active crater containing a thermal acid lake.

According to scientists from the Institute of Earth Sciences at the University of Iceland and the Icelandic Meteorological Office, an eruption from the subglacial Gr¡msvtn volcano began following about an hour of tremor. The eruption began at 1630.
In the afternoon lightning strikes ranged from 60-70 per hour (up to 300 during one hour) and were most frequent in the ash plume to the S.
Tephra fall was concentrated to the S and to a lesser extent N and E.

At 2000 the eruption plume rose to an altitude over 20 km. The plume altitude fell to 15 km during the night but occasionally still rose to 20 km. Ash from the lower part of the eruption plume drifted S and at higher altitudes drifted E. During the morning of 22 May the plume rose to an altitude of 10-15 km. The color of the plume was brown-to-grayish and sometimes black close to the source. Most of the plume drifted S, but lower parts traveled SW.
Venting came from four tephra cones in the main crater/caldera surrounded by meltwater.
A 420 m long lava flow appeared on the SW flank in both visible and infrared imagery from the Earth Observing-1 (EO-1) satellite's Advanced Land Imager (ALI).
MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued on 21 and 24 September 2012.

During a helicopter flight on 15 October, steamy lava fragments in a small area were observed. In the same area, during 15-17 October, frequent episodes of emission, forming big turbulent rings of gas and foaming, were observed on the sea surface. Volcanic ?bombs? with cores of white and porous pumice-like material encased in a fine coating of basaltic glass were floating on the surface over the eruption site.

Since 0515 volcanic tremor was clearly recorded by all of the seismic stations on the island, with highest amplitudes recorded in the southernmost station. The next day at about 0700 the amplitude of the tremor increased. During that morning residents on the S of the island reported feeling vibrations. After 21 October, most of the events were located in the N part of the island, aligned NNW-SSE from the center of the island to around 13 km offshore. The earthquakes ranged from 6-25 km in depth. Tremors continued through early February 2012. Tremors continued until early February. After 15 February 2012 the amplitude of the tremor showed very low values.
SERNAGEOMIN staff aboard an overflight reported three new craters along the S and SE edge of the caldera, with diameters of 200, 300, and 500 m.
Scientists aboard an overflight observed lahars in Rio Huemul, to the W.

At 1908 on 25 October an M 4.6 volcano-tectonic earthquake occurred at a depth of 19 km, followed by a seismic swarm starting at 2149. More than 100 events, with depths ranging from 15 to 25 km, were recorded through the next day; 12 of the events were M 3, and three events were M 4. Five earthquakes per hour were recorded between 1600 on 26 October and 1600 on 27 October. The most significant event, a M 3.6, occurred at 0227 on 27 October and was located in the SW edge of the crater. One earthquake per hour was recorded between 1600 on 27 October and 1600 on 28 October. Seismicity continued to decrease during 28-29 October.
Scientists aboard an overflight on 26 October observed a white plume with some ash content that rose 1.5 km.
During an overflight by INGEOMINAS on 14 January 2012 it was noted that the higher region of the dome had distinguishable spines that may have formed recently.
JMSDF reported a mud ejection at an old crater along the Asodai fault.
Emissions rose 20 m above the crater, and small amounts of ash rose more than 10 m and scattered within 20 m in every direction.
The ocean NE of the island was discolored, suggesting an offshore underwater eruption.
Satellite images showed a detached ash plume, 8 km in length, which drifted 39 km NE.
Lava flows were visible at the summit.
An ash plume rose to an altitude of 2.4 km and drifted 55 km SW.
Blocks originating from the lava dome traveled as far as 2 km down the flanks.
Multiple pyroclastic flows about 1.5-2.3 km long destroyed a bridge, damaged a house, and trapped 31 people (later rescued) between the flow paths.

Multiple pyroclastic flows about 1.5 km long destroyed a bridge, damaged a house, and trapped 31 people between the flow paths who were later evacuated. According to news articles, 600-1,200 people were evacuated from villages on the W flank.
According to a news article, about 600 people living on the flanks evacuated after the Alert Level was raised.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
According to a news article, pahoehoe lava flows traveled 150 m.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Darwin VAAC reported that a possible ash plume from Karkar rose to altitudes of 7.6-10.7 km and drifted NE and E.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery and wind data, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 9.1 km.

According to the Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA), weak tremor was detected at 0502 on 4 June. At ~0517, an eruption began, with explosions occurring intermittently until 1500. An ash plume drifted W from Satsuma Iwo-jima's summit, Iodake. The Tokyo Volcanic Ash Advisory Center (VAAC) issued two advisories on 4 June, although no ash was visible in satellite images.
An explosion produced a shock wave that was detected 12 km NE.
Lightning in the ash plume was visible in video footage.

On 28 January, a small lava dome 200 m in diameter appeared on the crater floor near the vent. In three days, it grew to ~600 m in diameter and attained a volume of more than 107 m3. ALOS satellite images disclosed that the dome grew to the point where it completely covered the active vent.

During an overflight on 29 January 2011, scientists from the ERI observed freshly erupted dome material on the crater floor and saw that the crater lake was gone. Fresh pyroclastic flow deposits in the SW crater had runout distances of 500-600 m.
Pumice from this eruption was composed of pyroxene-bearing andesite (57 to 62% SiO2), showing mingling of two magmas with different colors.
Some people in Miyazaki (55 km E) voluntarily evacuated and approximately 30 people in Takaharu (15 km E) spent the night in an evacuation center.
Car windows, solar panels, and roofs were damaged from a shockwave and rock fragments that ranged from lapilli to bombs (up to 0.7 m).
The largest explosion, at 0754 on 1 February 2011 was heard more than 7 km away, and broke glass in buildings and cars as far as 8 km away.

Roofs were damaged when volcanic bombs traveled up to 16 km NE; JMA reported that strong winds that day contributed to these long dispersal distances. According to local news reports, bombs struck and damaged cars parked in the service area of Miyazaki Expressway and they shattered windows in Kobayashi, 13 km NE.
Ballistics impacted the local region as far as 1 km W and N; ash was reported 60 km E, and lapilli reached 9 km from the crater, damaging solar heaters and roof panels in the town of Takaharu.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Tokyo VAAC reported that a possible eruption from Kliuchevskoi produced a plume that rose to an altitude of 5.2 km and drifted E.

Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Tokyo VAAC reported that a possible eruption from Kliuchevskoi produced a plume that rose to an altitude of 5.2 km and drifted E. Subsequent images that day showed continuing ash emissions that later dissipated.
KVERT reported that video footage and satellite imagery showed Strombolian explosions at Kliuchevskoi, along with crater incandescence and gas-and-steam emissions.
A weak thermal anomaly was detected in satellite imagery.
Video images recorded incandescence from the crater, and gas-and-steam plumes containing minor amounts of ash rising as high as 6 km and drifting NE.
Satellite images detected a large, bright thermal anomaly on 15-16 August.
Observations from Anderson confirmed lava bombs.
Chris Weber reported fire fountaining reaching ~10 m high.
Rosadi described and photographed large areas of incandescence within the summit crater.

Lava flowed down both the W and E sides of the volcano, leaving deep scars on both flanks. According to NASA's Earth Observatory, a satellite image of Krakatau acquired on 4 September showed fresh lava flows descending the SE flank of Anak Krakatau, extending the shoreline by about 100 m.
According to the Darwin VAAC, an ash plume at an altitude of 1.5 km was observed by a pilot.
Increased emissions from the crater fluctuated from white to gray, indicating possible ash. Plumes rose 320 m and drifted SE.
A group of conservation biologists heard a 'whoosh' from two boiling, rolling, lava pools that spilled pitch-black lava into a growing lake flowing E in the crater floor.
Seismicity increased on 31 December and intensified on 2 January with tremor commencing at 1400, the same day incandescence was observed.
Black smoke rose from the crater.
According to news articles, 500 people evacuated their homes because of increased activity.
A phreatic eruption from Tompaluan crater was possibly triggered by high rainfall. It produced an ash plume that rose 400 m.
A phreatic eruption ejected material that fell around the crater and produced a gray plume that rose 400 m above the crater rim and drifted N.
A phreatic eruption produced a gray plume that rose 400 m above the crater rim and drifted N.
According to news articles, close to 1,000 residents were evacuated from the area.

A local mayor noted that 6,000 people were in shelters and one person had died from a heart attack while evacuating. Other articles stated that 5,200 people had evacuated. HOPE Worldwide, a non-profit non-governmental organization, issued a report on 15 July 2011 stating that at 2331 on the 14 July Lokon erupted and sent lava, ash, and gases 1.5 km over the summit. "No death is yet to be reported due to the eruption, but there are 4,412 persons displaced in the Tomohon city, just south of Manado city, the capital of North Sulawesi Province." Displaced residents went to schools and a city park.
According to a news article an explosion sent incandescent material as far as 800 m away from Tompaluan crater.
According to the Darwin VAAC, ground-based observers reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 3 km.
According to the Darwin VAAC, ground-based observers reported that an ash plume from Lokon-Empung rose to an altitude of 3 km. Satellite imagery showed an ash plume drifting 185 km SE.
Dense gray plumes rose 300-1,000 m above the crater on eight occasions.
According to a news article from 5 March, several eruptions from Marapi produced ash plumes during the previous week.
According to news articles, an eruption produced an ash plume that rose 1.5 km above the crater.
PHIVOLCS reported that a small phreatic eruption occurred at 0800 and lasted for 2 minutes and 26 seconds.
A gray-to-brown ash cloud rose 500 m above the crater and drifted WSW.
According to a news article, the eruption ejected large "room-sized rocks" towards about 30 climbers, killing five and injuring eight.

The major highway between Magelang and Yogyakarta was cut off when a 60 m wide section of blacktop was torn away by torrential mudflows along the eroded banks of the Putih river. As a result, hundreds of homes within 12 different villages near the river were inundated forcing 5,000 people to flee. There were three fatalities.
Seismographs in Rarotonga recorded eruptive activity.
The Toulouse VAAC reported that an eruption from Nabro (originally attributed to Dubbi) started between 0000 and 0200 on 13 June.
A thermal satellite image acquired at night revealed a 15-km-long lava flow that had traveled NW.

According to a news article, the eruption resulted in at least seven deaths in the first few days, injured many, and displaced thousands in Eritrea, and affected about 5,000 Ethiopians living near the border. In Bidu woreda, deaths of 31 persons were reported by 6 July as a result of the volcanic ash.
Virunga National Park reported that a fissure eruption began low on the flank, producing slow-moving lava flows that traveled into unpopulated areas to the N.
Virunga National Park reported that a fissure eruption began low on the flank, producing slow-moving lava flows that traveled into unpopulated areas to the N.
GORISK reported two days of "intense seismic activity" prior to the start of the eruption.
Video posted on the park's website showed a fissure eruption with lava fountains.
Virunga National Park staff and rangers observed thunder and lightening.

GORISK noted that radar images showed the largest deformation ever detected by the method (InSAR) since the early 1990's over Nyamuragira. A preliminary analysis of the observed deformation suggested an affected area of more than 250 square kilometers. The ground rose more than 50 cm at the eruptive site where the spatter cone was developing. Another 15 cm of deformation was detected within the caldera accompanied by deflation on the flanks.

The initial scoria cone appeared inactive and second cone formed to the N of the first cone. Both cones were about 300 m high. The second cone was extremely active during the duration of the observations (about 15 hours) with fire fountains over twice the height of the cone.
A Volcano Discovery Team observed the newly formed cinder cones located about 10 km E of the summit crater. They reported three coalescent cones with the largest cone containing a small lava lake.

A Volcano Discovery Team observed three coalescent cones with the largest cone containing a small lava lake. The lake ejected spatter every few seconds as high as 200 m above the summit; individual bombs reached the base of the cone.

A Volcano Discovery Team observed three coalescent cones with the largest cone containing a small lava lake. The lake ejected spatter every few seconds as high as 200 m above the summit; individual bombs reached the base of the cone.
Tens of MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued daily through late March 2012, before tapering off to a few per day.

On 24 April 2013 tephra was ejected 25 m high by weak explosions. Incandescence from the crater was observed through the night, and explosions were detected the next day. Incandescence and explosions were again detected on 29 April.
INSIVUMEH reported that during 13-14 and 16-18 March 2013 weak gas-and-ash plumes rose and drifted N, NW, and S.

On 24 April 2013 tephra was ejected 25 m high by weak explosions. Incandescence from the crater was observed through the night, and explosions were detected the next day. Incandescence and explosions were again detected on 29 April.

A late June 2013 investigation of MacKenney cone determined that a 15 m high cone had been the source of recent explosive activity. The cone continued to grow and was 30 m high by about 20 July. By 24 July the cone was 4 m above the MacKenney crater rim. In a report on 21 January 2014 volcanologists observed that the cone in Mackenney Crater had been completely destroyed, leaving a deep crater that produced fumarolic activity.
A small effusive eruption occurred for about two hours.
A NOAA research vessel reported incandescence at the summit at night.
Gas emissions and possible light ash rose to 0.9 km altitude and drifted W.
Trace amounts of ashfall were reported on parts of the island.

According to the Washington VAAC a pilot observed a plume containing a small amount of ash that rose to an altitude below 1.5 km. Satellite imagery showed a gas-and-steam plume, with possible ash content, drifting 204 km SSW.
Based on information from the Honolulu MWO, satellite imagery, and a pilot observation, the Washington VAAC reported gas emissions and a possible light-brown ash plume drifting E.
The Marianas Emergency Management Center reported local observations of ashfall on the island.
A single MODVOLC thermal alert was issued.

According to the Washington VAAC, ash from an unknown volcano was reported by a pilot in the vicinity of Pagan. Satellite imagery suggested continuing degassing, but it was possible that ash was present in a 30-km-wide plume that was drifting almost 90 km S.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash-and-steam plumes from Pago rose to an altitude of 13.7 km and drifted 75 km NE.

PVMBG stated that dome growth began on 8 October 2012. Local people observed the dome growing next to the Rokatenda crater in late October. Multiple photographs confirmed continuing dome growth in early December when it was about 150 m high, and the basal diameter was 200-250 m. The lava-dome volume had been an estimated 5.1 million cubic meters on 13 January.
Ash plumes rose from 1.5 to 4 km altitude on most days, drifting primarily NW and W as far as 150 km.
Small pyroclastic flows descended the lava dome.

According to PVMBG, a substantial pyroclastic flow traveled NW from the summit down the Ojaubi drainage towards a village on the beach and killed five fisherman. BBC News Asia reported six dead, four adults and two children.
After the 10 August eruption, the BNPB source said that at least another 1,203 had moved by 30 August.

Seismicity increased at 0800 along with the presence of an intense thermal anomaly at the summit observed in satellite imagery. Several spikes in seismicity occurred between 0900 and 1000. Seismicity persisted for several days.
Pilot reports and satellite images confirmed activity; a spatter-fed lava flow advanced about 0.5 km down the N flank.

Minor steam-and-ash emissions from the summit were visible from Cold Bay (60 km SW). According to AVO, a diffuse ash plume drifted about 160 km NE at an altitude of 4.6 km before dissipating on 14 May. Steam-and-ash clouds observed with a web camera occasionally rose up to 6.1 km. On 15 May a pilot reported a dark ash cloud drifting ENE at an altitude of 6.1 km. The next day a continuous ash, steam, and gas cloud extended downwind 50-100 km at an altitude of about 6.1 km.
Event was "Partial collapse at end of eruption"
A small amount of ash was observed rising to 800 m.

Between 31 October and 11 November IGP-OVS reported an increase in emissions of steam and ash, some rising to 3,000 m above the crater and drifting S, N, and NE. The highest steam and ash emissions in mid-November were recorded at 1,600 m above the crater, and drifted both N and S. On 23 November two explosive events released ash plumes that rose 2.5 and 2.2 km above the crater and drifted S and SE.

According to IGP a small 64-second-long explosion at Ubinas, that started at 0741, produced an ash plume that rose 2.5 km above the crater's base, and drifted S and SE. A second explosion occurred at 1004 and generated an ash plume that rose 2.2 km and drifted S. Residents of Ubinas felt a slight rumble at the time of the second explosion.

An increase in the number of hybrid-type seismic events was noted in December 2014, and also a brief spike in "tornillo" events, but no explosive ash-bearing emissions were reported. A large increase in LP seismic events was recorded on 26 December.
In their monthly summary, OVI-INGEMMET reported referred to 'two light gray emissions with slight ash content', and a plume height of 1,500 m above the crater.

OVI-INGEMMET reported three small lahars, one on 21 January in Chiflon ravine and two on 31 January in Volc nmayo creek (SE of the volcano), which caused damage to the road linking the towns of Querapi and Ubinas, a few kilometers SE.
OVI-INGEMMET reported minor amounts of ash in the emissions from the volcano.

Two lahars descended drainages on the SE side of the volcano on 6 February and caused damage near Tonohaya (10 km SE) and to the access road to the village; another lahar reported on 13 February in Volc nmayo creek was reported by villagers as 1.6 m deep.
OVI-INGEMMET noted that a villager in Ubinas (6.5 km SSE) reported a lahar on Volc nmayo creek.
IGP-OVS reported sporadic ash emissions in the morning.

Volcano-tectonic (VT) earthquakes showed an upward trend from the beginning of February 2015 into the first week of March. Two main foci were observed, the first located 2 km NW of the crater at depths between 1 and 5 km, the second 1 km W of the crater between 1 and 3 km deep. In the last week of March, the numbers of LP and Hybrid earthquakes each increased 10-fold from the previous week's measurements.

Two phreatic explosions were detected on 8 April. The explosions occurred at 0424 and 0550, generated ash-and-gas plumes that rose 2-2.5 km above the crater and drifted SE. OVI-INGEMMET reported 12 minor explosions between 8 and 12 April during constant tremors. In a joint announcement on 17 April, IGP-OVS and OVI-INGEMMET reported six explosions between 12 and 17 April with nearly-constant ash emissions between 1,000 and 3,500 m above the summit crater, and ashfall in the local villages within 15 km. The largest explosion on 15 April released 24.5 MJ of energy and sent an ash plume 3.5 km above the summit. The other explosions (at 1408 on 15 April, at 0600 on 16 April, and at 0743, 0936, and 1518 on 17 April) generated ash plumes that rose 1.5-1.8 km.

On 8 April 2015 at 0332 local time IGP-OVS reported a small explosion that initiated a sequence of constant seismic tremors and ash emissions that lasted for 41 hours. Ash drifted SE. This was followed by four days (11-14 April) of pulsing ash emissions and seismic tremors.  Very little wind caused the ash column to rise nearly vertically to 2,500 m above the crater.  In a joint announcement on 17 April, IGP-OVS and OVI-INGEMMET reported six explosions between 12 and 17 April with nearly-constant ash emissions between 1,000 and 3,500 m above the summit crater. Ash plumes drifted 15 km SW, S, and SE. The largest ash plume, generated from an explosion detected at 0759 on 15 April, rose 3.5 km. The other explosions (at 1408 on 15 April, at 0600 on 16 April, and at 0743, 0936, and 1518 on 17 April) generated ash plumes that rose 1.5-1.8 km. Ash emissions continued at decreased levels during the third week of April according to both OVI-INGEMMET and IGP-OVS, with plumes not rising beyond 1,000 m above the summit crater.

Ash deposits up to 1.5 cm thick were noted in Ubinas (6 km SE), Escacha (10 km SE), and elsewhere in the Ubinas valley by 12 April 2015. An isopach map of ash thickness from explosions beginning on 8 April was generated by IGP-OVS scientists; they estimated the ashfall at 650,000 m3. In a joint announcement on 10 April, IGP-OVS and OVI-INGEMMET reported that field observations on 8 and 9 April revealed pyroclastic fragments 20-40 cm in diameter in areas 200 m N of the crater. In addition, ash deposit thicknesses were more than 5 cm inside the crater, 3 cm at the edge of the crater, 1 cm above elevations of 4,800 m, and 1 mm in areas 6 km away in Ubinas. Trace ash deposits were observed as far away as Anascapa (10 km SE). In a joint announcement on 17 April, IGP-OVS and OVI-INGEMMET reported six explosions between 12 and 17 April with nearly-constant ash emissions and ashfall in the local villages within 15 km. During the third week of April according to both OVI-INGEMMET and IGP-OVS, minor ashfall was still reported in nearby villages.
In a joint announcement on 10 April, IGP-OVS and OVI-INGEMMET reported that field observations on 8 and 9 April revealed pyroclastic fragments 20-40 cm in diameter in areas 200 m N of the crater.

Lahars descended the Volcanmayo drainage on the S flank during to a distance of 10 km, affecting agricultural land, irrigation canals, and roads as a result of the large volumes of ashfall and abundant snowfall followed by plentiful solar radiation.

According to IGP-OVS, ash emissions increased on 1 May 2015, rising to 800 m above the summit. OVI-INGEMMET reported an 1,100 m plume on 11 May that drifted E and NE. Increasingly dense, intermittent ash-and-water-vapor plumes rising to between 1,100 and 1,800 m continued into the third week of May. IGP-OVS scientists visited between 20 and 22 May; they observed water vapor, gas, and 400-m-high ash emissions. The Buenos Aires VAAC reported continuous emissions of steam with diffuse ash rising to an altitude of 6 km (400 m above the summit) and drifting 100 km ENE on 23 May, and emissions to 6.4 km drifting 30 km SE the next day. Additional emissions with bursts of fine ash and bluish gases on 29 and 30 May led to a greater volume of total ash emission than the previous week, although the plumes only rose to 400 m.
OVI-INGEMMET reported a 1,100 m plume that drifted E and NE, causing ashfall in Ubinas, Santa Rosa de Phara, and Eschacha (5-10 km E and S).

Pulsing ash emissions and a sudden increase to 748 LP seismic events were recorded by IGP-OVS on 1 June 2015. IGP-OVS reported five ash emission events between 3 and 5 June with plume heights to 1,200 m above the summit. These events were reported by the Buenos Aires VAAC as continuous emissions rising to 7 km and drifting 30 km E. During the second week of June, OVI-INGEMMET noted that ash emissions were minor and continuous with fine, light gray or white ash, and bluish magmatic gases; the plumes rose from 300 to 1,300 m above the summit. Constant ash emissions from 9 to 11 June rose to 1,400 m above the summit. The Buenos Aires VAAC reported a brief emission on 17 June of volcanic ash that rose to 6.1 km altitude. OVI-INGEMMET reported that large quantities of ash were emitted during 20-22 June in plumes rising to 1,800 m. The Buenos Aires VAAC also reported continuous and sporadic emissions during 20-22 June to 6.7 km altitude. During the last week of June, IGP-OVS noted that four explosions occurred between 24 and 27 June with emissions rising to 3,000 m above the summit (8,670 m altitude), and that 13 emission events occurred on 28 June. The Buenos Aires VAAC reported an explosive eruption on 28 June with a plume to 7 km altitude, and continuous emissions over the next few days rising to 6.7 km and drifting E.

In their annual report, IGP-OVS pointed out that a spike in hybrid-type seismic events on 14 June occurred a few hours prior to a thermal anomaly that was recorded by the MIROVA system. Another thermal anomaly was detected on 16 June.
OVI-INGEMMET reported that large quantities of ash were emitted in plumes rising to 1,800 m; ashfall was reported in the villages in the Ubinas Valley to the SE.

During the last week of June, IGP-OVS noted that four explosions occurred between 24 and 27 June with emissions rising to 3,000 m above the summit (8,670 m altitude). The Buenos Aires VAAC reported an explosive eruption with a plume to 7 km altitude on 28 June 2015.

During early July 2015, decreasing tremors and ash emissions with plumes to 2,500 m above the crater were typical according to OVI-INGEMMET. On 1 July the Buenos Aires VAAC reported ongoing emissions rising to an altitude of 6.7 km and drifting SE. Explosions on 9 and 11 July emitted dense plumes that were observed by the Buenos Aires VAAC rising to 6.7 and 7.6 km. A dense ash plume from an explosion observed by OVI-INGEMMET on 16 July caused ashfall in Ubinas; the Buenos Aires VAAC reported its plume to nearly 8 km altitude and drifting E. Constant gas, steam, and ash emissions were observed during 21-24 July. A significant explosion occurred at 1903 local time on 25 July. It registered at 507 MJ of energy, the largest of 2015, and ejected ash, lapilli, and bombs to the SE. It was followed by a second smaller explosion one hour later. The plume from the second event was reported to rise 4,000 m above the crater by OVI-INGEMMET (9,670 m altitude).

An explosion on 3 July caused ashfall in Ubinas to the SE. Larger explosions on 9 and 11 July emitted dense plumes that were observed by the Buenos Aires VAAC rising to 6.7 and 7.6 km. A dense ash plume from an explosion observed by OVI-INGEMMET on 16 July caused ashfall in Ubinas. They also noted a sharp decrease in RSAM values for 14 hours prior to a significant explosion that occurred at 1903 local time on 25 July. The explosion registered at 507 MJ of energy, the largest of 2015, and ejected ash, lapilli, and bombs to the SE. The explosion was heard and felt in Querapi and Ubinas. It was followed by a second smaller explosion one hour later.

Explosions on 3 and 16 July 2015 caused ashfall in Ubinas to the SE. On 25 July the largest explosion of 2015 ejected ash, lapilli, and bombs to the SE. Ashfall was reported up to 20 km away. Ash deposits 3 mm thick were observed in Ubinas and Escacha, along with lapilli fragments as large as 1.5 cm.

A large explosion registered at 507 MJ of energy and ejected ash, lapilli, and bombs to the SE. Fragments of incandescent rocks were observed S and E of the crater, and ashfall was reported up to 20 km away.

A large explosion ejected ash, lapilli, and bombs to the SE. Fragments of incandescent rocks were observed S and E of the crater, and ashfall was reported up to 20 km away. Ash deposits 3 mm thick were observed in Ubinas and Escacha, along with lapilli fragments as large as 1.5 cm.
The explosion was heard and felt in Querapi and Ubinas.

IGP-OVS scientists conducted a field visit during 5-7 August 2015 and observed impact craters from volcanic bombs ejected during the 25 July explosion that were up to 2 m in diameter as far as 1.4 km from the crater.

OVI-INGEMMET reported dense and continuous emissions of ash, steam, and gases throughout the month. A moderate ash plume on 6 August that drifted NNE at 6.7 km altitude was the only plume reported by the Buenos Aires VAAC in August. IGP-OVS noted continuous tremors for 36 hours beginning on 10 August with minor ash emissions. The highest ash plumes of 2,300 m above the crater were observed on 27 August.

The Buenos Aires VAAC reported a narrow, diffuse ash plume on 6 September at 6.1 km altitude extending 25 km ENE. The pulsing ash emissions observed by IGP-OVS on 9 and 10 September were recorded by the Buenos Aires VAAC as an irregular puff rising to 6.1 km. They also noted an explosive puff to 6.7 km on 21 September. A large (53 MJ) explosion on 28 September emitted a significant amount of ash and gas 4,000 m above the summit. The Buenos Aires VAAC reported a plume drifting NE that rose to 8.2 km altitude from this event, followed by another explosive eruption on 29 September with a plume that rose to 7.3 km. IGP-OVS reported an explosion on 30 September with an ash plume that rose 1,400 m above the crater.

Lava fountains, seen from the air, were ejected from a 500-m-long NE-SW trending fissure on the NE flank of Eyjafjll at an elevation of about 1,000 m. Airborne observers during 0400-0700 described a short eruptive fissure with fire fountaining from 10-12 vents reaching up to ~ 100 m height. Lava fountains remained active through 5 April.

The onset of seismic tremor indicated an eruption from a new vent on the S rim of the central caldera, capped by Eyjafjallajkull glacier. After about 1100 on 18 April, tremor intensified beyond levels maintained since 16 April. Daily solutions from continuous, 15-second GPS stations operated by IMO and IES, revealed centimeter-scale horizontal movements toward the center of the volcano, with some stations also registering centimeter-scale vertical elevation decreases. Tremor with a dominant frequency of 0.5 Hz remained continuous during this second eruptive phase.
A pulsating eruptive column reached above 8 km altitude, and lightning was frequently seen within the plume. There were at least 115 lightning strikes in vicinity of the eruption.
An ash plume rose 2.1 km altitude.
An ash plume rose 3 km altitude and drifted less than 30 km N.
An ash plume rose 1.8 km altitude and drifted 75 km SW.
A gas-and-steam plume containing some ash rose 2.1 km altitude and drifted 25 km SW.
An ash plume rose 2.1 km altitude and drifted SW.
KVERT reported intermittent thermal anomalies through November 2012. MODVOLC reported intermittent thermal alerts through 19 August 2010.

The Darwin VAAC issued an advisory of an eruption plume to 9.1 km altitude reported at 0237 UTC on 8 November 2012. In a second advisory about two hours later they noted that an ash plume was not visible in satellite imagery.
Incandescence from Manam's South Crater was visible at 4-5 minute intervals.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal alerts; one on 10 Aug 2010, three on 4 Sep, increasing in frequency and intensity through December.
Diffuse black ash rose a few hundred meters above the rim.
Periodic ejections of lava fragments rose to 400-500 m above the rim.
Ash plumes rose to an altitude of 2.4 km and drifted 55 km NW.
Incandescence from Manam's South Crater was visible at night.
Incandescent ejecta tens to hundreds of meters above South Crater was reported from observers in Bogia, about 23 km SSW.
An ash plume rose to 2.4 km and drifted 55 km NW.
Ash plumes rose from Manam's South Crater.
Minor ashfall was reported on the NW part of the island.
An ash plume rose to an altitude of 4.3 km and drifted 130 km NW.
An ash plume rose to an altitude of 4.6 km and drifted about 95 km NW.
Ash plumes rose to an altitude of 2.7 km and drifted about 95 km NW.
Light brown to dark gray ash plumes were seen rising 400-500 m above Manam's South Crater.
Ash plumes rose daily from South Crater to as high as 3 km above the summit.
Intermittent incandescent ejecta was observed. Blocks rolled down the SE valley.

Three pyroclastic flows descended the SE valley, stopping a few hundred meters from the coastline. The first and largest pyroclastic flow devastated a broad unpopulated area between Warisi and Dugulava villages.
Ash plumes drifted NW and caused light ashfall in Tabele.
Incandescence was observed at both craters.
Diffuse brown ash plumes occasionally rose from South Crater.
Gray emissions were reported from Main Crater.
The only evidence of activity between Jan and Jun 2011 was a single MODVOLC thermal alert located near the summit.
MODVOLC thermal alerts begin and continue with increasing numbers each month.
Intermittent ash plumes were observed. They rose to altitudes of 1.8-2.1 km and drifted 45-90 km NW and W.
Ash plumes rose to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifted 150-220 km NW.
An ash plume rose to an altitude of 3 km and drifted about 90 km NE.
RVO reported ash plumes that rose several hundred meters above both craters during the months of Dec 2011 and Jan 2012.
Incandescent ejecta was reported from both craters multiple times during Dec 2011 and Jan 2012.
Observers noted there were possibly three vents emitting columns of vapor and ash.
MODVOLC thermal alerts resume 29 April 2012; increasing to multiple per day in late June 2012, continuing through 19 June 2013.
Gray and brown ash clouds were observed on 7, 9, and 12 May 2012.
Dense gray and black ash plumes were reported often through July rising up to 700 m above the crater.
Ash fell intermittently on the NW part of the island and other areas downwind through June.
Four pyroclastic flows (at 0700, 0720, 0722, and 0729) channeled into the SE valley. The last pyroclastic flow was the largest and reached 300-400 m above sea level but was far from populated areas.
Small lava flows descended the SW flank.

Four pyroclastic flows traveled down the SE valley at 0638, 0640, during 1200-1300, and at 1428. The first event was the largest, and generated an ash plume that rose 1.8 km above the crater and drifted NW.
Intermittent dark gray and black ash plumes rising up to 3.4 km altitude multiple times each month.
Reported multiple times during the month.
Reported multiple times during the month.
Reported multiple times during the month.
Two vents in the SE valley, just below the summit crater, produced small-volume lava flows, channeled into the deep ravines on the upper slopes of the SE valley.
At 1700 a small pyroclastic flow traveled down the upper part of the SW valley.
A lava flow was extruded into the SE valley from a new vent beneath Southern Crater.
A small volume of lava effused from a SE valley vent that formed in August. Small volumes of lava also flowed from a vent, adjacent to the first vent, which opened in late November.
An ash plume rose to an altitude of 10.1 km and drifted 55 km SW.
An ash plume rose to altitudes of 6.1-7.6 km and drifted 110-150 km ESE.
Strombolian activity was sustained for extended periods during 9-11 and 13-14 April.
Lava was observed flowing from a new vent on the headwall of SW valley during a brief clear period from 1800 to 1850.
Ash and scoria fell in most villages between Dugulava on the SW side of the island and Kuluguma on the NW side.

Loud booming noises were heard each day; however, between 0700 and 1900 on 27 April the noises became frequent, louder, and explosive in nature, and were heard at Bogia, 25-30 km SSW of Manam on the N coast of the mainland. Strong explosions vibrated structures on the island.
Two explosions at midnight were heard in Bogia, 25-30 km SSW of Manam on the N coast of the mainland. Loud noises continued through 20 June.
Multiple diffuse gray emissions were observed.
Incandescent fragment ejections from the crater were observed at night through 18 June. Strombolian activity increased on 18 June, generating plumes that rose 800 m above the crater.
At 0635 a small-to-moderate sized pyroclastic flow traveled down the SE valley and stopped 400 m above sea level. Ash plumes from the pyroclastic flow rose 900 m above the crater.
A loud explosion was heard in Bogia, 25-30 km SSW of Manam on the N coast of the mainland.
Ash plumes rose as high as 4.6 km altitude and drifted up to 150 km.
Bright incandescence from the crater and occasional ejected incandescent fragments were observed.

Light gray ash clouds were visible.

Light gray ash clouds rose from Southern Crater during 6, 10, and 13-14 December, and from Main Crater on 13-14 December.

Avalanches traveled as far as 1.5 km down the Batang (S), Batu Awang (E), and Nanitu drainages.
Avalanches from the end of the flow traveled 2 km down the Batang, Kahetang (E), and Nanitu drainages.
An ash cloud was visible in a satellite image at 0756 that rose to an altitude of ~ 4.9 km and drifted to the SW.
Satellite images from 31 May showed minor deposits on the upper flanks, and a 1 June image showed debris flow deposits down the E flank and ashfall deposits on the SW flank.
Thermal anomalies from the crater were seen in satellite imagery during the previous few days. A weak thermal anomaly was detected on 2 June.
Instruments recorded weak, faltering, and spasmodic volcanic tremor.
Volcanic tremor was first detected on 8 November. It became almost continuous by 22 November along with degassing.
Satellite imagery showed ash plumes drifting 55-165 km at an altitude of 4.3 km.
Ashfall was heavy around the crater and was reported in areas as far away as the Juanda Airport (70 km NNW) in Surabaya.
Warm, easterly winds (called Puelche-type winds) carried ash and sulfurous smells to the town of Los Que¤es (~30 km NE of the volcano).
SERNAGEOMIN officials flew over the volcano and observed modest pyroclastic eruptions, emissions slightly stronger than those observed for during the previous 3 weeks.
A persistent thermal anomaly near the summit was visible in satellite imagery on most days after 16 August and intermittent during September.
A possible ash plume rose to ~7.6-km altitude and drifted E.

An observer from the Emergency Management Office (EMO) in Saipan photographed an area of discolored ocean water and possible light-colored floating material about 7 km S of Sarigan during an overflight. The area was about 1.6 km long; two days later, the area of affected water was about twice the size of Sarigan Island.
A plume of mostly water vapor was seen in satellite imagery rising to a possible altitude of 12.2 km and dissipating as it drifted S over Guam.
Observers on Sarigan reported hearing a loud explosion from the S, and shortly thereafter received ashfall.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes drifted 35-130 km at an altitude of 3 km.

Very fine ashfall was reported on 30 May in areas to the SSW, S, and SSE. It was reported on 3 and 8 June, ~10 km NW (in Ulamona). During 9 June-9 July, fine ashfall was reported almost daily on the NW, SW, and sometimes W flanks. During 6-24 August fine ash fell on the NW and W flanks.

Intermittent gray and brown ash plumes rose a few hundred meters above the summit. Between 3-6 June, the plumes extended up to 315 km W. During 1-5 July, ash plumes drifted 55-195 km at an altitude of 3 km.
Four major tectonic earthquakes with magnitudes ranging from 5.8-7.3 on New Britain Island. Structural damage and fatalities reported. Many aftershocks from 18 July 7.3 event.
The Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifted 55 km NE.
Gray ash plumes occasionally drifted NE, SW, and NW.
RSAM values increased, fluctuated, and peaked at 1,300 units before declining back to 100 units.
During 10, 13-14, 17, and 19-27 May, RVO reported gray-to-brown ash plumes rose above Ulawun's summit crater. On 17 May, emissions became briefly forceful and booming noises were reported.
Activity was characterized by brown-to-gray ash plumes that rose less than 500 m and produced fine ashfall to the SE.
Light ashfall was reported in areas between Ubili in the NW and Voluvolu in the NE and on the NW and W flanks.
Ashfall was reported in multiple areas to the W and SW.
A steam-and-ash plume rose to an altitude of 11 km and drifted W and NW.

Ashfall was reported in areas SW and WNW.
Explosions joined two craters (2006-2007) into one based on an aerial survey on 11 November 2010.
An ash explosion  produced an ash-and steam plume rising 700 m above the crater drifting SW.

There were 13 lahar-related seismic signals detected during 27-28 February. Continuous heavy rain caused small lahars on the flanks and in river channels, including the Cogon and Monbon rivers to the SW.
Inflation, detected since March, increased from background levels of 0.1 to 0.3 mm per day to a rate of 11 mm per day.
CVGHM reported that a pattern of increasing seismicity began to emerge in early September.

CVGHM raised the Alert Level to 4, and recommended immediate evacuation for several communities (news reports estimated 11,000-19,000 people) within a 10-km radius.
Following the eruption intense tremor took place. It was felt by people up to 20 km from the volcano.
CVGHM reported that two pyroclastic flows occurred on 30 October following an early morning explosion.
Ash plumes rose to an altitude of 6.1 km and drifted as far as 75 km.

Although fog often prevented observations, white and brown plumes rising 100 m above the crater drifted SW on 25 November, and brownish plumes rose 300 m above the crater on 27 November.

Lahars and high water damaged infrastructure and caused temporary road closures.

According to news articles a lahar traveled through the village of Sleman, approximately 20 km SW of Merapi, burying 21 homes in addition to vehicles and livestock. At least 200 residents were evacuated.
The weekly report by BPPTK (20 March to 12 June 2011), described plumes of gas and ash that occurred regularly. The average height of these plumes was about 500 m.

A slow but steady increase in the number and magnitude of earthquakes.
Inflation of the summit area began in late August. A report on 13 September noted localized deformation W of Dolomieu crater and a small number of landslides in the crater.

On 20 September a significant increase in earthquakes was recorded, although the average magnitude was low. The earthquakes were located at the base of Piton de la Fournaise, W and S of Dolomieu crater.
A seismic crisis was characterized by several tens of earthquakes located beneath Dolomieu crater, and occurred in conjunction with 3 cm of inflation.
A seismic crisis was characterized by several tens of earthquakes located beneath Dolomieu crater, and occurred in conjunction with 3 cm of inflation.

The summit area inflated 3-7 cm and an increase in the number of landslides in the crater was detected.
Observations during an overflight and through web cameras located in the vicinity of Arenas Crater revealed that gas-and-ash plumes rose at most 1 km above the crater and drifted W and NW.

Seismic signals indicated that ash emissions continued. Based on analysis of satellite imagery, the Washington VAAC reported that an ash plume drifted 40 km W. The VAAC also noted that the Bogota MWO reported ash emissions drifting NNW at an altitude of 9.1 km.
A satellite image showed ash deposits on the N, NW, W and SW flanks.

A satellite image acquired on 6 June showed an ash plume rising from the crater and drifting NW. Based on analysis of satellite imagery and information from INGEOMINAS, the Washington VAAC reported that gas plumes possibly containing some ash drifted 75-110 km W, WNW, and N during 7 and 9-10 June. Ash plumes drifted almost 30 km SE on 8 June. INGEOMINAS reported that on 11 June seismic signals indicated continuing ash emissions.

Seismic signals on 15 and 18 June indicated continuing ash emissions. Based on analysis of satellite imagery and web camera views, the Washington VAAC reported that on 17 June a 5.5-km-wide gas plume, possibly containing ash, drifted more than 90 km NW. The VAAC noted on 18 June that INGEOMINAS reported a gas-and-ash plume drifting N and NW at an altitude of 6.1 km. The plume was later detected in satellite imagery drifting more than 90 km NW.
Reports stated that seismic signals had indicated continuing gas and ash emissions.
An explosion produced an ash plume that rose 8 km above the crater and drifted SW.
An explosion produced an ash plume that rose 8 km above the crater and drifted SW. The Washington VAAC reported that a 7.5-km-wide ash plume was detected in satellite imagery drifting 75 km W.
Ashfall was reported in areas near the volcano including Manizales (30 km NW) and Villamar¡a (28 km NW).

INGEOMINAS noted that seismic signals indicated continuing gas and ash emissions on 3 July. During 5-9 July seismic signals at Nevado del Ruiz indicated continuing gas and ash emissions. On 6 and 8 July a gas-and-ash plume rose 400-500 m above the crater and drifted SW, NW, and W. The Washington Volcanic Ash Advisory Center (VAAC) reported that a gas-and-ash plume was observed in satellite imagery drifting 65 km on 8 July. On 9 July INGEOMINAS noted that a gas-and-ash plume, observed with a web camera, rose around 400 m above the crater.

Low levels of tremor were detected, possibly associated with continuing gas and ash emissions. A gas-and-ash plume observed with a web camera rose 1 km above the crater and drifted W on 12 August.

A total of 140 low-magnitude earthquakes (M< 1.8) were detected in a seismic swarm that began at 0956 and ended at 1800. The earthquakes were located about 4 km WSW of Arenas Crater at depths of less than 5 km. On 13 August a seismic swarm was characterized by events less than M 1, and located NE of Arenas Crater at depths between 3 and 5 km.
Ashfall was reported in Brisas (50 km SW).
A thin layer of ash was deposited at the observatory in Manizales.

Variations in volcanic tremor amplitude were detected, possibly associated with continuing gas and ash emissions. Web cameras showed gas-and-ash plumes rising 400 m and drifting W and NW during 15-16 August. A gas plume rose 400 m and drifted NW on 19 August.
Variations in volcanic tremor amplitude were detected, possibly associated with continuing gas and ash emissions.
The Washington VAAC issued a notice about a possible eruption. Cloud cover prevented observations of a possible ash plume but elevated seismicity was detected.
Based on analysis of satellite imagery, the Washington VAAC reported a diffuse plume possibly contained ash and drifted almost 55 km NE.

INGEOMINAS reported that seismicity associated with fluid movement beneath Nevado del Ruiz was detected on 13-14 April along with volcano-tectonic earthquakes. The earthquakes were located NW of Arenas Crater at depths between 5 and 9 km; the largest was a M 2.6, felt by officials of Los Nevados National Park in the area of Brisas (50 km SW). On 15 April a M 3 volcano-tectonic earthquake was located NW of Arenas Crater at a depth of 6.6 km. Later that day a M 2.5 volcano-tectonic earthquake was located again NW of Arenas Crater at a depth of 5.78 km. On 16 April at 0714 a M 3.2 earthquake was located in the same area at a depth of 6.22 km. Earthquakes continued to be felt by officials in the National Park.
During the early morning of 14 April webcams recorded a gas-and-ash plume that rose 630 m and drifted NW.
Continuous volcanic tremor associated with emissions was detected; ashfall was reported in Los Nevados Natural Park and in some parts of Manizales (30 km NW).
Continuous volcanic tremor associated with emissions was detected; ashfall was reported in Los Nevados Natural Park and in some parts of Manizales (30 km NW).

Early morning, gas and ash emissions.

A gas and ash plume was seen in webcam images and in visual observation from Observatorio Manizales, 1,600 m above the crater.
Gas and ash emissions were reported by officials from the Parque Nacional Natural los Nevados (PNNN).
Ashfall confirmed near Villahermosa (Tolima), 30 km NE.
Ash and gas emissions were confirmed by seismic signals as well as the webcams on 22 and 27 May.
Low-energy tremors were associated with gas and ash emissions and pulses of low energy.
A small ash plume was confirmed by OVSM webcams and officials at PNNN.
An explosion at 1936 ejected incandescent tephra 50 m above the crater and produced a plume that rose 1 km and drifted W.
An explosion at 1936 ejected incandescent tephra 50 m above the crater and produced a plume that rose 1 km and drifted W.
An ash plume drifted 220 km SW at an altitude of 6.1 km.

Based on information from US Air Force Weather Agency (AFWA), the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume from Soputan rose to an altitude of 9.1 km. The ash cloud dispersed to the W between the summit elevation (1,785 m) and 3.7 km altitude, and to the NNE between 3.7 and 9.1 km altitude.
An eruption included an ash explosion, lava flows, and incandescent material, according to CVGHM.
An eruption included an ash explosion, lava flows, and incandescent material, according to CVGHM.
PVMBG noted that there were 60 shallow volcanic earthquakes.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal alerts were measured every week.
Volcano Discovery reported that the lava dome seemed to be visibly growing from all sides, with almost constant incandescent rockfalls in multiple areas.
Ejecta as large as 6 cm in diameter was deposited up to 3 km from the summit during dome growth.
Ashfall affected the entire island, averaging 2 cm thick in places.
Ash plumes rose to 3.7 km altitude and drifted as far as 37 km NE.
The Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes rose to an altitude of 1.8 km and drifted less than 20 km ENE.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal  alerts were issued each week.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal  alerts were issued each week.
At 1652 an eruption generated an ash plume that rose 2 km.
