An explosion produced an ash plume that rose 4 km and was accompanied by booms and rumbling.
Pyroclastic flows and avalanches were observed.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery, wind data, and pilot reports, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes rose to altitudes of 13.1-13.7 km and drifted 325-590 km SE, S, and SW.
Authorities evacuated by boat all residents from the eight villages on the island.
Pyroclastic flows occurred on the S and SW flanks.

Ashfall was reported up to 1 mm thick in Ende (60 km S on East Nusa Tenggara Island). Thick ashfall was also reported in Ona (SE part of the island) and thin deposits were reported in other areas of the island to the W, N, and E.
Ash plumes at an altitude of 7.6 km were observed.
The Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes rose to altitudes of 2.1-3.7 km and drifted 35-110 km NW, NNW, and N.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery and wind data, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes rose to an altitude of 7 km and drifted 75 km E and NE.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery and wind data, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes rose to altitudes of 2.1-3.7 km and drifted 25-335 km in many directions multiple times each week.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery and wind data, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes rose to an altitude of 2.4 km and drifted over 35 km SE.
A partial lava-dome collapse generated a pyroclastic flow and an ash plume. A volcanologist at the monitoring post for Paluweh noted that the eruption lasted seven minutes.

A partial lava-dome collapse generated a pyroclastic flow that traveled N towards a beach village and killed at least 5 people.  The pyroclastic flow burned trees around the beach and villages. Pyroclastic flows continued to be reported hours after the initial eruption. The ground was hot and covered in 10-20 cm of ash.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery and wind data, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 4.3 km and drifted 130 km W.
The VAAC reported that ash plumes rose to an altitude of 1.8 km and drifted 110-130 km W.
Smaller pyroclastic flows continued to be observed.
Visual observations of occasional eruptive activity were noted until November 2013.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery and wind data analyses, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 4.3 km and drifted less than 40 km NE.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery and wind data, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 8.5 km and drifted 75 km N and 130 km E.
Light ashfall was reported in the evening at a mining camp 80 km NE of the volcano.
Residents in Cold Bay (37 km SW) observed incandescence from the summit during the night.
A narrow plume of steam, ash, and gas, rose up to 6.7 km and drifted southeast.
Trace amounts of ash fell on the community of Sand Point and in Nelson Lagoon, 78 km NNE.

AVO reported that ash emissions began at approximately 1100 on 4 June as observed in satellite images and by pilots. Satellite images showed an ash cloud drifting SE, and pilots estimated that the cloud was at an altitude of 5.8 km. Emissions continued and were accompanied by seismic tremor and explosion signals. On 5 and 6 June an ash plume observed in images drifted 40-45 km W and SW, at altitudes of 4.3-5.5 km based on pilot estimates. During 8-10 June images showed an ash plume drifting 20-53 km SE.
AVO reported that a low-level plume of steam, gas, and ash occasionally rose to an altitude of 6.1 km and drifted NNE.
Small discrete seismic events, likely indicative of small explosions, were measured by pressure sensors.
Emissions were accompanied by seismic tremor and explosion signals.
Emissions were accompanied by seismic tremor and explosion signals. Seismicity decreased during 14-15 June.

Satellite images detected elevated surface temperatures near the vent consistent with lava effusion and fountaining. Elevated surface temperatures consistent with lava effusion persisted until 1620 on 14 June.
Satellite images detected elevated surface temperatures near the vent consistent with lava effusion and fountaining.
AVO reported that ash emissions were intermittent and minor; ash plumes below an altitude of 6.1 km mostly drifted SE.
Seismic tremor amplitude increased slightly, and elevated surface temperatures consistent with lava effusion were detected in satellite images.
Seismic tremor amplitude increased slightly, and elevated surface temperatures consistent with lava effusion were detected in satellite images.
Multiple small small ash plumes rose from the crater.

Seismic tremor and occasional explosions were detected. At 2250 on 24 June seismicity increased and became the strongest seismic activity detected so far during 2013. The seismicity was characterized by continuous intense tremor and frequent small explosions likely associated with lava fountaining and ash production. Seismicity remained high on 25 June. During 25-26 June seismicity declined, and consisted of intermittent bursts of tremor and occasional small explosions.
Seismic tremor and occasional explosions were detected.

At 2250 on 24 June seismicity increased and became the strongest seismic activity detected so far during 2013. The seismicity was characterized by continuous intense tremor and frequent small explosions likely associated with lava fountaining and ash production. Seismicity remained high on 25 June.

At 2250 on 24 June seismicity increased and became the strongest seismic activity detected so far during 2013. The seismicity was characterized by continuous intense tremor and frequent small explosions likely associated with lava fountaining and ash production. Seismicity remained high on 25 June. Satellite images and pilot observations indicated that a plume drifted W at altitudes as high as 8.2-8.5 km. Satellite images showed a plume containing small amounts of ash drifting NW on 26 June. Pilot reports that day indicated that plumes rose to altitudes between 6.1-7.6 km and then to heights just above the summit later that day.
Satellite images detected a strong thermal anomaly at the summit.
Trace amounts of ash fell in King Cove, 48 km SW.

At 2323 a pilot observed ash at an altitude of 3.7 km. Residents in Perryville (32 km SSE) and Port Moller (77 km WSW) also observed ash emissions at about 2330. The first VAAC report around the same time listed the ash plume at 4.3 km altitude, drifting NNE.

Lava effusion from the intracaldera cone resumed on 6 October.  On 17 October AVO noted that seismicity had decreased during the previous week and satellite observations during periods of clear weather showed no evidence of eruptive activity.

Slightly elevated surface temperatures, consistent with cooling lava flows, were detected in partly cloudy satellite images during 9-10 August. During 11-15 August persistent elevated surface temperatures were visible in satellite imagery. Very high surface temperatures were detected in images during 16-17 August. Elevated surface temperatures were detected in satellite data during 19-20 August. During 20-21 August elevated surface temperatures at the cone were observed in satellite data. During 23-26 August satellite data showed weak thermal anomalies at the intracaldera cone. During 27-29 August satellite images detected prominent thermal anomalies at the intracaldera cone. During 4-17 September elevated surface temperatures were detected in satellite data.
Small ash clouds that rose less than 4.6 km were intermittently observed in web-camera images.
Satellite images detected a plume that drifted SW. The web camera showed a light-colored plume rising from the intracaldera cone to just above the caldera rim.
The web camera recorded a small area of incandescence on the intracaldera cone.
Emission of minor amounts of ash and steam were reported.
Occasional small explosions were detected by the seismic network.
The web camera in Perryville (32 km SSE) recorded nighttime incandescence and low-level ash-and-steam plumes.
A pilot reported an ash plume that rose 60-100 m above the cone and drifted almost 25 km S.
A pilot observed an ash emission that rose 300-600 m and drifted NW.
A water-rich plume likely containing minor amounts of ash was detected in satellite images drifting NW at an altitude of 4.5 km.
The web camera in Perryville (32 km SSE) recorded intermittent steam-and-ash plumes; one on 12 August rose 3.7 km and drifted W.
Clear views on from the FAA web-camera in Perryville (32 km SSE) showed minor ash emissions.
Clear web-camera views showed minor ash emissions rising to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifting W and then SSE, just past the caldera rim.
AVO reported that residents of Perryville (32 km SSE) reported hearing loud explosions coming from Veniaminof, and air waves were detected by infrasound equipment in Dillingham (322 km NE).
Trace amounts of ash fell in Perryville.
Minor ash emissions were occasionally observed in web camera views from Perryville.
Lava effusion, fountaining, and nearly continuous small ash plumes continued through the first week in September.
Ash emissions to 4.6-6.1 km were observed. Ash plumes drifted SE.  Lava effusion, fountaining, and nearly continuous small ash plumes continued through the first week in September.
Ash plumes drifted SE and caused ashfall in areas downwind including Perryville (32 km SSE).
A diffuse ash plume was observed rising several hundred feet above the cone and drifting E.
A diffuse steam plume possibly containing ash was recorded by the web cam in Perryville, 32 km SSE.
Residents in Sandy River reported ash bursts. AVO reported an ash plume that rose to 4.6 km and drifted NE.
AVO reported ash plumes that rose to 4.5 km altitude and drifted NW.
Pilots of aircraft PEN241 saw intermittent ash discharges around 1720 UTC that produced plumes that rose up to 4 km altitude and drifted NNE every 2-5 minutes.
Ash deposits on the snow-covered caldera floor, and lava on the cone, were visible in satellite images.
Images of the vent area showed a new cone of accumulated spatter nested within the summit crater of the main cone.
Numerous reports from the Anchorage VAAC confirmed ash plumes rising as high as 4.6 km altitude and drifting up to 20 km NW.
Strombolian explosions of incandescent lava and minor ash emissions were observed at the central active vent during the flyover.
An ash plume reported by the Anchorage VAAC rose to 6.1 km altitude.
Trace amounts of ash were reported in the communities of Chignik Lake and Chignik Lagoon, 40-55 km E of the active vent.
Deposits about 1 mm thick covered the Nalychevo Valley bordering the S of the massif.
At 1134 an ash plume rose 3 km and drifted 20 km NE.
A phreatic eruption from Tompaluan crater, in the saddle between the Lokon-Empung peaks, produced an ash plume that rose 400 m above the crater rim and drifted SE.
A phreatic eruption from Tompaluan crater, in the saddle between the Lokon-Empung peaks, produced an ash plume that rose 400 m above the crater rim and drifted SE.
Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (IVS FEB RAS) scientists inspected the summit and found ~10 cm deep ash covered the crater area (figure 3).
KVERT stated pilots and ground crew at Elizovo airport observed a gas-and-steam plume that may have contained ash. The plume rose to 1.5 km and drifted E.
EO-1 satellite's Advanced Land Imager (ALI) captured an ash plume emitted from Zhupanovsky (figure 4, BGVN 39:09).
A phreatic eruption ejected material that fell around the crater.
Gray ash plumes rose 100-500 m above the crater.
The Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes detected in satellite imagery rose to an altitude of 1.5 km and drifted NW.
Three eruptions from Tompaluan crater, in the saddle between the Lokon-Empung peaks, ejected lava and ash, and caused forest fires on the W flank.
Three eruptions from Tompaluan crater, in the saddle between the Lokon-Empung peaks, ejected lava and ash, and caused forest fires on the W flank.

Three eruptions from Tompaluan crater, in the saddle between the Lokon-Empung peaks, ejected lava and ash, and caused forest fires on the W flank. HOPE Worldwide, a non-profit non-governmental organization, issued a report stating that at 2331 on the 14 July Lokon erupted and sent lava, ash, and gases 1.5 km over the summit. "No death is yet to be reported due to the eruption, but there are 4,412 persons displaced in the Tomohon city, just south of Manado city, the capital of North Sulawesi Province." Displaced residents went to schools and a city park.
Explosions produced ash plumes that rose 0.6-3.5 km above the crater.
Explosions produced ash plumes that rose 0.6-3.5 km above the crater.
Lokon erupted 12 times on 28 August. One explosion on 29 August ejected material 250 m above the crater.
CVGHM reported that white and gray plumes rose 100-300 m above Tompaluan crater.
The Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 2.1 km.

According to a news article, a gray plume rose 1.2 km above Tompaluan crater, in the saddle between the Lokon-Empung peaks, and drifted SW. A second eruption produced a plume that rose 500 m above the crater.
According to a news article, an explosion sent incandescent material as far as 800 m away from Tompaluan crater.
Event was "Partial collapse at end of eruption"
Event was "Partial collapse at end of eruption"
Lava fountaining at the summit was observed and photographed.
Based on SIGMET notices, the Buenos Aires VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to altitudes of 3-4.3 km and drifted SE.
On 31 August 2011, OVSICORI-UNA reported that since mid-July incandescence was visible during the day on the lava dome of Po s, which had not occurred since 1981.

OVDAS-SERNAGEOMIN reported that between 2000 on 2 June and 1959 on 3 June about 1,450 earthquakes were detected, or an average of about 60 earthquakes per hour. The earthquakes were mostly hybrid and long-period, and located in the SE sector of the Cord¢n Caulle rift zone at depths of 2-5 km. Area residents reported feeling earthquakes during the evening of 3 June through the morning of 4 June. For a six-hour period on 4 June, seismicity increased to an average of 230 earthquakes per hour, at depths of 1-4 km. About 12 events were magnitudes greater than 4, and 50 events were magnitudes greater than 3.
An explosion from Cord¢n Caulle produced a 5-km-wide ash-and-gas plume that rose to an altitude of 12.2 km as noted by OVDAS scientists.

An explosion from Cord¢n Caulle produced a 5-km-wide ash-and-gas plume that rose to an altitude of 12.2 km as noted by OVDAS scientists. The plume drifted S at 5 km altitude, and W and E at 10 km altitude. The Buenos Aires VAAC reported that ash plumes rose to altitudes of 10.7-13.7 km and drifted 870 km ESE.
At least five pyroclastic flows were generated from partial collapses of the eruptive column and traveled N in the Nilahue River drainage. The pyroclastic flows were possibly 10 km long.
ONEMI reported the continuation of evacuations that had begun the previous day and increased the potential number of evacuees to 3,000.

Scientists observed a viscous lava flow with concentric morphology, confirming speculation of magma ascent reflected in seismic data from the previous few days. A 50-m-wide lava flow from the emissions center had traveled 200 m NW and 100 m NE, filling up a depression. Pulses of high-intensity tremor indicated that the lava flow remained active.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone rose to an altitude of 3 km and drifted more than 53 km NW.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone rose to an altitude of 3 km and drifted more than 53 km NW.
RVO reported that roaring and rumbling noises from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone began at 2128 and lasted for about 15 minutes.
Small discrete explosions generated ash clouds that rose up to 500 m above the crater and drifted E and SE.
Small discrete explosions generated ash clouds that rose up to 500 m above the crater and drifted E and SE.

A well-documented event ejected sediment that covered sections of the upper N walls. Some of the material was washed down the flanks and caused changes in water quality along the main creeks and major rivers up to 18 km away from the source.
OVSICORI-UNA reported that seismic data revealed two eruptions.
A small explosion detected by the seismic network produced an ash emission that was observed with a camera installed in La Piranha (NW).
According to news reports, communities around the volcano evacuated, and airports in Manizales, Pereira, and Armenia closed.
The Washington VAAC reported that emissions of gas and light ash were possibly detected in satellite imagery drifting 35 km WNW.
A sudden ash explosion was reported by Chinandega Civil Defense at 1900.
INETER reported that three explosions produced ash-and-gas plumes that rose 1.5 km above the crater and drifted 9 km/hr NW.

INETER reported that three explosions produced ash-and-gas plumes that rose 1.5 km above the crater and drifted 9 km/hr NW. Sporadic explosions later that day generated ash plumes that rose 1.5-5 km and drifted 50 km WNW.
Incandescent rocks fell in areas NW, causing burns on livestock.
According to a news article, officials evacuated about 3,000 people.
A series of explosions starting at 2000 produced ash-and-gas plumes that rose 500 m above the crater and drifted SW and likely W.
A series of explosions starting at 2000 produced ash-and-gas plumes that rose 500 m above the crater and drifted SW and likely W.

INETER reported that seven explosions  ejected gas and ash, and were detected by the seismic station located on the W flank. The explosions occurred at 0615, 0645, 0653, 0911, 1137, 1139, and 1143, and were also observed by civil defense and INETER staff. The largest explosion, at 1139, generated a plume that rose 100 m.
INETER reported that seven explosions  ejected gas and ash, and were detected by the seismic station located on the W flank. The largest explosion, at 1139, generated a plume that rose 100 m.
According to news articles an eruption at 0245 produced an ash plume and ashfall.

About 3,000 people initially evacuated from areas within a 3-km radius of the volcano. According to a news article, about 6,000 people that had evacuated after the 15 September eruption started to return home on 22 September.
CVGHM reported that a three-hour long ash eruption from Sirung was accompanied by loud sounds and incandescence that reached 10 m above the crater.
An ash plume rose 3.5 km above the crater and drifted N, producing ashfall up to 4 mm thick near the crater.
A CVGHM volcanologist reported that a Strombolian eruption produced an ash plume that rose 6 km and drifted W.
CVGHM reported that an explosion of incandescent material was followed by a 6-km-high ash plume and a pyroclastic flow that traveled as far as 4 km W.
A CVGHM volcanologist reported that a Strombolian eruption produced an ash plume that rose 6 km and drifted W. Ashfall impacted villages, trees, and vegetation downwind.
An early morning photograph captured an eruption showing a small plume and lava flows down the flank of Soputan.

A gray-and-white eruption plume rose 1 km above the crater. Throughout the day, two more similar plumes rose 1.3 km above the crater. Based on analysis of satellite imagery, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume drifted more than 100 km W.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
According to NASA's Earth Observatory, a satellite image showed a small volcanic plume rising from Soputan.
Seismicity increased during 8-22 August; on 23 August volcanic earthquakes and avalanches significantly increased.
An explosion at 1936 ejected incandescent tephra 50 m above the crater and produced a plume that rose 1 km and drifted W.

Based on information from CVGHM, NOAA, and analysis of satellite imagery, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 12.1 km and drifted 150 km W. The eruption lasted four hours. Later, a plume detected in satellite imagery rose to an altitude of 6.1 km.
Thermally anomalous pixels were recorded by the MODVOLC thermal alert system from 18 to 20 September, followed by a two-pixel anomaly on 22 September and a single-pixel anomaly on 27 September.
CVGHM reported that tremor increased and diffuse ash emissions rose from Ratu Crater.
CVGHM reported that phreatic eruptions from Ratu Crater occurred on 28 February and during 4-6 March, and generated ash plumes that rose up to 100 m above the crater.
Deflation was detected from 24 February through early March, but was then stable during 7-14 March.
CVGHM reported that tremor increased and diffuse ash emissions rose from Ratu Crater.
At approximately 2310 a series of explosions were detected by the seismic network and were accompanied by ash and gas emissions.
At approximately 2310 a series of explosions were detected by the seismic network and were accompanied by ash and gas emissions.
Sailors who went to the crater rim observed a small active vent at the bottom of the Lofia crater. Ledges were also draped with ash.

Swiss adventurer Xavier Rosset posted an audio dialog on 13 March 2009 referring to his visit the preceding week, although the exact date of observation was unclear. The crater was 80-100 m deep and the same in diameter. Three openings of undetermined size displayed an orange glow. Lava ejections from these vents rose 10-50 m high accompanied by loud noises. Rosset's 27 March dialog discusses a strong earthquake in the region on 20 March, which caused several rockfalls on the island. He visited the volcano in the afternoon and, looking into the active crater, saw few noticeable changes.

Nicole Keller: "The only fumaroles were located inside Lofia crater. Every few minutes there was a rumbling, and every now and again (1-2/hour) there was a bigger explosion ejecting juvenile scoria over the crater rim."
Richard Crowley visited and reported seeing lava bubbling in a crater vent.

KVERT reported that episodes of volcanic tremor were detected in the area of Plosky Tolbachik during 7-10, 18, and 26 November. The number of shallow volcanic earthquakes increased to 250 on 26 November. A strong event occurred at 1652 on 27 November.
Observers from Kozyrevsk (40 km NW) and Lazo (50 km SW) villages reported ash explosions and lava flows at Tolbachinsky Dol, in the same area as the 1975 eruption (northern vents).

Observers from Kozyrevsk (40 km NW) and Lazo (50 km SW) villages reported lava flows at Tolbachinsky Dol, in the same area as the 1975 eruption (northern vents). Lava effused from two fissures along the W side of Tolbachinsky Dol, a lava plateau on the SW side of the volcano. According to a news article on 30 November, the lava flows destroyed two scientific base camps 10 km away. Lava had flowed 17-20 km away from the S fissure by 7 December. KVERT reported that the S fissure along the W side of Tolbachinsky Dol continued to produce very fluid lava flows that traveled 17-20 km. The flows traveled to the W, S, and E sides of Tolbachinsky Dol.
Ashfall, 4 cm thick, was reported in Krasny Yar (60 km NNW).
Tens of MODVOLC thermal alerts issued virtually every day during the period until stopping abruptly at the end of August 2013.

Lava effused from two fissures along the W side of Tolbachinsky Dol, a lava plateau on the SW side of the volcano. KVERT reported that the N and S fissures were located 4-5 km and 6-7 km S of Plosky Tolbachik, respectively.

At least two were observed initially, and five were present by 17 December; the fifth cone continued to grow through 18 January. From 18 January - 22 February 2013 four cinder cones continued to grow on the S fissure above Krasny cone. Cinder cones continued to grow on the fissure through the end of the eruption.
Edwards and others (2013) noted that at the vent molten lava bombs shot more than 100 m above the crater floor.
Strombolian activity and lava effusion from two fissures continued.
At about 2350 a short-lived (~1-2 minutes) phreatic eruption occurred at the Te Mari craters area, followed by a series of discrete small earthquakes over the next few tens of minutes.

A sequence of small volcanic earthquakes beneath Tongariro was detected by a few of the seismometers in the permanent network. Earthquakes with magnitudes less than 2.5 were clustered between Emerald Crater (E of the summit) and the Te Mari craters (2 km E east of Ketetahi hot springs on the N flank) at 2-7 km depth. The sequence started on 13 July, soon declined, and then again increased during 18-20 July.

Approximately one hour after the eruption, the Cooperative Institute for Meteorological Satellite Studies (CIMSS) observed in satellite imagery that an ash plume was drifting more than 50 km E from Tongariro.
According to a news article, a GNS Science volcanologist noted that there were reports of "red hot rocks being thrown out of the crater", explosions, and lighting.

Blocks of old and hydrothermally altered lava, as large as 1 m in diameter, ejected by the eruption fell 1.5-2 km from the Te Mari craters area. Falling blocks formed impact craters in the ground in an extensive area to the E and W of the new vents. Most blocks were covered by grey ash but many on the W slopes were not, suggesting that they were ejected after the main ash-producing phase of the eruption.

A small eruption at Tongariro's Te Maari Craters occurred at 1325, without precursory events. The eruption occurred in the same area as the previous eruption on 6 August and lasted less than five minutes, although local seismic activity lasted about 15 minutes. GNS staff and hikers saw the eruption.
An ash plume rose 3-4 km above the Upper Te Maari crater and produced ashfall across part of State Highway 46 and NE towards Turangi (21 km NE).
Two small pyroclastic density currents were produced at the base of the ash column, to the W and N of the crater, and traveled a limited distance of a few hundred meters downslope.

During a visit to the volcano OVSICORI-UNA found that a 2- to 5-cm-thick layer of freshly ejected material, with clasts ranging in size from a few millimeters to 5 cm, blanketed the W edge of the crater.
OVSICORI closed the Turrialba Volcano National Park temporarily and evacuated a few people as a precaution.
Residents reported a dark plume from La Quemada and a white vapor plume that rose from the fumarolic vent formed in the main crater on 5 January 2010.
An ash plume rose 500 m above the crater and drifted NNE and NNW, rising to an altitude of 4 km.
During the evening scientists observed gas emissions and ejection of tephra from the vent.
OVSICORI-UNA reported that an eruption from Turrialba's West Crater on 21 May was preceded by seismic activity characterized by more than 150 volcanic earthquakes per day since 18 April.
Eruptions from West Crater occurred at 0830 and after 1100 from vents which opened in January 2010 (Boca 2010, on the W wall) and January 2012 (Boca 2012, on the E wall).
The eruptions generated ash plumes that rose more than 500 m. At around 1200 ash emissions ceased and seismicity decreased.
Slight ashfall was reported in Pacayas and San Pablo in Oreamuno de Cartago (25 km SW).
The Buenos Aires VAAC reported that, although a pilot reported an ash plume from Ubinas rising to an altitude of 5.5 km and drifting W, there was no ash detected in clear satellite images.
IGP reported nine phreatic explosions from Ubinas.
IGP reported nine phreatic explosions. Most of the explosions generated ash plumes that rose 1.5-2 km above the crater.
RVO reported that during 7-9 May gray-brown ash plumes rose from the crater.
RVO reported that starting on 6 November through 30 November Ulawun produced pale grey and brown ash plumes that rose 200 m and drifted in multiple directions.

Emissions from the summit crater consisted of white vapor during 1-7 July 2013, and then changed to occasionally sub-continuous, light gray ash clouds during 8 and 11-14 July. Ash clouds changed to gray-brown on 14 July. Emissions from the summit crater were light gray during 15-16 July, and then changed to white vapor during 17-21 July.

Elevated surface temperatures were detected in satellite images at 0525, likely indicating an intra-caldera eruption on 13 June. During 15-18 June satellite images showed very high elevated surface temperatures at the intra-caldera cinder cone consistent with continued lava effusion. Most days satellite images showed highly elevated surface temperatures at the cinder cone inside the caldera consistent with lava effusion.

On 8 June AVO reported that gradually increasing seismic tremor at Veniaminof had been detected during the previous two days. During 8-10 June seismicity continued to increase and a persistent steam plume rose from the central cone within the caldera. Although seismic activity decreased during 31 July-2 August, it still remained above background levels through 11 August and then increased again until 21 August. Intense seismicity was recorded on 30 August. Elevated and continuous tremor persisted during 31 August-10 September. Low-level seismic tremor continued through 24 September.
Seismic tremor was indicative of low-level effusive activity and small explosions.

Seismic tremor was indicative of low-level effusive activity and small explosions beginning 13 June. At 2323 a pilot observed a lava flow effusing from the intra-caldera cinder cone. The 100-m-wide lava flow extended 500 m down the SW flank of the cone onto the adjacent snow and ice field by 18 June. Through the end of July satellite images showed high elevated surface temperatures at the intra-caldera cinder cone consistent with continued lava effusion. Satellite images during 3-16 July showed that most of the lava flows traveled S of the cone a few hundred meters. On 25 July a pilot reported a "river of lava" flowing down from the cone. During a helicopter overflight on 19 August geologists observed two active lava flows from the cone, and lava flowing passively over ice at the foot of the cone.  Episodic tremor bursts on 27-29 August  were likely associated with lava effusion. Elevated surface temperatures detected in satellite images that were consistent with lava effusion and fountaining continued through 17 September.

According to Projecto Observaci¢n Visual Volc n Villarrica (POVI), satellite images of Villarrica acquired on 25 July revealed a weak thermal anomaly. On 29 July observers photographed the crater and described a thermal anomaly on the S edge of the crater rim.
A photograph showed a diffuse gas plume rising from the bottom of the crater, and ash and lapilli on the snow on the inner crater walls.
The color of the plume rising from the lake changed from white to light brown, indicating more ash in the plume.
GeoNet volcanologists described a 40-50-m-wide tuff cone forming around the vent and isolating the vent from the lake water.

On 12 December the GeoNet Data Centre posted a report describing a new lava dome at White Island that volcanologists recently noticed. The spiny lava dome was 20-30 m in diameter and grew in a crater formed during an eruption beginning 5 August 2012. A prominent steam plume rose from the dome. Comments from tour operators at White Island suggested that the dome may have been visible two weeks earlier, but not as clearly as on 10 December. On 20 December, GeoNet Data Centre reported that the spiny lava dome at White Island had not changed during the previous 10 days.
A particularly strong period of volcanic tremor was recorded during 4-5 August, and ended with an earthquake at 0454.
GeoNet Data Centre reported that White Island's "hot lake" had dried up and a small tuff cone was forming on the former floor of the lake.
GeoNet Data Centre reported a small ash cone surrounded by a small moat of water built in the crater that formerly contained the hot lake.
The GeoNet Data Centre reported that a small eruption from White Island occurred at 1023 on 20 August and continued for about 10 minutes.

Imagery acquired from the Advanced Land Imager (ALI) on NASA's EO-1 satellite showed a new island with a plume rising from it, roughly 500 m N of Rugged Island and more than 500 m in diameter. A satellite image acquired on 7 January showed that the island had grown to about 530 x 710 m, and a gas-and-steam plume containing ash rose from a distinct cone.
Moderate Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer (MODIS) images of the area first revealed a plume.
MODIS imagery from NASA's satellites showed a plume, possibly containing ash, rising from what was thought to be a submarine eruption.
A MODVOLC thermal anomaly was recorded.

Sezione di Catania - Osservatorio Etneo reported that a series of small and sporadic ash emissions from Etna's New Southeast Crater (NSEC) began during the morning of 3 September 2013. At daybreak on 6 September small ash puffs were emitted once or twice per hour.

Sezione di Catania - Osservatorio Etneo reported that Etna's New Southeast Crater (NSEC) produced a new episode of lava fountaining. Lava fountaining from NSEC continued through the late morning and was then followed by a long series of powerful explosions audible to many tens of kilometers away.
Lava extrusions built a small dome in the crater.
The explosion, ash plume and pyroclastic flows killed 35 people.
Event was "Partial collapse at end of eruption"

Intermittent ash emission gradually turned into Strombolian activity. After 1413 the activity intensified; small ash puffs were produced and Strombolian explosions ejected incandescent pyroclastics onto the flanks of the cone. During the night explosive activity continued to intensify, and by 0330 on 15 December Strombolian activity was intense and virtually continuous. After 0500 explosive activity started to diminish, and at 0550 the volcanic tremor amplitude and the intensity and frequency of Strombolian explosions showed a sharp drop.

At 2323 lava overflowed the SE crater rim and flowed towards the Valle del Bove. At 0610 and 0633 the next day two vents opened within the deep trench cutting the SE flank of the NSEC cone (where lava was still flowing from the crater since the previous evening), the first just a few tens of meters below the crater rim, the second about 100 m further downslope. Both vents initially produced lava fountains for a few minutes, with jets a few tens of meters high, and then produced lava flows that descended through the trench. At night during 15-16 December lava flows continued to flow towards the Valle del Bove. Lava effusion gradually diminished, but at about 1430 on 16 December, a short fissure opened on the lower NE flank of the NSEC cone, producing a small lava flow which advanced a few hundred meters. Very slow lava effusion continued, at a gradually decreasing rate, from the fissure on the NE flank of the NSEC cone, through the night of 17-18 December.

At 0610 and 0633 two vents opened within the deep trench cutting the SE flank of the NSEC cone (where lava was still flowing from the crater since the previous evening), the first just a few tens of meters below the crater rim, the second about 100 m further downslope. Both vents initially produced lava fountains for a few minutes, with jets a few tens of meters high, and then produced lava flows that descended through the trench. During the afternoon and evening of 15 December explosive activity lasted a few to a few tens of minutes and Strombolian activity became significantly more intense or passed into pulsating, low lava fountains.

Between 0945 on 15 December and the morning of 16 December ash emission varied in frequency and intensity, related to variations in the intensity of the Strombolian activity at NSEC. Strombolian activity at NSEC continued through 16 December at a slowly decreasing rate and with numerous minor intensifications that generated diluted ash plumes. Explosive activity finally ceased around midnight on 17 December.

The more intense explosive periods produced greater amounts of ash leading to ashfall in populated areas on the E and SE flank, from the Milo-Zafferana area toward the Ionian coast. At night during 15-16 December a shift in wind direction caused ashfall in areas SE, S, and SW.

Between 0945 on 15 December and the morning of 16 December ash emission varied in frequency and intensity, related to variations in the intensity of the Strombolian activity. During the afternoon and evening of 15 December explosive activity lasted a few to a few tens of minutes and Strombolian activity became significantly more intense or passed into pulsating, low lava fountains. Strombolian activity at the NSEC continued through 16 December at a slowly decreasing rate and with numerous minor intensifications that generated diluted ash plumes. Explosive activity finally ceased around midnight on 17 December.
Forty-seven MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
Small and periodic ash emissions occurred from Northeast Crater.
Small thermal anomalies were detected with a thermal camera.

During the early morning hours on 29 December a camera recorded weak and sporadic incandescence from NSEC.  At 1115 NSEC produced a single Strombolian explosion, accompanied by an ash plume that rose 1 km and drifted E. After the explosion mild Strombolian activity continued and then progressively intensified in the evening.

At 1115 NSEC produced a single Strombolian explosion, accompanied by an ash plume that rose 1 km and drifted E. Frequent powerful explosions from two vents located within the crater were audible in a vast sector around the volcano.

At 1115 NSEC produced a single Strombolian explosion, accompanied by an ash plume that rose 1 km and drifted E. After the explosion mild Strombolian activity continued and then progressively intensified in the evening. Diffuse ash plumes drifted NE.
Frequent powerful explosions from two vents located within the crater were audible in a vast sector around the volcano.

INGV reported that two lava flows were active, one from a vent on the E flank of the NSEC cone, and the second, fed directly from the crater, traveled down the NE flank of the cone.  During 31 December 2013-1 January 2014 lava flows from a vent located on the NE flank of the cone of Etna's New Southeast Crater (NSEC) continued to travel towards the N part of the Valle de Bove; the lava flows had been active since activity resumed on 29 December. On 3 January staff doing field work noted that the effusive activity had stopped.
Strong pulsating degassing occurred at Northeast Crater.
INGV reported that during 4-13 January nearly continuous emissions of reddish ash from Etna's Northeast Crater were visible. Strong degassing continued at least through 22 January.
At 0255 incandescence from the crater was observed.
According to news articles an eruption at 0245 produced an ash plume and ashfall in Sukameriah (50 km NE), Kutarayat, Kutagugung (16 km SW), and Berastagi (14 km E).

An eruption at 1203 on 17 September ejected tephra and a dense ash plume that rose higher than the plume from 15 September. According to the Darwin VAAC, a pilot observed an ash plume that rose to an altitude of 6.1 km and drifted 55 km SE. On 18 September a low-level ash plume rose to an altitude of 3 km and drifted SE.
According to a news article, the volcano was continuing to emit ash.
Plumes were grayish and rose 250 m.

Fog prevented observations for a period after the explosions; once the fog cleared dense gray plumes were observed. On 24 October an explosion at 0550 generated an ash plume that rose 3 km and caused ashfall in areas S.
An explosion at 0550 generated an ash plume that rose 3 km and caused ashfall in areas S.

Based on information from the Indonesian Meteorological Office, the Darwin VAAC reported that an eruption at 1737 on 26 October generated an ash plume that rose to an altitude of 4.9 km. At 0700 and 1200 on 27 October a webcam showed an ash plume rising to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifting over 35 km NE.
Ash plumes rose 200-2,000 m above the summit.
Ashfall was noted on the SE flank up to 1 km from the summit.

An eruption began at 0126 that generated ash plumes up to 7 km altitude and triggered evacuations from communities within 3 km of the volcano (approximately 1,681 residents); the ash plume drifted W. A second eruption occurred in the afternoon.
Rumbling sounds that lasted up to 10 minutes long were noted by staff at the Sinabung Observation Post (~8.5 km from the volcano).
PVMBG reported that an eruption occurred at 1423. This event lasted for 20 minutes and generated an ash plume up to 3,000 m above the crater that drifted SW.
Rumbling sounds were noted by staff at the observation post.
Pyroclastic flows were observed at 1431; the flows extended 1 km down the SE flank.

Based on information from the Jakarta Meteorological Watch Office, webcam data, wind data, and satellite images, the Darwin VAAC reported that on 6 November an ash plume from Sinabung rose to an altitude of 3 km. The next day an ash plume rose to the same altitude. According to webcam views an eruption on 8 November produced a low-level ash plume.

The Jakarta Meteorological Watch Office, the webcam, and satellite data detecting sulfur dioxide indicated two explosions. The first one, at 0720, generated an ash plume that rose to an altitude of 3.7 km. The altitude of the second plume, from an explosion at 1600, was unknown.

The Jakarta Meteorological Watch Office, the webcam, and satellite data detecting sulfur dioxide indicated two explosions on 10 November. The first one, at 0720, generated an ash plume that rose to an altitude of 3.7 km. The altitude of the second plume, from an explosion at 1600, was unknown. An ash plume on 11 November rose to an altitude of 3 km and drifted less than 20 km SW. The next day an ash plume rose to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifted almost 40 km NW.
Based on webcam data and satellite images, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume from Sinabung rose to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifted almost 150 km NW and W.
An explosion observed with the webcam produced an ash plume that rose to an altitude of 7.6 km.

An explosion observed with the webcam on 18 November produced an ash plume that rose to an altitude of 7.6 km. About 30 minutes later an ash plume also visible in satellite images rose to an altitude of 11.3 km and drifted 65 km W. Four hours later satellite images showed ash plumes at an altitude of 9.1 km to the W of Sinabung and at an altitude of 4.6 km over the crater. On 19 November the webcam recorded an ash plume that rose to an altitude of 4.6 km over the crater. A news article stated that later that night that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 10 km.

PVMBG reported three explosions. The first, at 2024, generated an ash plume that rose 500 m and drifted SW, and a pyroclastic flow that traveled 500 m down the SE flank. At 2152 a dense ash plume from an explosion rose 500 m and drifted SW. Incandescent material was ejected 50 m away from the crater. At 2252 an ash plume rose 1 km and drifted SW.

PVMBG reported three explosions. The first explosion, at 2024, generated an ash plume that rose 500 m and drifted SW, and a pyroclastic flow that traveled 500 m down the SE flank. At 2152 a dense ash plume from an explosion rose 500 m and drifted SW. Incandescent material was ejected 50 m away from the crater. At 2252 an ash plume rose 1 km and drifted SW.
PVMBG reported three explosions. The first explosion, at 2024, generated an ash plume that rose 500 m and drifted SW, and a pyroclastic flow that traveled 500 m down the SE flank.

PVMBG reported three explosions. The first explosion, at 2024, generated an ash plume and a pyroclastic flow. At 2152 a dense ash plume from an explosion rose 500 m and drifted SW and incandescent material was ejected 50 m away from the crater.
At 0704 an explosion generated an ash plume that rose 8 km and drifted SW. A pyroclastic flow also traveled 800 m down the SE flank.
At 2155 a dense ash plume rose 10 km, drifted SW, and exhibited lightning.
Multiple explosions at 0240, 0405, 0529, 0619, and 0641 generated ash plumes that rose to heights between 1 and 3.5 km.
Scoria fell in the Sigarang-garang and Desa Kuta villages in the NNE.
Two explosions, at 0043 and 0232, were detected but not visually observed.
Ash plumes rose 8 km and drifted NNE at 0727, rose 1 km at 0812, and rose 3 km at 0855.
Badan Nacional Penanggulangan Bencana (BNPB) reported that 17,713 people, out of the 20,270 residents living within 5 km, had been evacuated to 31 shelters.
News reported that six new eruptive events sent "lava and searing gas" up to 1.5 km down the slopes, causing villagers to evacuate.
Volcanic material erupted as high as 2 km above the crater.
Based on webcam data and wind data, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes from Sinabung rose to altitudes of 3-5.5 km. Ash plumes drifted 150 km W on 30 November.
Based on webcam data, wind data, satellite image analysis, and PVMBG, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes from Sinabung rose to altitudes of 3-5.5 km and drifted 55 km W.
Dense grayish-to-white plumes rose 70-200 m on 9 December. On 10 December an ash plume rose to an altitude of 5.5 km and drifted 75 km NW.
Based on webcam images, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plume rose up to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifted as far as 55 km W.

A lava dome in the North Crater, visible on 24 December, was 56 m high and 210 m wide. On 26 December the lava-dome volume was estimated to be over 1 million cubic meters, with a growth rate of 3.5 cubic meters per second.
Plumes were white and gray, and rose 300-400 m above the crater.
Badan Nacional Penanggulangan Bencana (BNPB) reported that the number of displaced people reached 19,126 (5, 979 families).
Collapsing parts of the lava dome generated block-and-ash flows as well as pyroclastic flows which traveled as far as 3.5 km down the SE flank.
Explosions and pyroclastic flows generated ash plumes that rose at least 6 km above the crater.
Explosions and pyroclastic flows generated ash plumes that rose at least 6 km above the crater.
Badan Nacional Penanggulangan Bencana (BNPB) reported that ash plumes rose as high as 7 km above the lava dome.
Badan Nacional Penanggulangan Bencana (BNPB) reported that pyroclastic flows traveled as far as 3.5 km SE.
Badan Nacional Penanggulangan Bencana (BNPB) reported that incandescent avalanches traveled 1.5 km SE.

The lava dome continued to grow and collapse. On 5 January the number of hybrid earthquakes increased, indicating a growing lava dome. Seismicity remained high, with constant tremor and hybrid earthquakes indicating a growing lava dome.

Pyroclastic flows occurred 172 times on 3 January and traveled 2-4 km SE. On 4 January pyroclastic flows were larger and more frequent. They continued to travel up to 5 km SE as well as 3.5 km SSE. On 5 January pyroclastic flows traveled 1.5-4.5 km SE. During 4-5 January pyroclastic flows were recorded 426 times. During 7-17 January pyroclastic flows continued to travel 0.5-4.5 km SE.
Brownish white or gray and white ash plumes rose 1-6 km and drifted SW.
Two villages located 6.5 km SE, Jerawa and Desa Pintu Besi, were evacuated on 3 January. The number of refugees reached 22,145 by 7 January.
Small explosions were detected from the crater that released gas and ash. There were four explosions during 0725-1605; the largest occurred at 0725 and generated a plume 50 m above the crater rim.
A field survey team observed strong degassing from the crater. The main source of the gas was the SW wall and jetting sounds were also noted.
Six earthquakes with magnitudes less than 4 were detected to the east of the Zubair islands two days before the eruption was noticed.
Optical imagery that showed the eruption was reported by Xu et al. (2015) until 20 November 2013.
Plumes from the pyroclastic flows rose 1.2 km.

The number of seismic signals indicating pyroclastic flows increased from the previous day. Pyroclastic flows traveled 5 km.
An explosion was heard and ash plumes rose 6 km and drifted W.
Ash plumes rose to an altitude of 4.5 km and drifted NE.
CVGHM noted a reduction in intensity of activity from Merapi; one pyroclastic flow occurred in a 6-hour period.
Rumbling sounds were accompanied by an ash plume that rose to an altitude of 4.5 km.
Plumes generally rose 800 m above the crater, but at about 2200 a brownish plume rose to a height of 1.5 km.
A 3.5-km-long pyroclastic flow and a 200-m-long avalanche both traveled S in the Gendol drainage.
Roaring was followed by light ashfall at the Ketep observation post.
Plumes, brownish-black at times, rose 800 m above the crater and drifted W and NW. A brownish plume rose 1.5 km above the crater.
One pyroclastic flow was observed through the CCTV traveling 3 km S.
Based on analysis of satellite imagery, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes drifted 185-280 km SW at an altitude of 7.6 km.
In the latter part of 14 November and during 15-16 November, ash plumes rose to altitude of 6.1-7.6 km and drifted 110-130 km S, SW, and W.
During 14-15 November, news articles stated that the death toll from the eruption was over 250.
About 390,000 residents began to return home after the "danger zones" were reduced in some areas due to decreased activity during the previous few days.
A gas-and-ash plume was observed rising 1.5 km above the crater and drifting SW.
A pyroclastic flow occurred with low intensity.
Lahar deposits were seen in multiple drainages around Merapi at a maximum distance of 16.5 km from the summit.

One pyroclastic flow was detected and five were recorded the next day.
The death toll from the eruption reached 322.
More than 130,000 people continued to live in temporary shelters.
CVGHM reported that avalanches on Merapi's flanks were detected by the seismic network.
According to news articles, a lahar in the Code River that runs through Yogyakarta, 30 km SSW, flooded streets and damaged bridges, and caused about 1,000 residents to evacuate.
A narrow tongue of lava was observed, and light-colored flow deposits extended S down several narrow channels (Gendol and Kuning drainages) at least 5 km from the summit.
According to news articles, a lahar in the Code River that runs through Yogyakarta, 30 km SSW, flooded streets and damaged bridges, and caused about 1,000 residents to evacuate.
Avalanches descended the Krasak drainage, traveling 1.5 km SW.

According to the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID) (quoting the Government of Indonesia's National Disaster Management Agency-Badan Nasional Penanggulangan Bencana or BNPB), the 2010 eruptions killed 386 people, injured 131 people, and displaced initially more than 300,000 residents (USAID, 2011).
A bright glow on the crater's E side was recorded on closed circuit television (CCTV).

The major highway between Magelang and Yogyakarta was cut off when a 60 m wide section of blacktop was torn away by torrential mudflows along the eroded banks of the Putih river. As a result, hundreds of homes within 12 different villages near the river were inundated forcing 5,000 people to flee. There were three fatalities.

Over the past weeks, the vent fed several active lava flow fronts that enlarged the land in more or less all directions. In particular, there were two active flows relatively close to the vent which had been traveling E and formed a small, almost closed bay with green-orange discolored water inside.

According to Pfeiffer (2014), the island continued growing with lava flows traveling in several directions. Its highest peak, formed by the most western of the two active vents, was measured at 66 m. The new additions more than doubled the size of the island by 16 February.

In a 24 January bulletin, the Unidad Estatal de Protecci¢n Civil reported that lava flows were active on the W and WNW flanks. In a 17 February bulletin, the Unidad Estatal de Protecci¢n Civil reported that lava flows on the SW and WNW flanks minimally advanced.

Based on webcam views and satellite images, the Washington VAAC reported that a brief emission with low ash content drifted 30 km SW. The next day a few brief emissions rose from the crater and dissipated about 37 km SW.

Based on satellite images, Mexico City MWO, METAR and Colima Tower notices, pilot observations, and a webcam, the Washington VAAC reported that multiple gas-and-ash plumes per day rose to altitudes of 5.5-7.3 km and drifted in multiple directions. Ash drifted as far as 350 km SE on 19 February.

Based on satellite images, Mexico City MWO, and a webcam, the Washington VAAC reported that multiple gas-and-ash plumes per day rose to altitudes of 5.2-7.6 km and drifted in multiple directions. Ash drifted as far as 370 km SE on 28 February.

Based on satellite images and wind models, the Washington VAAC reported that on 4 March an ash plume rose to an altitude of 5.2 km and drifted 65 km NE and ENE. The webcam recorded an ash plume rising from the crater and drifting NE later that day. On 5 March the webcam recorded an ash plume that rose to an altitude of 7.6 km and drifted NNE. Gas emissions with some possible ash continued to be recorded. An explosion at 1546 on 6 March generated an ash plume that rose to an altitude of 7.6 km and drifted NNE. Satellite images detected a plume drifting almost 65 km E at an altitude of 6.1 km. The webcam recorded continuing ash puffs on 7 March drifting NW. A wide ash plume rose to an altitude of 7 km and fanned out N and NE. On 9 March the Mexico City MWO reported an ash plume that rose to an altitude of 6.1 km and drifted NE. Webcam views indicated that the emission rose higher. Multiple ash emissions were detected later that day, and one was detected on 10 March.

Based on satellite images, Mexico City MWO, Colima Tower notices, and a webcam, the Washington VAAC reported ash plumes during 11-13 March. On 12 March an ash cloud observed in satellite images was located between 40 and 90 km ENE. Additional emissions produced ash plumes that drifted 50-90 km ENE. Later that day ash plumes rose to altitudes of 6.1-6.7 km and drifted E, ESE, and SE. On 13 March an ash plume rose to an altitude below 4.9 km and drifted E.

Based on satellite images, Mexico City MWO, webcam images, and METAR notices, the Washington VAAC reported that daily ash plumes rose to altitudes of 4.9-8.2 km and drifted 40-150 km NNE, NE, ENE, E and SE. Ash plumes on 30 March also drifted W.

Based on satellite images, Mexico City MWO, Colima Observatory notices, webcam views, local media, and wind data, the Washington VAAC reported multiple ash emissions per day from Colima during 1-3, 5-10 and 13-20 April. Five MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
