Based on satellite images, wind data, webcam images, and notices from the Mexico City MWO, the Washington VAAC reported that during 30 December - 29 January daily ash plumes rose to altitudes of 4.3-6.7 km and drifted as far as 145 km in many different directions.

Based on satellite images, wind data, webcam images, and notices from the Mexico City MWO, the Washington VAAC reported that during 3-8, 14-15, 18-19, 24-25, and 27 February ash plumes rose to altitudes of 4.6-6.7 km and drifted 75-150 km in multiple directions.

Based on satellite and webcam images, notices from the Mexico City MWO, and information from Colima Towers, the Washington VAAC reported that on 2, 4, 5, 7, 11-12, 16-17, 24, and 27-30 March ash plumes rose to altitude of 4-6.1 km and drifted NW, NE, E, SE and SW.

Based on satellite images, wind data, webcam images, and notices from the Mexico City MWO, the Washington VAAC reported that during 2, 6-8, 13, 15-16, 20-22, 25 and 28 April ash plumes rose to altitudes of 4-6.7 km and drifted NW, NNE and NE. They noted that a three-minute-long ash emission was recorded on 28 April by Colima's webcam.

Based on information from Colima Towers and the Mexico City MWO, and webcam and satellite views, the Washington VAAC reported that on 1-4, 6, 9-10, 15-17, 19, 24, and 27 May ash plumes rose to altitudes of 4.3-7.6 km and drifted NW, NE, and E.
Based on satellite images and wind data, the Washington VAAC reported that on 1, 4, 13, 23 and 30 June ash plumes rose to altitudes of 4.6-6.1 km and drifted SW and W.

Based on satellite and webcam images, the Washington VAAC reported that on 17 July an ash emission rose to an altitude of 4.9 km, drifted just over 10 km NW, and quickly dissipated. The next day an ash plume rose to an altitude of 4.6 km and drifted W. During 21, 23-25, and 28-29 July ash plumes rose to altitudes of 4.3-7 km and drifted W and NW. On 31 July Colima Towers and the Mexico City MWO reported that ash plumes rose to altitudes of 5.2-7.3 km and drifted W and WSW.

Based on satellite and webcam images, the Washington VAAC reported that on 12, 14, 16, 20, 26-27, and 29 August ash plumes rose to altitudes of 4.3-6.1 km and drifted as far as 30 km NW, N, W, SE and S.
Based on satellite and webcam images, the Washington VAAC reported that on 1, 7, 18-20 and 25 September ash plumes from rose to altitudes of 4.3-5.5 km and drifted up to 30 km W and NNE.
The Unidad Estatal de Protecci¢n Civil de Colima reported that seismicity increased.
Small landslides originating from a new and growing lava dome traveled 100 m down the S flank. The volume of the lava dome was estimated to have exceeded 1.2 million cubic meters by 4 October 2016.
According to news articles, incandescent landslides traveled down the S and SE flanks.

The Washington VAAC reported that on 29 September gas-and-steam emission possibly containing minor amounts of ash rose to an altitude of 4.9 km and drifted NW. On 30 September the webcam showed gas-and-steam emissions that may have contained ash drifting WNW. Later that day an ash plume rose to an altitude of 5.8 km and drifted 35 km W. Possible emissions with ash were recorded by the webcam on 1 October. An ash plume detected in satellite images drifted almost 40 km S and SW. On 2 October ash plumes rose to altitudes of 6.1-8.2 km and drifted SW and W. On 3 October ash plumes rose to altitudes of 5.5-6.4 and drifted 25-40 km SW and SWW. Based on webcam views ash emissions rose to an estimated altitude of 5.5 km and drifted S on 4 October.

Ash fell in nearby areas including La Becererra, La Yerbabuena, San Antonio, and El Jabali in the municipality of Comala, Montitl n in the municipality of Cuauhtmoc, and Juan Barragan in Tonila, Jalisco.

The Colima State government stated that the communities of La Yerbabuena (80 people) and La Becerrera (230 people) were preemptively evacuated. A news article noted that Juan Barragan was also evacuated.
The webcam showed intense activity and crater incandescence.
An intense thermal anomaly was visible in short-wave infrared satellite images.
The webcam recorded explosions and pyroclastic flows.
The webcam recorded explosions and pyroclastic flows.
Ashfall was reported in areas on the S and SW flanks.

Based on webcam and satellite images, and information from the Mexico City MWO, the Washington VAAC reported that ash plumes rose to altitudes of 4.3-7 km during 5-6, 8-20, 22, 24 and 30 October and drifted 35-215 km W, NW, N, SW, and NE.
Thermal anomalies were observed on most days.

A strong hotspot consistent with lava flow was observed. On 21 October the Unidad Estatal de Protecci¢n Civil de Colima reported that lava continued to flow down the S flank. The lava flow was 2.3 km long, 320 m wide, and had an estimated volume of 21 million m3.
Based on satellite and webcam images, the Washington VAAC reported that on 4 November an ash plume rose to an altitude of 4.6 km and drifted over 30 km SW.

Based on webcam and satellite images, and information from the Mexico City MWO, the Washington VAAC reported that ash plumes rose to altitudes of 4.6-7.3 km and drifted almost 170 km in multiple directions.

Based on information from the National Civil Protection coordinator, news articles reported that an explosion occurred at 0943, generating an ash plume that rose 2.3 km above the crater rim and drifted NNW.

Based on information from the National Civil Protection coordinator, news articles reported that an explosion occurred at 0943, generating an ash plume that rose 2.3 km above the crater rim and drifted NNW.

Lava fountaining occurred from four vents along a fissure at the start of the eruption.  Lava fountains were 10 m high during 16-18 October and rose from two vents. The next day a hornito formed in the second vent and lava was ejected 5-15 m above a third vent. During 20-21 October small lava fountains fed lava flows that traveled as far as 2 km E and SE.  During 22-24 October fountains and gas emissions originated from one vent, and lava traveled ESE. On 28 October material was ejected from Cone 3 (the main vent).

A new eruption began from an eruptive fissure oriented N-S, characterized by lava fountaining and two lava flows. Later that day lava flows from two fissures traveled about 1.5 km N and NW. On 10 December 2010, seismicity and deformation measurements indicated that eruption of lava had stopped.
A seismic swarm preceded the eruption.

A new eruption began from an eruptive fissure oriented N-S, characterized by lava fountaining and two lava flows.  On 10 December 2010, seismicity and deformation measurements indicated that eruption of lava had stopped.
A seismic crisis was detected about 1.5 km SE of the Dolomieu crater rim, a few hours before the eruption began.
Increased gas emissions were recorded a few days prior to an earthquake swarm which began on 20 August.

An earthquake swarm began on 20 August. During 21-22 August seismicity remained high. Five volcano-tectonic earthquakes were felt by local residents and caused windows to vibrate. They were located within a 300-900 m radius from the crater, at depths of less than 2 km. The largest event was M 4.3. On 23 August a M 4.6 earthquake was located E of Galeras at a depth of 2 km.
Seven explosions were recorded during this period.
Loud detonations were audible many kilometers away including in Monti Sartorius (NE flank) and in Zafferana Etnea (SW flank).
The final phase of the event was characterized by a series of violent explosions that produced loud detonations heard in the E and SE sectors of the volcano.
Loud detonations were audible across a vast sector of Etna's densely populated SE to E flanks.
Large bombs and blocks fell onto the cone surrounding the New SE Crater.

Lava fountaining generated heavy fallout of large pyroclastics onto the flanks of the cone.  The continuous, intense ejection of pyroclastics onto the flanks of the cone generated avalanches resembling pyroclastic flows, which descended a few hundred meters beyond the base of the cone, mainly towards the S. The morphological changes affecting the pyroclastic cone surrounding the New SE Crater were significant. Besides the collapse on the lower E flank of the cone, the S and NE rims of the cone had grown in height.
At 0220 the SE flank of the cone fractured and exposed a line of new eruptive vents down to the base of the cone that produced lava fountains.

The pyroclastic cone that grew around the New SE Crater during the recent series of eruptive episodes had undergone significant morphological changes. The S and N crater rims had further increased in height, whereas degradation and mass wasting on the SE flank had become more conspicuous. A large chunk of rock on the lower SE flank was rotated and uplifted, forming a steep-sided "spine" about 20-30 m tall, with locally vertical and sub-vertical flanks.
At approximately 2229 two lightning flashes near the crater were observed.

A small lava flow appeared at the lower end of the eruptive fissure on the SE flank of the cone at about 0700. The lava flow spread out into several branches at the SE base of the cone, advancing only a few hundred meters. Slow lava effusion continued for a few hours from a single vent in the central portion of the eruptive fissure on the SE flank of the New SEC cone. Lava flows from the eruption traveled less than 4 km toward the floor of the Valle del Bove, immediately to the N of the Serra Giannicola ridge, stopping to the SW of Monte Centenari.

Mild Strombolian activity commenced at 0900 from within the New SEC, and spattering began from several vents along the fissure on the SE flank of the cone. This activity continued for nearly three hours, increasing very slowly. At about 1155, the activity markedly and rapidly increased both within the crater and along the fissure, and just after 1200 lava fountains and ash emissions rose from the crater.

At about 1155, the activity markedly and rapidly increased both within the crater and along the fissure, and just after 1200 lava fountains and ash emissions rose from the crater. Lava fountains then rose from vents along the SE flank fissure. Between 1245 and 1315 jets heavily laden with incandescent bombs rose as high as 800 m above the crater.

Bombs and scoria fell into the cone. The most intense phase of the eruption occurred between 1245 and 1315 when jets heavily laden with incandescent bombs rose as high as 800 m above the crater. Pyroclastic material fell onto the New SEC cone, areas well beyond the base, and the nearby old SEC cone.
Explosions occurred from a vent on the N flank of the New SEC cone, likely the same vent that emitted small lava flows on 28 September and 8 October.
A small lava flow spread out into several branches at the SE base of the cone.

Strombolian activity increased around 0400, generating lava fountains, from several vents within the crater that rose 100-150 m above the crater. Around 0515 lava fountains generated a continuous eruption of ash-and-gas plumes that rose to an altitude of 2.1-2.4 km. Around 0600 active vents along the N edge of the New SEC produced intermittent lava fountains.
Significant ashfall and pyroclastic material fell onto the flanks at 0450 on 5 January.
Significant ashfall and pyroclastic material fell onto the flanks at 0450. The N slope of New SEC showed gravitational movement due to the amount of deposited pyroclastic material.
Multiple explosions produced ash emissions, Strombolian activity, and a lava jet.
At 2140 an explosion ejected incandescent material in a narrow vertical jet that rose a few tens of meters above the crater. A small Strombolian explosion occurred at 2231.
On 8 February the New SE Crater (New SEC) of Etna entered another paroxysmal eruption episode after about 12 days of Strombolian activity.

During the afternoon the Strombolian activity increased in both frequency and intensity of explosions from the vent on the W portion of the crater floor, and occasionally from a vent to the E. Around 2100 the Strombolian activity slowly increased, turning into a discontinuous lava fountain around 2330.

After about 1900, lava began to spill into the deep breach on the SE crater rim and then descended to the base of the cone. The lava flow expanded around 2100. The lava flow reached the W rim around 0130, descended the flank, and branched into three different flows that reached a distance of 3 km from the New SEC.
The vent in the SE crater breach produced strong explosions that ejected bombs many meters in diameter. These explosions generated loud bangs that were heard all over Etna.
The beginning of the eruption was characterized by a rapid increase in volcanic tremor amplitude coincident with Strombolian explosions that increased in intensity and frequency.
Explosive activity changed to continuous lava fountaining at about 0830. Lava fountaining ceased at 1032, two hours after the onset of the paroxysmal phase.
An eruption plume developed at about 0830. The eruption column rose several kilometers above the summit of Etna. Ash and lapilli were carried NE by the wind.
In the early morning incandescence intensified due to Strombolian activity on the crater floor.

Pulsating lava fountains from a vent on the crater floor rose about 100 m high. Shortly before 0900 two vents were active within the crater and a jet of lava was emitted from another vent within the breach in the SE crater rim. During 0900-0915 lava fountaining was essentially continuous from all three vents. Lava fountaining continued without significant variations until about 1040 when it diminished.
An intense shower of coarse-grained pyroclastic material falling onto the N and NE flanks of the cone generated avalanches and clouds of rock and dust, which traveled to the base of the cone.
Tall lava fountains rose from vents within the crater and on the SE flank of its cone.
Lava flows descended the flank of the cone towards the Valle del Bove.
The episode included emissions of ash and lapilli.
The episode included lava flows that descended the Valle del Bove.
The episode included lava flows that explosively interacted with snow cover.
A series of small ash emissions that observed by web cameras drifted downslope to the E.

A tiny lava flow issued from an area in the upper portion of the fissure that cuts the SE flank of the cone. The lava flow slowly advanced a few hundred meters toward the Valle del Bove, but stagnated on the W rim. Another lava flow was produced later in the day.

At around 1800 the effusive vent in the upper portion of the fissure that cuts the SE flank of the cone started to vigorously spatter. A second vent became active a few tens of meters further upslope, which initially ejected spatter, but activity rapidly evolved into frequent Strombolian explosions. During the following hours, sporadic explosions were also observed from a vent located within the New SEC. At 0210 on 24 April the Strombolian activity showed a marked increase and turned into sustained lava fountaining.

At 0210 the Strombolian activity showed a marked increase and turned into sustained lava fountaining at 0230. The phase of most intense lava fountaining lasted approximately 25 minutes, from 0240 until 0305, after which the intensity rapidly decreased and returned to Strombolian activity, before ceasing completely around 0340.
INGV-CT reported that at 1509 a powerful explosion initiated a series of ash emissions, which continued at decreasing strength for about 20 minutes.
Ash rose 200-250 m above the crater rim drifting E.
During limited periods of good visibility, sporadic small reddish-to-grayish-brown ash plumes were observed to occur every 5-15 minutes.
Strombolian activity began from Etna's Bocca Nuova crater, representing the first magmatic eruption since 2002.
The strongest explosions ejected incandescent bombs several tens of meters above the crater rim. Most bombs fell back into the crater.

Immediately to the W of the explosive vent, a lava flow was issuing from underneath a sheet of pyroclastic material deposited by the nearby Strombolian activity. The flow cascaded into a deeper depression in the W central portion of the crater floor.

Weak incandescence began to illuminate a gas plume rising from Bocca Nuova, marking the resumption of eruptive activity in this crater nearly one year after a short period of Strombolian and effusive activity.

Strombolian activity occurred at a single vent, a few meters in diameter, at the base of the SE crater wall. Incandescent bombs and scoria ejected by the explosions fell back around the vent. On 4 July, a few bombs fell outside the E crater rim. Similar activity was also observed on 11 and 13 July. During the night of 16-17 July, continuous, bright glow from the crater was visible from populated areas around the volcano. Activity was virtually continuous for three weeks.

Lava was emitted from vents on the flanks of the pyroclastic cone that had begun to grow around the explosive vent. Rarely, lava was emitted from the main explosive vent. The lava progressively covered the crater floor next to the pyroclastic cone before the activity ceased on 24 July.
A pyroclastic cone grew around the explosive vent. The pyroclastic cone grew 30-40 m before the activity ceased. Renewed activity on 26 July increased the size of the cone.
Frequent ash emissions were mostly due to explosions, and possibly from minor collapses of the summit area of the new cone.

Episodic activity occurred every few days during the period. Frequent Strombolian explosions occurred from a vent located on the W flank of the cone on 26-27 July.  Small Strombolian explosions from a vent located on the S flank of the pyroclastic cone occurred during 29 July-1 August. Strombolian activity recurred on 3-4, 6-7, 10-11, and 13 August. Some of the explosions ejected incandescent pyroclastic material well above the crater rim.

Lava flows issued from a vent located on the W flank of the cone on 26 July. The next day, the lava had almost completely filled the central subsidence pit on the floor of Bocca Nuova, and the cone had grown in height. Lava issued from a vent located on the S flank of the pyroclastic cone during 29 July-1 August. Additional lava flows occurred on 3-4 and 6-7 August.

There were intermittent ash emissions on 28 July, 2, 4, 6, and 11-13 August. They were particularly frequent on 13 August, and produced small, brownish-gray clouds of fine-grained tephra. Some of the ash emissions later that evening were accompanied by ejected incandescent material.

During the evening of 2 October weak Strombolian activity resumed within Etna's Bocca Nuova crater, from the same vent on the SE part of the crater floor that was active in July and August 2012. Over the next few days the activity slowly intensified. The intensity of both the eruptive activity and the volcanic tremor amplitude peaked just after midnight on 7 October, and strong glow from the crater was observed from nearby populated areas. Activity decreased at 0430, and the next day dropped to the lowest levels recorded for many weeks.
A small inter-crater lava flow appeared on the S part of the floor. Lava flowed towards the W part of the crater floor and lava fountains pulsated during the peak of activity.
Activity slowly intensified and a small new cone developed over the old cone formed during July-August, which had subsequently nearly completely collapsed.

Volcanic tremor amplitude and eruptive activity rapidly increased on the evening of 6 October. Lava flowed towards the W part of the crater floor and lava fountains pulsated. Some of the lava jets rose well above the crater rim before activity diminished.
A weak glow emanated from Etna's New Southeast Crater (NSEC) caused by the emission of high-temperature gas. The glow was most intense during 1-2 December, then rapidly diminished.
A seismic swarm, consisting of around seventy events, occurred below the NW flank with epicenters located in the area of Monte Maletto.
Sporadic and weak ash emissions from NSEC were accompanied by increased gas emissions.
A strong glow was briefly observed.

Vigorous Strombolian activity at Bocca Nuova Crater began at night three months after the last episode.  Ten minutes after midnight a video camera recorded the first burst in the E part of the crater, which progressively became stronger and more frequent. At 0350 jets of incandescent fragments rose significantly higher than the crater rim. In the early morning of 15 January volcanic tremor amplitude rapidly decreased, marking the cessation of Strombolian activity in the Bocca Nuova Crater.

At 0000 a rapid rise in tremor amplitude was detected. the volcanic tremor amplitude remained elevated but started to decrease around 1200. In the early morning of 15 January volcanic tremor amplitude rapidly decreased.

Two episodes of Strombolian activity from Etna's Bocca Nuova Crater occurred during the evenings of 16 and 18 January. Both began with a sudden increase in volcanic tremor amplitude. Poor weather conditions prevented direct observations; the only visible evidence was a bright glow illuminating the clouds covering the summit. On 18 January some clasts were ejected onto the S outer slope of the central summit cone.

In the early morning volcanic tremor amplitude rose, and was much more pronounced at the EBEL station about 700 m from the New Southeast Crater (NSEC) than at the ECPN station much closer to Bocca Nuova. Contemporaneously, there were reports of glow illuminating the clouds over the summit of Etna. Seismic and infrasonic data analyses suggested that the activity occurred at NSEC and consisted of mild Strombolian explosions, which ceased a few hours later.
Seismic and infrasonic data analyses suggested that the activity occurred at NSEC and consisted of mild Strombolian explosions, which lasted for a few hours.

Glow from Strombolian activity was first recorded by a camera at 1856; the activity then became more clearly visible and the Strombolian explosions became more frequent. Incandescent bombs were ejected as high as 100 m above the crater rim. The strongest explosions were followed by abundant fallout of coarse-grained tephra onto the flanks of the NSEC cone.
Noises produced by the explosions were audible to residents on the E flank.
A few small, sporadic puffs of vapor mixed with volcanic ash rose from the crater and drifted E.

Intense Strombolian activity at Etna's Bocca Nuova Crater began on the evening of 30 January. Weak glow from a vent on the SE part of the crater floor was first observed at 1807. The glow became stronger and was visible to nearby residents. Between 1900 and 1915 the activity intensified, and from 1920 onward jets of incandescent volcanic bombs and scoria nearly continuously rose higher than the crater rim. Some tephra was ejected 150 m above the rim. During the night weak eruptive activity continued on the crater floor, evident from a dull glow emanating from the crater.

During 1930-2000, lava fountains rose 100 m above the rim. Shortly after 2000, the fountain leaned SW and produced heavy fallout of incandescent bombs and scoria on the outer SW flank of the central summit cone, down to its base. At 2016 the fountain rose vertically and pyroclastic fallout outside the crater diminished. Around 2030 the lava fountain started to wane; the incandescent jets became discontinuous and only rarely rose more than 100 m above the crater rim, except for one jet, at 2100, which rose 150 m above the rim. After 2200, the incandescent pyroclastic jets no longer rose above the crater rim, and the glow became progressively less brilliant.
Ash emissions at New Southeast Crater (NSEC) were nearly continuous for intervals lasting from a few minutes to more than one hour. Plumes rose no higher than 100 m above the crater rims.

After 0330 sporadic small explosions ejected incandescent pyroclastic material up to a few tens of meters above the crater rim. The strongest explosions (at 0345, 0400, 0409, and 0411) ejected glowing bombs onto the flanks of the NSEC cone. Small Strombolian explosions resumed in NSEC at 0512. Activity at NSEC started to decrease at 0530 then ceased just before 0600.
During the days following the 2 February eruptive episode at Etna intermittent emissions of small quantities of ash were repeatedly observed.

Volcanologists observed the recent changes that had taken place at Bocca Nuova Crater, notably the growth of a pyroclastic cone surrounding the eruptive vent in the SE portion of the crater. This cone had grown at least 50-70 m, about halfway up the inner crater wall, and was leaning into the wall. The entire crater floor was covered with recent lava.

At 2100 a webcam recorded fluctuating glow from within Bocca Nuova which became more intense over the next 10 minutes. Around 2125 jets of incandescent lava were repeatedly seen rising above a thick blanket of clouds drifting over the summit area of Etna. Volcanic tremor amplitude rose sharply. After 2200 the volcanic tremor amplitude began to decrease, whereas the eruptive activity continued without showing signs of diminishing until about 30 minutes later.
A webcam recorded weak Strombolian activity at NSEC in the evening, which continued until daybreak the next day,
Sporadic ash emissions from NSEC were observed, although poor weather conditions often prevented observations. On the evening of 8 February weak glow from NSEC was intermittently visible.
A camera recorded incandescence from Etna's New Southeast Crater (NSEC).

Strombolian activity gradually intensified on 17 February along with volcanic tremor amplitude. Small Strombolian explosions occurred every 1-2 seconds at daybreak, launching coarse-grained pyroclastic material a few tens of meters above the crater rim. After reaching a peak around 0700, activity started to diminish; a few hours later, the volcanic tremor amplitude returned to background levels, and by the evening there was no sign of eruptive activity. Shortly before midnight on 18 February, the clouds dissipated from the summit area, revealing continuous weak Strombolian activity within NSEC. During 0000-0200 on 19 February the volcanic tremor amplitude rose gradually, then distinctly increased after 0200. The eruptive activity started to intensify from one vent in the center of the crater. From 0503 until 0507 several vents became active along a fracture from the pit crater to the notch in the SE crater rim. The entire NSEC cone was subjected to heavy fallout of coarse-grained pyroclastic material.
The episode ended with a series of sporadic, small ash emissions, the last of which was seen around 0641.
Small discrete "puffs" of ash rose from Bocca Nuova. Ash plumes rose no higher than 100 m above the crater rim.

At 0450 jets of lava rose above the rim of Bocca Nuova; at 0500 Strombolian activity became continuous, producing jest that rose many tens of meters above the rim. Just after 0515 activity at Bocca Nuova started to increase rapidly; contemporaneously, the volcanic tremor amplitude showed a sharp rise. Lava fountains rose 120-150 m above the rim. Activity at Bocca Nuova decreased markedly between 0620 and 0630.
During the days following the 2 February eruptive episode at Etna intermittent emissions of small quantities of ash were repeatedly observed.
A brief ash emission was observed.

A dark-colored ash plume rose 1 km above the pit crater at the eastern base of the South-East Crater (SEC) after it collapsed, and drifted NE at the same time that 12 seismic events were recorded.
INGV-CT reported that twelve low-frequency events located near the summit were detected by the seismic network.

Three explosions from the Tompaluan crater, in the saddle between the Lokon-Empung peaks were recorded by the CVGHM. The Darwin VAAC reported a low-level eruption on 27 December based on media reports that rose to 1.5 km altitude.
The Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 3.7 km.
According to news articles, an explosion from the Tompaluan crater, in the saddle between the Lokon-Empung peaks, produced an ash plume that rose as high as 2 km above the crater.

According to news articles, an explosion from the Tompaluan crater, in the saddle between the Lokon-Empung peaks, produced an ash plume that rose as high as 2 km above the crater. Based on information from CVGHM, the Darwin VAAC reported ash plumes that rose to altitudes of 3-3.4 km, though clouds prevented the detection of ash in satellite imagery.
According to news articles loud "thumping" noises were heard.
An eruption was accompanied by loud "thumping" noises heard at local observation posts; fog prevented views of the crater.
According to the Darwin VAAC, ash plumes that rose to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifted 75 km N, were detected in satellite imagery and reported by ground-based observers.

According to the Center of Volcanology and Geological Hazard Mitigation (CVGHM), seismicity and visual observations of Tompaluan crater in the saddle between the twin peaks of Lokon and Empung indicated that activity continued to be high.

According to the Center of Volcanology and Geological Hazard Mitigation (CVGHM) seismicity and visual observations of Tompaluan crater in the saddle between the twin peaks of Lokon and Empung indicated that activity continued to be high.
Lokon erupted 12 times on 28 August. One explosion on 29 August ejected material 250 m above the crater.
Explosions from the crater produced ash plumes.
Satellite observations showed ash and block deposits from the previous day's eruption scattered to the N and E of Tompaluan crater out to a distance of ~400 m from the crater rim.

The Jakarta Post reported that Lokon-Empung erupted at 1155. This eruption was larger in magnitude than the one on 24-25 April 2012. The eruption was preceded by a number of mild earthquakes that occurred over a span of 2 min. A report noted that "smoke" plumes reached an altitude of 2.5 km.
The Jakarta Post reported that Lokon-Empung erupted at 1155. A report noted that "smoke" plumes reached an altitude of 2.5 km.
The Darwin VAAC reported an ash plume that rose to 1.5 km altitude.
Residents living near Telica felt an earthquake during the night and during the following day they observed small plumes rising from the volcano.
INETER scientists visited for routine data collection and to investigate reports of fresh ashfall. Light ash was still visible on leaves and rooftops and appeared directed towards the N and SE.
INETER reported that during April seismicity  increased, with earthquake magnitudes ranging up to 3.3 and some explosions detected.
Small explosions from the summit occurred at least once per week throughout the month.
Explosions were registered having 30-minute durations and were followed by periods of degassing and low-altitude ash plumes.
Explosions were registered having 30-minute durations and were followed by periods of degassing and low-altitude ash plumes.
During the first week of May seismicity increased to 500 microseismic events per day.
Tephra fall was reported in La Quemada, 4 km N.
The seismic network registered three explosions that were accompanied by gas-and-tephra emissions.
The seismic network registered three explosions that were accompanied by gas-and-tephra emissions.
One plume rose 1.2 km above the crater.
Nearby communities to the SE, including Cristo Rey, Las Colinas, and La Quemada, were affected by the emissions.
A series of small explosions was detected.
A gas-and-ash plume rose 600 m above the crater.
After two hours of sustained explosive activity producing ash plumes ~ 600 m high, the largest explosion suddenly occurred at 1350.
A column of ash rose to an altitude of 2.6 km and was maintained for six minutes.
More than 15 explosions were accompanied by gas-and-ash plumes that rose 500-800 m high.
More than 15 explosions were accompanied by gas-and-ash plumes that rose 500-800 m high.

The municipal committee for disaster prevention and mitigation (COMUPRED) reported the evacuation of 390 families from nine villages near the volcano. The villages included Agua Fr¡a (150 m from the edifice) and Los Patos, the most distant of the villages at 8 km from the edifice.
An observer reported four strong explosions and gas-and-tephra plumes that rose 500-700 m high. In addition, at 1500 on the 20th, one large, continuous explosion occurred that lasted 36 minutes.

An observer reported four strong explosions and gas-and-tephra plumes that rose 500-700 m high. Observers described a plume containing gas, steam, tephra, and small rocks from a large, continuous explosion at 1500 that lasted 36 minutes.
At 1500 one large, continuous explosion occurred that lasted 36 minutes. Observers described a plume containing gas, steam, tephra, and small rocks. The plume reached 2 km altitude.
INETER reported that ash explosions became infrequent.
INETER reported that ash explosions became infrequent.
A cluster of eight explosions occurred sequentially and created plumes reaching 600 m above the crater.
A cluster of eight explosions occurred sequentially and created plumes reaching 600 m above the crater. Ash drifted SE at 8-15 km/hour at altitudes of 1.5 km.

During a field visit by INETER the investigators counted 17 explosions that expelled ash and gas. Most of the explosions occurred in intervals of two to three minutes with the longest interval of 10 minutes.
During a field visit by INETER the investigators managed to count 17 explosions that expelled ash and gas.
The VAAC noted an ash plume rose to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifted 37 km.
Lava flows traveled as far as 2 km from the main crater, accompanied by roaring and booming noises, and block avalanches from the flow fronts moved 500 m down the flanks.
Avalanches from the crater traveled 3.8 km down the flanks.

Multiple pyroclastic flows about 1.5 km long destroyed a bridge, damaged a house, and trapped 31 people between the flow paths who were later evacuated. Later that day pyroclastic flows traveled 4 km, reaching the shore.
Lava flows traveled as far as 2 km and avalanches from the lava flow fronts went up to 500 m further.
Incandescent material rolled 1.5 km down the flanks.
Pyroclastic flows traveled 2.3 km from the crater.

A thunderous sound was accompanied by a gray plume that rose 200 m above the crater.
Lava flowed 200 m down the flanks and produced incandescent material from the flow fronts that traveled an additional 1.5-1.8 km. Lava flow and avalanche activity decreased on 19 May.
Lava flowed 200 m down the flanks and produced incandescent material from the flow fronts that traveled an additional 1.5-1.8 km. Lava flow and avalanche activity decreased on 19 May.
Bluish-white emissions rose as high as 500 m from the main crater and incandescence from the crater was observed at night.

Incandescent material traveled 1,500 m from the Main Crater.

A Reuters News photo published in Okezone News showed a moderate Strombolian eruption venting from the summit  with an apron of incandescent spatter dotting the upper slopes, and a swath of red spatter and bombs bouncing down one flank.
MODVOLC thermal alerts were reported multiple times each month.
Single MODVOLC alerts issued on 8 and 13 August 2011 were the last for the year.
RVO reported that variable amounts of white vapor plumes rose from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone and were occasionally tinted brown.
Dull incandescence emanated from a small caved-in vent on the floor of the crater.
The start of an ash eruption was marked by an emergent low-frequency tremor and slowly rising gray ash plumes.
One explosion possibly produced light ashfall to the NW.
One explosion possibly produced light ashfall to the NW.
An explosion produced a gray ash plume that rose 1 km above the crater and drifted NNW.
An explosion produced a gray ash plume that rose 1 km above the crater and drifted NNW. Sustained emissions of pale-gray ash continued for about an hour afterwards.
Ash deposited at the former airport was re-suspended and blown NW into the E part of Rabaul town (3-5 km NW) and towards Namanula hill (3 km W).

RVO reported a decline in frequency of ash emission from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone. Ash-rich plumes rose 1 km above the crater and drifted NW, causing ashfall in Rabaul town (3-5 km NW) and in areas between Toliap (10 km NW) and Tavui.
Ash-rich plumes rose 1 km above the crater and drifted NW, causing ashfall in Rabaul town (3-5 km NW) and in areas between Toliap (10 km NW) and Tavui.

Gray ash emissions periodically continued, punctuated by a few large and notable explosions. Ash plumes from the explosions rose 1 km above the crater and drifted N and NW producing fine ashfall in the E part of Rabaul town, Namanula Hill, and further downwind towards Tavui Point. During 5-9 August activity increased, characterized by an increased frequency and duration of ash emissions. Ash-rich clouds that rose 1.5 km above the crater drifted NW causing ashfall in most parts of Rabaul town and in areas between Toliap and Nonga (10 km NW).

Gray ash emissions periodically continued, punctuated by a few large and notable explosions. Ash plumes from the explosions rose 1 km above the crater and drifted N and NW producing fine ashfall in the E part of Rabaul town, Namanula Hill, and further downwind towards Tavui Point. During 5-9 August activity increased, characterized by more explosions. About 34 explosions were recorded between 5 and 8 August.

Ash plumes from explosions rose 1 km above the crater and drifted N and NW producing fine ashfall in the E part of Rabaul town, Namanula Hill, and further downwind towards Tavui Point. During 5-9 August activity increased. Ash-rich clouds that rose 1.5 km above the crater drifted NW causing ashfall in most parts of Rabaul town and in areas between Toliap and Nonga (10 km NW).
KVERT reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 5 km and drifted SW.

The Tokyo VAAC reported that a possible eruption detected in satellite imagery produced a plume that rose to an altitude of 6.1 km and drifted NE. The VAAC stated that the ash could have also originated at Bezymianny.
Based on information from the Yelizovo Airport (UHPP), the Tokyo VAAC reported that an eruption from Kliuchevskoi produced a plume that rose to an altitude of 7 km and drifted E.
A Northern Mariana Islands status report noted that a low-level gas-and-steam plume with possible fine ash was detected in satellite imagery as well as noted by observers on the island.

A Northern Mariana Islands status report noted that low-level vapor plumes, possibly containing minor amounts of ash, were visible in satellite imagery. Reports from people on Pagan Island also indicated intermittent low-level but diffuse ash emissions and trace amounts of ashfall on parts of the island.
Steam and gas emissions with possible ash. Plumes rose to 3 km altitude and drifted E on 1 July and to 1.5 km altitude and drifted NW and W on 2 and 3 July.
Gas emissions and possible ash rose to 1.5 km altitude and drifted S.
Gas emissions and possible ash rose to 1.5 km altitude and drifted W.
Gas and ash emissions rose to 2.4 km altitude and drifted NE.
Evidence for activity in May  2011 comes from a report by Volcano Discovery of 2-3 small ash eruptions per day.
MODVOLC thermal alert pixels appeared on 2 June, 15 June, and 1 July.
PVMBG reported eruptions of pyroclastic material on 9, 14, and 17 June.
Volcano Discovery reported a growing lava dome on 1 September with 3-4 ash explosions per day during the first two weeks of September.
Volcano Discovery reported a growing lava dome on 1 September with 3-4 ash explosions per day during the first two weeks of September.
Volcano Discovery reported a growing lava dome on 1 September with 3-4 ash explosions per day during the first two weeks of September.
Seismicity increased, and dense white and gray plumes rose as high as 600 m above the Jonggring Seloko crater.
Dense white and gray plumes rose as high as 600 m above the Jonggring Seloko crater.
Dense gray-white plumes rose 600 m and preceded an explosion.
Dense gray-white plumes rose 600 m and preceded an explosion on 6 January 2012; the explosion was followed by summit incandescence.
Repeated observations of incandescent material flowing up to 400 m SE toward the Besuk Kembar drainage were made during the rest of January.
Just after midnight, a pyroclastic flow traveled 300 m from the Jongring Seloko crater, and by mid-morning it had traveled farther, to 2.5 km from the crater.
Numerous MODVOLC thermal alert pixels were recorded between 30 January and 21 April 2012, and a final pixel recorded on 9 May 2012.
CVGHM reported that multiple pyroclastic flows traveled 500 and 2,500 m into the Besuk Kembar and Besuk Kobokan rivers (on the S flank).
Incandescence was visible up to 50 m above the crater.
Volcano Discovery reported that on an expedition they observed slow lava dome growth, with an incandescent area at the SW part of the dome producing small to moderate ash explosions.
Volcano Discovery reported that on an expedition they observed slow lava dome growth, with an incandescent area at the SW part of the dome producing small to moderate ash explosions.
Crater incandescence was observed and avalanches carried incandescent material 200-400 m away from the crater.
Dense gray-to-white plumes rose 100-500 m above Jongring Seloko crater and drifted W and N.
Observations indicated that the lava dome grew in April.
Based on pilot observations, the Tokyo VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 2.1 km and drifted NE.
JMA reported that plumes intermittently rose to altitudes of 1.8-2.1 km and drifted in many directions. A pilot noted on 18 May that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 3 km.
A GPS-station on the rim of the Gr¡msvtn caldera had revealed continuous inflation and expansion of few centimeters per year since the 2004 eruption.
A few hours after the onset of the eruption ashfall began over areas S of the Vatnajkull ice cap, more than 50 km from the eruption site.
Ashfall was reported from the Reykjav¡k area in the SW to Trllaskagi Peninsula in the N.
The ash plume rose to altitudes of 5-10 km and drifted S at lower altitudes and W at altitudes of 8 km and higher.

The ash plume was estimated to be mostly below 5 km because meteorological clouds over the glacier were at 5-7 km and the plume only briefly rose above the cloud deck. Satellite images showed the plume extending over 800 km from the eruption site towards the S and SE.

According to scientists from the Institute of Earth Sciences at the University of Iceland and the Icelandic Meteorological Office, explosive activity occurred from four tephra cones surrounded by water in Gr¡msvtn's crater during the evening.
Observers noted steam bursts from the crater.
Tephra fallout was noted only in the vicinity of the eruption site.
Pilots reported widespread airborne ash in layers 5-7 km W of the volcano and also some ash haze below 3 km to the SW.
Observers noted ash thicknesses varying from 10 to 130 cm in the vicinity of the eruption site.
Local ashfall occurred around the crater.
A seismic swarm was detected at depths of 4-6 km.
Residents reported a strong sulfur odor and significant ash and pumice fall. Ashfall several centimeters thick was reported in San Carlos de Bariloche, 100 km SE in Argentina, and surrounding areas.
An ash plume continued to rise to altitudes of 10.7-12.2 km and had drifted as far as 1,778 km ESE, over the coast of Argentina, and out into the Atlantic Ocean. A portion of the plume drifted WSW.

On 6 June the continuous ash plume changed direction and was blown ENE as far as 178 km while the previous portion of the plume continued to drift ESE over the ocean. On 7 June the VAAC reported continuous emissions. Ash plumes rose to altitudes of 5.5-9.8 km and were 65-95 km wide. A large area of ash continued to drift E over the Atlantic Ocean.
News photos showed ashfall and people collecting pumice in San Martin de los Andes, Argentina, 80 km NE.

OVDAS-SERNAGEOMIN reported that on 8 June satellite imagery showed a 1,200-km-long eruption plume drifting NE, then SE over the Atlantic Ocean. Personnel working in the area reported that the ash plume rose 7.5 km above the crater. On 9 June climatic conditions prevented ground-based observations, however satellite imagery showed a 200-km-long plume drifting NE. Despite poor visibility due to meteorological conditions on 10 June, the plume was observed to have risen 3.7 km above the crater and drifted SE. On 11 June the plume was whiter than previous days and rose to heights 4-4.5 km above the crater and drifted 350 km E. A dispersed plume was detected as far as 600 km ENE.
Pumice and vitreous tephra had accumulated in many area lakes and rivers, and ash had turned many rivers darker.
Abundant amounts of ash had accumulated around the vent as well as to the E and SW.
An explosion caused an ash plume to rise 8 km above the crater.
An explosion caused an ash plume to rise 8 km above the crater.
A series of explosions (up to 8 events per minute) were registered.

Very dense, dark gray ash plumes rose 8 km above the crater. Satellite imagery showed a distinct eruption plume drifting 300 km E, with a diffuse plume reaching 1,000 km ENE. According to news articles, the ash plume that had been drifting mostly E since the beginning of the eruption had reached Australia and beyond, causing flight cancellations in southern Australia and New Zealand.

Scientists aboard an overflight observed the plume height oscillating and noted that the eruptive vent diameter was 300-400 m. Gas-and-steam plumes rose from two or three locations along the same fissure as the eruptive vent.
Pulses of tremor were associated with dark gray ash plumes that rose 9 km above the crater. Satellite imagery showed the plume drifting 250 km SE.
Ashfall and column collapses were noted.
At night incandescence from the base of the plume reached 1.5-2 km high.
Explosions generated pyroclastic flows (that traveled N), with associated ash-and-gas plumes.
Explosions generated pyroclastic flows (that traveled N), with associated ash-and-gas plumes.
Based on analysis of satellite imagery, the VAAC stated that ash plumes rose to altitudes of 5.5-7.6 km while previously emitted ash plumes drifted NE, E, and SE at altitudes of 0.9-3 km.

The eruption plume rose 4-5 km above the crater and drifted SE. The base of the plume was dark gray and ash continued to fall in areas near the volcano. The next day the plume rose 3 km above the crater and was whiter. Satellite imagery showed the plume drifting 1,400 km ESE. On 17 June the plume rose 2 km above the crater and drifted SE. According to news articles, plumes from the eruption had circumnavigated the globe, and arrived in the W part of Chile (in Coyhaique, 550 km S of the volcano). On 19 June the plume rose 2 km above the crater and drifted SE.
A white plume that was gray at the base rose 3-4 km above the crater. Cameras installed around the volcano showed the plume, which was periodically very dark, rising 5-6 km above the crater.

During 22 and 24-26 June cameras installed around the volcano recorded ash plumes that rose 2-4 km above the crater and drifted NW, N, and NE. On 23 and 28 June the Buenos Aires VAAC reported that ash clouds detected in satellite imagery rose to altitudes of 4-4.6 km and drifted E and NE. On 25 June SERNAGEOMIN noted that satellite images showed that the plume drifted 200 km N then an additional 900 km NNE. The next day the plume drifted 250 km N, then turned NNW and drifted 1,450 km. On 27 June satellite images detected a plume that was dense for 300 m then was no longer discernible due to meteorological clouds.

Ashfall was periodically reported in areas downwind, including in Ri¤inahue (5-10 mm of ash) Llifen, Futrono, and Curarrehue on 22 June, and Ri¤inahue, Puc¢n, and Melipeuco (in the region of Araucan¡a) on 25 June.

On 1 July a white plume, possibly with lower ash content, rose 3 km above the crater and was observed in satellite imagery drifting 200 km N. During 2-4 July SERNAGEOMIN noted that dark gray plumes rose 2-4 km above the crater and were detected in satellite imagery drifting 200-900 km NW, N, and somewhat E. On 5 July satellite imagery showed that the plume drifted N then NW.

Seismicity indicated that during 29 June-2 July the lava flow remained active, although to a lesser degree than during previous days. During 2-3 July seismic signals indicated that lava had stopped flowing or was emitted at a slower rate. The next day high-intensity tremor suggested that the lava flow was again active. On 9 July seismicity indicated that lava flows had ceased.
Lava fountaining from NSEC continued through the late morning and was then followed by a long series of powerful explosions audible to many tens of kilometers away.

Lava emitted from the saddle between the two cones of the Southeast Crater (SEC, NSEC) advanced S, destroying two wooden shacks at Torre del Filosofo. Another smaller lava flow descended the SE flank of the NSEC cone, partially filling the deep collapse scar formed during the 27 April 2013 paroxysm. Lava flows continued to advance the next day.
According to news articles, a phreatic eruption produced an ash plume that rose 2 km above the crater and caused ashfall in areas as far as 60 km E.
A news article in the Jakarta Post said that an eruption began at 0453 LT forming a plume that rose to 2 km above the crater.

Explosions occurred at 1619 and 1651. Fog prevented observations for a period after the explosions; once the fog cleared dense gray plumes were observed. A third explosion occurred at 2100. The next day an explosion at 0550 generated an ash plume that rose 3 km and caused ashfall in areas S. Another explosion was detected at 0612.
According to a news article, about 3,300 people that evacuated their homes were mostly from two villages within 3 km of Sinabung, in the Karo district.
An eruption began at 0126 on that generated ash plumes up to 7 km altitude and triggered evacuations from communities within 3 km of the volcano (approximately 1,681 residents).
A news article noted that more than 7,000 people had been evacuated from 10 villages.
According to a news article, a pyroclastic flow traveled 1.2 km down the SE flank, prompting evacuations from villages near the base of the volcano.

Lava dome formation preceded and followed plinian explosive phase.
A special report by MARN (Ministerio de Medio Ambiente Y Recursos Naturales) noted the sudden eruption of San Miguel at 1030 local time. The main eruptive phase lasted until 1300.

Washington VAAC reported that the ash plume rose to an altitude of 9.7 km and drifted ENE at altitudes above 6 km and W at lower altitudes. Volcanic ash from the eruption traveled more than 70 km downwind to the SW.
According to news articles, an explosive eruption at San Miguel that began at 1030 prompted an evacuation of 1,400-2,600 people.
KVERT reported that a weak thermal anomaly was detected.

A phreatic eruption began at about 0300 and generated an ash plume that rose 5 km. On 27 October KVERT noted that strong fumarolic activity and gas emissions continued, but that the phreatic explosions likely had ceased.

A phreatic eruption began at about 0300 and generated an ash plume that rose 5 km. The ash plume was visible in satellite images drifting 40 km SE and S. Ash plumes at 1635 and 2218 rose to altitudes of 2.5-3 km and drifted 120 km ESE and 25 km S.
Pilots observed ash-and-steam plumes at an altitude of 7.3 km that drifted SSW.
BNPB reported that two explosions occurred at 1330 and 2242, larger than the previous day.
Based on satellite images, pilot observations, and the Indonesian Meteorological Office, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 15.2 km and drifted 440 km E and 750 km SE.

At 0714 an eruption from the submarine SE flank vent, Hobal, ejected dense white plumes 2 km high that drifted S. Incandescence at sea level was observed at 0746, and the water around the eruption site turned yellow.

The Japanese Coast Guard reported that a Surtseyan eruption 500 m SE from the coast of Nishimo-shima generated a new island. The island was about 300 x 200 m, and developed a crater 150m wide. Discolored water surrounded the island. The new island, originally called Niijima ('new island') by the Japan Coast Guard (JCG), eventually merged with Nishinoshima on 24 December 2013.
Based on satellite images, the Tokyo Volcanic Ash Advisory Center (VAAC) reported that at 0717 UTC a plume rose 600 m over a new island.
Television footage (Frisk, 2013) showed ash and rocks exploding from the crater as steam billowed out of the crater.
The island was about 300 x 200 m, and developed a crater 150m wide. On 22 November the eruption continued and incandescence within the crater was observed.

Lava flows from the crater extended to the coastline of the island by 24 November. On 1 December the crater remained very hot and lava flows continued to expand. According to a news article, since mid-December lava flows from the newly formed Niijima island expanded NE towards Nishino-shima, and on 24 December the two islands joined. The Niijima area was about 500 m long and 450 m wide.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
Based on analysis of satellite imagery and wind data, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifted less than 30 km NW.
The fissures were aligned with at least six different fissures from earlier eruptions and erupted lava flows covering 10.1 sq km with a volume of 0.099 cu km.
This Axial eruption caused the caldera floor to subside by more than 2 m.

The lava flow was at least 2 km wide. The flows originated from multiple fissure vents extending 10 km from the eastern caldera rim south to near the south rift lava flow from the 1998 eruption. The lava flows covered 10.1 sq km with a volume of 0.099 cu km.

The bottom-anchored instruments documented hundreds of tiny earthquakes during the volcanic eruption, but land-based seismic monitors and the Sound Surveillance System (SOSUS) hydrophone array operated by the U.S. Navy only detected a handful of them on the day of the eruption because many components of the hydrophone system were offline.
Two explosions within 40 minutes; plume to 17 km.

Heavy rain on 18 February caused lahars in Ngobo, Mangli (Kediri, 35 km WNW), Bladak (Blitar, 20 km SW), and Konto (Malang, 35 km E). BNPB noted that the lahars flooded five houses and one mosque, and destroyed two homes and one bridge.
JMA reported that a very small explosion from Naka-daka Crater occurred. An off-white plume rose 100 m above the crater rim and drifted S.
At 1215 a very small eruption from Naka-dake Crater generated a grayish white plume that rose 600 m and drifted S, producing ashfall downwind.

The Darwin VAAC reported ash plumes from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone rose to 18.3 km altitude.
The Tokyo VAAC reported ash plumes that rose 1.5-2.1 km and drifted N and NE.
Fifty-six (56) deaths due to pyroclastic flows, and 7 more missing (as of October 2014).

On 5 January, OVSICORI-UNA reported that an eruption from Turrialba produced ashfall in local areas, particularly in areas to the SW, including near Iraz£ volcano (11 km SW). Ash fell mainly over the farms adjacent to La Central and La Silvia, Capellades town. Finer ash was reported at Tierra Blanca, Llano Grande and Tres R¡os, ~ 25 km SW, and in eastern San Jos, ~ 30 km away. The ash was expelled for over 22 hours, in a continuing sequence of pulses.

Two seismic events detected about 15 minutes apart were followed by reports of ashfall as far away as 30 km. Field observations on 6 January revealed that two small vents had opened and joined together on the SE inner wall of the SW crater. The combined vent was about 25 m wide and 80 m long.
Around 60 people had evacuated from nearby farms.
A gas-and-steam plume on 15 February that reached 1.5-2 km in height produced noise that was heard 4 km to the SW.
OVSICORI-UNA reported that a phreatic eruption from Turrialba that began on 5 January was preceded by about 30 minutes of almost constant tremor.
OVSICORI-UNA reported that a phreatic eruption from Turrialba that began on 5 January was preceded by a day of increased seismicity. On 8 January seismic activity and gas emissions decreased.
According to news articles, about 7,000 were requested by officials to evacuate, although few left their homes.

Seismicity associated with the eruption continued for a period of about 12 hours and gradually declined in the afternoon. During 26-31 August at least 12 earthquakes, M 2-4, were located within a 2-km radius from the crater, at depths not more than 3 km.

Incandescent material was observed by JMSDF inside Crater 2; light grayish-white plumes intermittently rose to 800 m at intervals of approximately one minute, and ejecta were scattered several tens of meters into the air above the crater.
Light grayish-white plumes intermittently rose to 800 m at intervals of approximately one minute.
Plumes rose as high as 1,500 m in February 2014 according to JCG.

By 11 February, the Japan Coast Guard reported the new land area from lava flows was 920 m E-W and 750 m N-S. Incandescence was photographed at Crater 2 along with a rapidly changing landscape from the active lava flows. In just three weeks, the lagoon on the eastern side of the island went from open, to closed off by lava flows and volcanic debris.
The land area was reported by JCG as 1,190 x 1,000 m, with an elevation of 72 m at the highest point.
A new cone (Crater 3) that emerged in between the first two was first observed with incandescent spatter reaching tens of meters into the air.
A new cone (Crater 3) that emerged in between the first two was first observed with incandescent spatter reaching tens of meters into the air.
The island was about 300 x 200 m, and developed a crater 150m wide. On 22 November the eruption continued and incandescence within the crater was observed.
A fourth crater was seen emitting brown ash plumes.
A fourth crater was seen emitting brown ash plumes.

Multiple near-daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.

Multiple near-daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
A MODVOLC thermal alert was issued.
Multiple near-daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.

Steaming along the shoreline indicated at least two locations with active, or recently active, lava ocean entries, possibly tube-fed since no surface incandescence was visible. Night video clearly showed an active lava flow and ocean entry being supplied from lava fountaining out of a cinder cone.
Night video clearly showed an active lava flow and ocean entry being supplied from lava fountaining out of a cinder cone.

A significant steam plume was rising from the center of the lava shield from hot tephra deposits over a broad area rather than a crater. However, pulsating tephra ejections and distinctly brown ash plumes were rising from two smaller craters.
An incandescent lava lake was visible in one of the small craters on both days.
Tokyo VAAC reported volcanic ash at 3 km altitude at 2203; the plume extended NE.
JCG observed another new crater (Crater 5) on the east side of the island generating a continuous steam-and-ash plume.
JCG observed a new crater (Crater 5) on the east side of the island generating a continuous steam-and-ash plume.
Multiple near-daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
Multiple near-daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
Crater 6 was first observed to the E of the main crater complex.

Lava flowing from the central crater complex had enlarged Crater 2 and created an oval lava mound with dimensions of 90 x 60 m. The overall dimensions of newly formed land were around 1,550 m E-W and 1,250 m N-S, and the highest elevation was 87 m.
Multiple near-daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
Multiple near-daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
The Tokyo VAAC reported an ash plume that rose to an altitude of about 3 km and drifted S.

Aerial observation conducted by JCG found that most of the lava mound identified on 26 August had become buried in a new pyroclastic cone that had formed to the north of it. A new row of three craters (vent 7) was found to the north of this new cone.
Lava was flowing northward from the new row of craters and covering much of the original island.

By the middle of October 2014 a large new area of lava flows had extended to the north and east well beyond the older part of the island, and lava flows were entering the sea over the entire northeastern quadrant of the island at many locations.
Strombolian eruptions with ejecta and ash plumes were observed coming from Crater 7 on the pyroclastic cone at the center of the island by JCG.
The height of the cone was measured at 96 m above sea level.
Strombolian eruptions with ejecta and ash plumes were observed coming from Crater 7 on the pyroclastic cone at the center of the island by JCG.
Aerial observations by the National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology (AIST) found a pyroclastic cone with a single clear conical crater at the summit.
At the crater, Strombolian eruptions were observed which produced a grayish-brown plume containing volcanic ash and ejecta.
At the crater, Strombolian eruptions were observed which produced a grayish-brown plume containing volcanic ash and ejecta.
Lava was observed flowing northward from the crater and then splitting into two directions that covered both the NW and NE coasts; white-vapor spouts formed where it entered the ocean.
Data from infrasound monitoring on Chichijima Island (134 km E) facilitated by the University of Tokyo's Earthquake Research Institute (ERI) showed an air shock starting on 13 November 2014.
According to Ogasawara Village Office, rumbling was heard on Chichijima Island (134 km E)  and a shock wave was also reported.
Aerial observation conducted by JCG revealed periodic eruptions at Crater 7, which was producing gray plumes and emitting ejecta.
Aerial observation conducted by JCG revealed periodic eruptions at Crater 7, which was producing gray plumes and emitting ejecta.
Aerial observation conducted by JCG revealed that lava was flowing to the NW and NE to the ocean. The extent of the island was about 1,710 m E-W and 1,830 m N-S, creating an area of around 2.29 km2.
Plumes were seen in aerial observation conducted by JCG.
