Through the morning of 31 December emissions consisted of gas and slight amounts of ash that drifted WSW.
MARN geoscientists estimated that the eruption deposits around the crater were about 50 cm thick. Ashfall deposits were observed in Santiago de Maria (1 mm), Placitas (5 mm) and San Jorge (2 mm).
Light-gray gas plumes rose 200 m and drifted SW.
Gas emissions were characterized by light gray plumes that rose 100-250 m above the crater and drifted S and SW.
White and light-gray plumes rising to 300 m were reported in February and March.

SNET reported that moderate-to-strong gas plumes rose from the crater and drifted SW. The biggest plume occurred at 1607 and rose 400 m. Images recorded by a webcam showed that the plumes had dark tones, suggesting small amounts of ash.
A plume, rising between 400 and 600 m was recorded with the thermal camera, but visual observations were obscured by weather conditions.
According to SNET, the Ministerio de Medio Ambiente y Recursos Naturales (MARN) reported that San Miguel emitted small amounts of ash.
According to SNET, the Ministerio de Medio Ambiente y Recursos Naturales (MARN) reported that ashfall, less than 1 mm thick, was observed in areas between the Parque de las Placitas and Placitas.

Activity was characterized by an increase in the frequency and magnitude of gas emissions, rumbling in the crater, and small explosions followed by juvenile ashfall.  On 19 May the webcam recorded periodic pulses of gray gas plumes that rose 300 m and drifted W. On 20 May seismicity remained high and gray emissions rose 300 m.
Between 2230 and 2300 less than 1 mm of ash fell to the WNW in San Jorge.
MARN reported that heavy rains caused lahars that originated from the upper part of the volcano and were heard by residents.
Locals observed gas plumes with occasional minor amounts of ash rising from the crater, especially after rainfall.
Ash emissions caused millimeter-scale ash deposits in areas 3 km N, NW and SW of the crater.
Ash emissions caused millimeter-scale ash deposits in areas 3 km N, NW and SW of the crater.
One mm of ashfall was reported on the N flank.
An inspection of the crater revealed strong degassing with plumes rising to 200 m and 2 cm of gray ash deposits.
A small explosion at 0941 sent ash to the WSW.
A small explosion at 0941 sent ash to the WSW.
One-mm-thick, dark-gray ash deposits were observed on the LACAYO farm, 4 km WSW.
At 1831 an ash cloud from a small explosion rose 400 m and drifted SW.
At 1831 an ash cloud from a small explosion rose 400 m and drifted SW.
Minutes after an explosion, local observers reported ashfall in the Cantons of La Morita (6 km SW) and Piedra Azul, and also in San Rafael Oriente (11 km SW).
At 1806 on a small ash-and-gas explosion occurred.
On 27 July a small ash-and-gas explosion occurred. A longer gas-and-ash explosion, lasting fifteen minutes occurred on 28 July at 0615.

On 27 July a small ash-and-gas explosion occurred. A longer gas-and-ash explosion, lasting fifteen minutes occurred on 28 July at 0615. Both the 27 and 28 July explosions produced plumes that rose between 300 and 500 m and drifted SW.
Local and Civil Protection of San Jorge observers reported millimeter depth ashfall from the two events in the cantons of La Morita, La Piedrita, and La Ceiba, located WSW of the crater.

Heavy rains generated two landslides along the creeks that flow down the SW and NE flanks of the volcano, causing damage to the small communities in the region, including San Jorge located 9 km WSW of the summit.

Heavy rains generated two landslides along the creeks that flow down the SW and NE flanks of the volcano, causing damage to the small communities in the region, including San Jorge located 9 km WSW of the summit.
Nine MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.

Strombolian activity at New Southeast Crater (NSEC) began in the evening, following 20 days of quiet. The next day, Strombolian explosions ejected incandescent pyroclastic material onto the cone flanks. The frequency and intensity of the explosions decreased early on 23 January. Weak Strombolian activity continued during 24-28 January, although on 25 January the amount of ash produced by the Strombolian activity increased. By evening on 26 January the intensity of the Strombolian activity as well as the amount of ash in the emissions decreased. INGV reported that on 28 January there was a gradual but steady decrease of activity. Weak and sporadic Strombolian explosions were detected at night, but then the thermal cameras recorded no anomalies associated with Strombolian activity.

Some explosions generated very small ash emissions that barely rose above the crater rim. On 23 January at 0105 a small puff of gas and/or ash from the E base of the cone heralded a new lava flow that traveled W towards the Valle del Bove. On 25 January the amount of ash produced by the Strombolian activity increased. On 26 January an ash plume drifted E. By evening the amount of ash in the emissions decreased.

Late in the day a small lava flow from the vent on the high E flank of the NSEC cone traveled a few hundred meters in a few hours. The lava flow stopped advancing on 23 January. At 0105 a small puff of gas and/or ash from the E base of the cone heralded a new lava flow that traveled W towards the Valle del Bove. Weak Strombolian activity and the advancing lava flow continued during 24-28 January. On 26 January The lava flow was 4 km long. Lava flows from two vents at the base of the NSEC cone continued to effuse at a very low rate on 28 January with a new lava flow advancing on top of the earlier one.
Multiple daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.

Late on 3 February 2014 observers noted that a lava flow remained active and was several hundred meters long. By 2000 on 4 February the lava flow had reached 1 km long. INGV reported that during 4-5 February there was a constant emission of lava from one or two vents at the E base of the NSEC cone. The lava flows reached the base of the W slope of the Valle del Bove on 5 February. During 9-11 February lava flows advanced. On 12 February lava continued to flow from the cone towards the Valle del Bove, and by nightfall had reached the base of the steep W wall of the valley, then advanced on the flat land to the N of Mount Centenarians. Activity during 14-15 February produced lava flows a few hundred meters long. During the afternoon of 15 February a small lava flow emerged from a new vent at the N base of the NSEC cone. The flow traveled 100 m towards the W wall of the Valle del Bove, and remained active the next day. Lava continued to flow from a vent on the lower part of the NSEC cone to the W wall of the Valle del Bove into March.

INGV reported that almost continuous ash emissions from NSEC began at about 1300 on 4 February and continued into the night; about 5-10 ash puffs were separated by steam emissions. Ash plumes drifted E. At 2000 the ash emissions ceased. During 4-5 February activity was characterized by intermittent ash emissions accompanied by jets of incandescent pyroclastic material, and a constant emission of lava.  On 6 February ash emissions ceased. Puffs of ash were observed on 8 February. Periodic ash emissions occurred during 9-11 February. At 0707 on 11 February a large quantity of reddish brown ash emitted from an area that collapsed near the vents. The unstable part of the lower E flank of the cone  continued to produce small collapses and reddish ash clouds the next day. At 1208 on 15 February an explosion generated a vapor-and-ash plume. During 16-17 February and through the end of the month Strombolian activity continued to produce small quantities of ash. The unstable part of the lower E flank of the cone that collapsed on 11 February continued to produce small collapses with reddish ash clouds through the end of February.

On 4 February after sunset, jets of hot material were observed rising 100 m above the crater rim. INGV reported that during 4-5 February activity was characterized by intermittent ash emissions accompanied by jets of incandescent pyroclastic material, and a constant emission of lava. On 6 February small Strombolian explosions ejected incandescent pyroclastic material 100 m above the crater. On 7 February Strombolian explosions ejected material onto the flanks of the cone. Strombolian activity continued throughout the rest of February.
At 1208 an explosion generated a vapor-and-ash plume, and was then followed by more explosions from the same area.
Multiple near-daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
A web camera photo near midday showed a dense black plume emerging from the crater.

At 0707 a large, dense, reddish-brown ash cloud discharged from a lower E-flank vent area. Rather than rising much distance, the ash-charged cloud moved rapidly downslope. The cloud consisted of a dense hot avalanche or landslide that INGV also said looked very much like a pyroclastic flow. The ash laden cloud took about a minute to reach the base of the W wall of the Valle del Bove only stopping after it encountered less steep terrain. After this event, reddish brown ash emissions continued. Shortly after reaching the level ground at the base of the W wall of the Valle del Bove, the flow stopped in an area about 3.5-4 km away from source vent. A cloud of ash rose up and drifted NE.

Strombolian activity and diffuse ash emissions continued to rise from one or two vents at the base of the NSEC cone. Activity intensified during 18-22 March, producing more ash, and then decreased and ceased during the night of 26-27 March, after 64 days of persistent activity.

Strombolian activity and diffuse ash emissions continued to rise from one or two vents at the base of the NSEC cone. An unstable part of the lower E flank of the cone that collapsed on 11 February continued to produce small collapses with reddish ash clouds. Activity intensified during 18-22 March, producing more ash, and then decreased. No ash was emitted on 23 March.

Lava continued to flow from a vent on the lower part of the NSEC cone to the W wall of the Valle del Bove, and during 2-3 March 2014 the flows reached the base of the wall. The lava flow fed by the vent on the inside of the unstable lower portion of the lower E flank remained active on 5 March. A second flow was fed a few hundred meters downslope , with an active front on the upper margin of the 2008-2009 lava field. After several days of lava emissions from a vent on the lower part of the NSEC cone, during 5-6 March lava flows originated only from a higher vent and traveled 1.5 km towards the lower part of the W wall of the Valle del Bove. During 14-24 March lava also flowed NE in the direction of Monte Simone. Lava emissions from the lower side of the NSEC significantly decreased during the last week of March; on the evening of 28 March a small lava flow continued to advance but had stopped and was cooling the next day.
Sporadic emissions of hot material with small amounts of volcanic ash originated from Bocca Nuova.
Sporadic emissions of hot material with small amounts of volcanic ash originated from Bocca Nuova.
INGV reported that during the night emissions of minor lava flows from the NE base of Etna's New Southeast Crater (NSEC) cone decreased. By 7 April the lava flows had ceased.
Strombolian activity gradually intensified during the evening and then decreased the next morning. By 7 April Strombolian activity had sharply declined. No activity was observed on 8 April.
Multiple daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.

INGV reported that during the morning of 22 April sporadic and weak Strombolian activity resumed at the New Southeast Crater (NSEC) and continued for the next few days. Explosions ejected incandescent pyroclastic material out of the crater and onto the upper S and SE flanks of the cone. Small collapses occurred on the cone's unstable E flank. The frequency and intensity of Strombolian explosions slightly increased late in the evening on 30 April. Weak Strombolian activity continued to be detected through 1 May. During the night of 2-3 May incandescence was caused by weak high-temperature gas emissions and/or Strombolian explosions. The activity intensified on 4 May and some of the explosions ejected incandescent pyroclastic material onto the high S and SE parts of the NSEC cone. Weak Strombolian activity continued through 10 June. Some explosions ejected incandescent pyroclastic material a few tens of meters above the crater rim that rarely fell onto the outer flanks.
A new eruptive episode began within the NSEC, beginning with near-continuous Strombolian explosions and lava fountaining and lasted for four days.
A new eruptive episode began within the NSEC, beginning with near-continuous Strombolian explosions and lava fountaining and lasted for four days.

On 14 June a new eruptive episode began within the NSEC. Fine ash emissions were concurrent with lava that began to overflow the SE edge of NSEC, forming a flow that continued downhill on the W wall of Valle del Bove. During the morning of 15 June the overflowing lava followed the fissure that had been formed on 28 November 2013. A spatter cone also formed in the E sector of the cone. During 14-15 June volcanic tremor increased sharply and remained at a medium-high level until 18 June when it returned to normal levels.
Multiple daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.

After images of a thermal anomaly in webcam images from Monte Cagliato, located on the E flank of Etna, a new, small fissure (tens of meters long) at the E base of the North East Crater (NEC) was observed by INGV Etna observatory personnel. The vent was located between 3,015 and 3,025 m elevation.

Weak spattering from the vent fed a lava flow that initially extended about 100 m. The lava flow diverged, and the longest of the two branches extended ~1.5 km, reaching the bottom of Valle del Leone.
Degassing increased and thermal anomalies were detected by a camera.
Weak and sporadic Strombolian explosions and small ash emissions were observed during 6-7 July, but by 11 July this activity had ceased.
Weak and sporadic Strombolian explosions and small ash emissions were observed during 6-7 July, but by 11 July this activity had ceased.
Activity from the new fissure included frequent Strombolian explosions that were audible in nearby towns.
Activity from the new fissure included frequent Strombolian explosions that were audible in nearby towns.

At about 1114 local time, a new eruptive vent opened near the 5 July eruptive fissure. This new vent ("25 July vent"), located at a distance of about 150-200 m to the N of the one from 5 July, was a source of Strombolian explosions, accompanied at times by modest quantities of ash. This activity continued through 31 July. The Strombolian explosions occurred at intervals of about 2-5 seconds and were often accompanied by visible compression waves ("flashing arcs") and audible rumblings up to a few tens of meters away, mostly in the E and NE sectors of the volcano.

About 1114 local time, a new eruptive vent opened near the 5 July eruptive fissure. This new vent ("25 July vent"), located at a distance of about 150-200 m to the N of the one from 5 July, was a source of Strombolian explosions, accompanied at times by modest quantities of ash. This activity continued through 31 July.
Bombs and scoria occasionally rose 200 m high and fell within a few hundred meter radius around the vent.

The lava flows, which reached about 1.8 km in length, (halting on the saddle between the Valle del Leone and the Valle del Bove), overlapped the earlier ones, with active fronts at least 1 km from the effusive vent.

From the 25 July vent, there began a gradual increase in the ash emissions that formed an ash plume, which rose to 1 km above the vent area. With the intensification of activity at the NSEC, the eruptive activity at the E flank of the NEC diminished.
Seismic data indicated an explosive eruption on 1 June, producing a large ash cloud about 127 by 93 km in dimension.
Ashfall was reported in Kozyrevsk village, 45 km W.
Two bright elongate thermal anomalies were seen in satellite imagery, possibly from pyroclastic flow deposits.
KVERT reported that earthquakes were detected in the vicinity of Bezymianny's lava dome.
VEI 2. I think it should be 3.

At 0807 an explosion sent an ash plume 1 km above the crater that then drifted NE. Later that day at 2058 a strong explosion (the strongest registered within the past 16 months) ejected incandescent material onto the flanks and ash plumes as high as 2 km.

At 0807 an explosion sent an ash plume 1 km above the crater that then drifted NE. Later that day at 2058 a strong explosion (the strongest registered within the past 16 months) ejected incandescent material onto the flanks and ash plumes as high as 2 km.
At 2058 a strong explosion (the strongest registered within the past 16 months) ejected incandescent material onto the flanks and ash plumes as high as 2 km.
Lava flows and rolling incandescent material traveled as far as 1.7 km down the flanks.
Explosions produced ash plumes that rose as high as 2 km above the crater.
Explosions produced ash plumes that rose as high as 2 km above the crater.

Based on webcam and satellite images, information from the Mexico City MWO, and wind data the Washington VAAC reported that ash plumes rose to altitudes of 4.1-7.6 km and drifted as far as 135 km in multiple directions. Remnant ash clouds were centered about 350 km SE on 20 January and about 185 km S on 22 January. Ash plumes were identified in satellite images at least 370 and 650 km NE of Colima on 25 and 27 January, respectively.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
The Unidad Estatal de Protecci¢n Civil de Colima reported that an explosion detected at 1602 was slightly stronger than a moderate level, and that winds were drifting SSE.
The Unidad Estatal de Protecci¢n Civil de Colima reported that at 0027 a moderate-to-large explosion ejected incandescent material as far as 2 km onto the W, SW, SE, and N flanks.
The Unidad Estatal de Protecci¢n Civil de Colima reported that at 0027 a moderate-to-large explosion ejected incandescent material as far as 2 km onto the W, SW, SE, and N flanks.
Explosions were recorded by the webcam and noted by the Jalisco Civil protection agency;
Ashfall was reported in Comala and Cuauhtmoc by the Jalisco Civil protection agency.
A strong thermal anomaly was identified in satellite images.

The Washington VAAC reported that on 1 February an ash emission was recorded by the webcam rising from Colima. Based on webcam and satellite images, the Mexico City MWO, and model data, the VAAC noted that during 3-6 February ash plumes rose to altitudes of 5.2-7.6 km and drifted NW, W, SW, and S. On 11 February an ash plume rose to an altitude of 4 km and drifted W. On 14 February an ash plume rose to an altitude of 5.2 km and drifted NE.
The Universidad de Colima reported that a large explosion was recorded at 1732, generating an ash plume that rose 6 km above the crater rim and drifted SSW.
The Universidad de Colima reported that a large explosion was recorded at 1732, generating an ash plume that rose 6 km above the crater rim and drifted SSW.
A small pyroclastic flow traveled down the E flank.
The Universidad de Colima reported that the internal crater was about 250 m in diameter and 50-60 m deep; previous lava domes had been destroyed in late September and mid-November 2016.

In late February scientists who visited the terminus of a 4.5-km-long pyroclastic flow that had been emplaced on 8 January observed that the flow was blocky with very little ash, and that the local vegetation had not been burnt, suggesting that the flow was low-temperature.
At 1823 an ash plume rose about 2 km above the crater and drifted SW.
Andersen reports ash venting from a remote camera on on nearby Verlaten Island.
Strombolian explosions were visible at the summit.
Lightning was visible in the ash plume near the summit (figure 119, BGVN 42:08).

CUEIV-UdC researcher Nick Varley observed a lava dome emerging from the floor of the crater during a helicopter overflight. It was estimated to be 25-30 m in diameter and 10 m high inside the almost 300-m-diameter, 50-m-deep summit crater. By 29 February, the dome had increased in size.
During the first week of April, scientists observed fresh ashfall covering the dome at the center of the crater,
An ash plume was observed moving ENE at 7.6 km altitude.

By the evening, the webcam showed intense activity and crater incandescence as lava spilled over the crater rim and flowed down the SW flank.The lava flow continued down the flank with incandescent rockfalls and occasional pyroclastic flows; by 4 October it had reached the base of the cone. By 8 October 2016, the lava flow was about 2,000 m long and 270 m wide at its front at the base of the cone.

On 26 November an ash plume rose to an altitude of 4.9 km and drifted 75 km W. The next day a gas plume with possible ash content rose to an altitude of 5.5 and drifted almost 20 km N. On 28 November an ash plume rose to an altitude of 5.2 km and drifted 13 km NE.
Effusive activity increased again at the very end of October 2016 with the growth of a new lava dome inside the summit crater.

By 17 November, a new lava flow was also visible on the S flank; it was reported to be about 500 m long by 20 November. Observations made on 5 December by UEPCC during a helicopter overflight indicated that the lava flow on the S flank was slowing its advance, and had reached about 1,700 m in length.
A new series of strong explosions with abundant ash emissions began and continued through the end of the month.
An ash plume rose to 7.3 km and extended about 185 km NE of the summit near Lago de Chapala before dissipating.
Ash clouds from multiple emissions were observed drifting W to WSW at altitudes from 6.1 to 7.9 km (about 4 km above the summit). These plumes were visible 370 km WSW of the summit the next day.
Ash plumes rose as high as 9.1 km altitude and spread N and NW.
Lightning was visible in the ash cloud.
A large ash plume rose to an altitude of 10.7 km and drifted NE.
Discolored water with gas bubbles and a sulfurous odor was observed during a planned swath mapping visit by the R/V Sonne.

Explosive eruptions took place as detected by T phase waves recorded at broadband seismic stations on Rarotonga (Cook Islands), Papeete (Tahiti), and the Marquesas Islands. Signals were also received at an International Monitoring System hydrophone array (maintained by the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty Organization) near Ascension Island, ~15,800 km from the seamount in the equatorial South Atlantic Ocean.
Watts et al. (2012) showed that there had been a depth change to the summit of 18.8 m between two surveys which was attributed to the growth of a cone or lava spine during the intervening eruption.

A second round of mapping by R/V Sonne on the return transit was accomplished, following the explosive activity. Watts et al. (2012) showed that there had been a depth change to the summit of 18.8 m between two surveys, which was attributed to the growth of a cone or lava spine during the intervening eruption.
There was an additional visual confirmation of activity in August 2011, and GeoNet stated that activity was continuing in September.
Seismicity indicated a period of significant activity, which was confirmed by discolored seawater in the area observed from an RNZAF flight on 3 June.

While the R/V Sonne was approaching the seamount scientists noticed a light yellowish water discoloration and a faint rumble. During profiling close to the summit the crew noticed that a "sudden and significant increase in volcanic activity with explosive hydroclastic eruptions was accompanied by thunder and shock waves rapidly spreading out on the water surface.

During profiling close to the summit the crew noticed that a "sudden and significant increase in volcanic activity with explosive hydroclastic eruptions was accompanied by thunder and shock waves rapidly spreading out on the water surface.
Pumice was collected in the vicinity, but the source volcano was not known.
Brad Scott observed that there had been eruptions detected during approximately 16-27 October, and 1-5 November based on T phase waves measured at Rarotonga.
Material was seen floating on the ocean surface over the seamount by a RNZAF airplane.
One or two anomalies every few days in MODVOLC.
A loud explosion at 2325 was followed by a few minutes of continuous roaring and rumbling.
A loud explosion at 2325 was followed by a few minutes of continuous roaring and rumbling.

Light gray ash emissions occurred at irregular intervals; the color of the plumes suggested mostly water vapor with low ash content. Plumes rose 200 m and drifted ESE on 20 January, and SW, S, and SSE on 21 January. Activity increased during 21-22 January with more frequent ash emissions occurring for extended periods. Emissions subsided in the afternoon of 22 January. A large explosion at 2147 produced an ash plume that rose 2 km and drifted SE and ESE. Ash plumes that rose from the crater on 23 January drifted SE.

Emissions subsided in the afternoon of 22 January but small-to-moderate explosions continued. A large explosion at 2147 ejected incandescent fragments, and produced an ash plume that rose 2 km and drifted SE and ESE. Explosions were heard through the night.
A large explosion at 2147 ejected incandescent fragments, and produced an ash plume that rose 2 km and drifted SE and ESE.

RVO reported that during 23-24 January, gray plumes rose 600 m above the crater following explosions.  Five explosions were detected between 0656 and 0859 on 24 January; these explosions produced light gray ash plumes that rose as high as 1 km above sea level. All plumes drifted E and ESE. On 24 and 25 January occasional light gray ash plumes rose from the crater and drifted E and SE. About five explosions occurred between 1947 on 26 January and 0414 on 27 January, producing plumes that drifted ESE. An explosion at 1000 on 27 January produced a dense, billowing, light gray ash plume that rose a few hundred meters above sea level and drifted ESE. Ash emissions continued until 1500, followed by white vapor emissions. Six explosions were detected overnight, possibly generating ash plumes that drifted E and ESE. At 1003 on 28 January an explosion produced a dense, billowing, gray ash plume; ash emissions continued from the next hour and then turned to white vapor. Two explosions occurred at 1323 and 1816, generating ash plumes and sub-continuous emissions for one hour and 15-20 minutes, respectively. Plumes again drifted E and ESE. On 29 January an explosion at 1723 generated a dense, billowing ash plume followed by a short period of sub-continuous emissions.

RVO reported that during 23-24 January following explosions gray plumes rose 600 m above the crater. Five explosions were detected between 0656 and 0859 on 24 January; these explosions produced light gray ash plumes that rose as high as 1 km above sea level. Several explosions were detected between 1630 on 24 January and 0232 on 25 January. About five explosions occurred between 1947 on 26 January and 0414 on 27 January, producing plumes that drifted ESE. An explosion at 1000 on 27 January produced a dense, billowing, light gray ash plume. Six explosions were detected overnight, possibly generating ash plumes that drifted E and ESE.  At 1003 on 28 January an explosion produced a dense, billowing, gray ash plume. Two explosions occurred at 1323 and 1816, generating ash plumes and sub-continuous emissions for one hour and 15-20 minutes, respectively. An explosion on 29 January at 1723 generated a dense, billowing ash plume followed by a short period of sub-continuous emissions.

RVO reported that occasional explosions produced light gray ash plumes that rose as high as 500 m above sea level and drifted E and ESE. At 1151 on 3 February an explosion produced a dense, dark ash plume that slowly rose 2 km above sea level and drifted ENE. Dark gray ash emissions continued for the next 15-20 minutes. During the afternoon of 3 February through the morning of 4 February light gray ash emissions rose at irregular intervals and drifted E and ESE. White vapor plumes rose from the crater in between the ash emissions.

RVO reported that occasional explosions produced light gray ash plumes that rose as high as 500 m above sea level and drifted E and ESE. At 1151 on 3 February an explosion produced a dense, dark ash plume that slowly rose 2 km above sea level and drifted ENE.

At 1151 an explosion produced a dense, dark ash plume that slowly rose 2 km above sea level and drifted ENE. Ash was observed falling on South Daughter (Turangunan, ~2 km to the E) and to the N of it.

RVO reported that during 4-5 February pale gray ash plumes rose from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone. On 5 February the ash plumes slowly rose 2 km and drifted E and ENE. On 6 February only white plumes rose from the crater during most of the day. In the evening a gray billowing ash cloud was followed by a sequence of "gentle puffs" of white to light gray ash emissions at irregular intervals into the night and through the morning of 7 February.
Fine ashfall was reported in Rabaul town (3-5 km NW) in the late evening.

RVO reported that ash emissions increased at Rabaul on 3 March and were mainly brownish. Emissions again increased the next day, occurring almost every minute. Billowing brown ash clouds slowly rose from the crater then quickly dispersed to the SE. The emissions decreased to about every hour on 7 March.
An explosion ejected tephra and a gray-to-black billowing ash plume rose 300 m and drifted SE.

An explosion ejected tephra and a gray-to-black billowing ash plume rose 300 m and drifted SE. The forcefulness and color lessened over at least the next 40 minutes; ash plumes rose 100 m, but were carried to 1 km with the wind. Seismicity remained low.
RVO reported that roaring and rumbling noises from Rabaul were heard during 1-14 April, especially at night.
White vapor plumes with ash rose at most 100 m above the main crater and drifted NW, causing ashfall in Rabaul town (3-5 km NW).
White vapor plumes with ash rose at most 100 m above the main crater and drifted NW, causing ashfall in Rabaul town (3-5 km NW).
RVO reported that white vapor plumes containing some ash rose at most 100 m from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone and drifted SE.

Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 4.6 km and drifted more than 35 km E. Satellite images later that day showed that the plume had dispersed.
RVO reported that white vapor plumes sometimes containing ash rose at most 200 m from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone and drifted SE and NW.
Ashfall was reported in areas downwind including Rabaul town (3-5 km NW).
RVO reported that white vapor plumes sometimes containing fine ash rose at most 800 m from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone and drifted NW and SE.
Photographers observed a 25-m-high lava dome on the crater floor on 12 June.
RVO reported that white-to-light-gray plumes sometimes containing fine ash rose at most 2 km from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone and drifted NW and SE.
Ashfall was reported in areas downwind including Rabaul town (3-5 km NW).
The lava dome on the crater floor of Tavurvur continued to glow; on 26 June and 4 July observers near the dome noted brief incandescence at the vent associated with strong and rapid venting.
Explosions generated dense gray ash clouds that drifted NW, causing ashfall between Namanula Hill (3 km W) and Malaguna No.1 (NW), and Pilapila and Tavui Point.
Explosions generated dense gray ash clouds that drifted NW, causing ashfall between Namanula Hill (3 km W) and Malaguna No.1 (NW), and Pilapila and Tavui Point.
Explosions generated dense gray ash clouds that drifted NW, causing ashfall between Namanula Hill (3 km W) and Malaguna No.1 (NW), and Pilapila and Tavui Point.

RVO reported that low-level activity consisted of discrete emissions of pale gray ash plumes occurring at short intervals. Some emissions were explosive and generated plumes that rose 2 km above the crater. Plumes drifted E, NE, N, NW, W, and SW, and deposited minor amounts of ash in areas downwind.
Some emissions were explosive and generated plumes that rose 2 km above the crater. Roaring and rumbling noises also continued, often in conjunction with explosions.

RVO reported that plumes drifted E, NE, N, NW, W, and SW, and deposited minor amounts of ash in areas downwind mainly between Nodup and Rapolo (with Rabaul Town, 3-5 km NW, in between), and to a lesser extent in the Vulcan area during 15-21 July and mainly between Namanula and Malaguna No. 1 (with Rabaul Town, 3-5 km NW, in between), and to a lesser extent between the Vulcan area and Malaguna No. 2 during 22-31 July.

Based on observations of satellite imagery and wind data analyses, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone rose to an altitude of 1.8 km and drifted almost 150 km NW.

Based on observations of satellite imagery and wind data analyses, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone rose to an altitude of 2.1 km and drifted almost 40 km NW.

RVO reported that during low-level activity at Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone consisted of pale gray plumes with variable but mostly minor ash content. Intervals between emissions ranged from tens of seconds to hours. Ash plumes rose as high as 1 km and drifted NW, causing ashfall mainly in a narrow band between the E part of old Rabaul town (3-5 km NW) and Namanula Hill, and further downwind towards Nonga area. Malaguna No. 1 and other parts of Rabaul town were also affected.

RVO reported that ash plumes rose as high as 1 km and drifted NW, causing ashfall mainly in a narrow band between the E part of old Rabaul town (3-5 km NW) and Namanula Hill, and further downwind towards Nonga area. Malaguna No. 1 and other parts of Rabaul town were also affected.

Emissions consisted of pale gray plumes with variable but mostly minor ash content. The interval time between emissions ranged from tens of seconds to tens of minutes. Plumes rose 50 m and were immediately blown NW by strong winds which re-suspended older ash deposits in widespread areas including Rabaul town.

RVO reported that  at 0516 on 13 November a moderate explosion generated a dense billowing ash cloud that rose 1 km above the crater and drifted NW. A few more explosions continued after that, at irregular intervals; notably on 14 November at 0738, 0851, 1308, 2044, and on 15 November at 1903.

At 0516 on 13 November a moderate explosion generated a dense billowing ash cloud that rose 1 km above the crater and drifted NW. A few more explosions continued after that, at irregular intervals; notably on 14 November at 0738, 0851, 1308, 2044, and on 15 November at 1903. Ash plumes from these events also drifted NW.
A few explosions generated ash plumes that rose to low altitudes (no more than 1 km) and drifted E, SE, and NW.
A few explosions during 15-18 November generated ash plumes that rose to low altitudes (no more than 1 km) and drifted E, SE, and NW.
Small amounts of fine-grained ash fell around Rabaul town (3-5 km NW).
White-to-light-gray emissions rose from the crater the remainder of the month.
An explosion at 1850 generated an ash-poor plume.
An explosion at 0732 generated an ash-poor plume.
Weak fluctuating glow was visible at night.
A pale gray/brown plume rose 50-100 m above the vent and dispersed.
RVO reported that explosions from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone were detected, notably during 1 and 6-11 March, and generated ash plumes that rose 1 km and drifted E and SE.

RVO reported that explosions from Rabaul caldera's Tavurvur cone during 1-11 March, notably during 1 and 6-11 March generated ash plumes that rose 1 km and drifted E and SE. Mild ash emissions on other days during 1-15 March also drifted E and SE.
The Darwin VAAC observed one ash plume. The plume rose to an altitude of 2,400 m and drifted 110 km NE and NW.
Based on a pilot report, analyses of satellite images, and information from the Guayaquil MWO, the Washington VAAC reported that a possible eruption before 1210 may have produced ash plumes.
A weak thermal anomaly was detected.
According to the Washington VAAC, on 22 February a pilot observed an ash plume that rose to an altitude of 7.6 km and drifted SW.
A MODVOLC thermal anomaly was detected.
A MODVOLC thermal alert was issued.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Washington VAAC reported that an ash plume drifted W.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery and a SIGMET aviation notice, the Washington VAAC reported that two brief ash emissions drifted SW and dissipated within 20 km.
A thermal anomaly was visible in infrared satellite images.
A MODVOLC thermal alert was issued each day.
Based on a pilot report, the Washington VAAC reported that an ash plume drifted W at an altitude of 7.6 km.
According to news reports, about 500 families evacuated and some local roads were impassable.
PHIVOLCS reported that an explosion from Bulusan's summit crater was accompanied by a rumbling sound audible up to 5 km away.
More than 350 persons lost their lives during a major eruption on November 5 that destroyed about 2300 homes and sent pyroclastic flows and surges to 15 km from the volcano.
One person was killed and another injured by secondary lahars.
Ash plume 7 km above the crater
Ashfall notable on snow near summit.
Lake Chala cryptotephra layer at least 70 km away.
Seismic data. Reported in INETER Dec 2010 Summary, ash is implied but not stated.
Seismic data. Reported in INETER Dec 2010 Summary, ash is implied but not stated.
Major Carlos C ceres, responsible for the Civil Defense of Chinandega, reported that the explosion occurred at approximately 02:30 in the morning.
Twenty minutes after the explosion the ash fell on the population. Ashfall reached the regional capital as well as the town of El Viejo to the NW.
A small explosion was reported at 06:38 in the morning, local time.
The explosion was reported by a commercial aircraft that encountered the ash cloud thirty minutes after the explosion.
Ash-bearing clouds emerged from a new vent.

The temperature of the thermal anomaly detected in satellite imagery increased from 18 degrees Celsius on 19 May to 48.8 degrees Celsius on 23 May. Intermittent thermal anomalies were ongoing and detected by satellite until 28 June 2010
Ash plumes rose ~8-10 km altitude and spread ~250 km W, ~160 km N and NE.
KVERT reported that a thermal anomaly over Bezymianny was observed in satellite imagery on 29 August and 1 September.
KVERT reported that, based on air photos taken of Bezymianny by helicopter on 21 November, a new area of lava possibly had extruded from the top of the lava dome.
Weak thermal anomaly was detected in satellite imagery on 3 and 7 December.
The temperature of thermal anomalies observed in satellite imagery during 23-24 and 27-28 December gradually increased.
A thermal anomaly over the volcano was observed daily in satellite imagery.
Gas and steam activity was observed during 30-31 January and 1-3 February.
Based on information from the Yelizovo Airport (UHPP), the Tokyo VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 4.6 km and drifted NE.
A thermal anomaly observed in satellite imagery was weak during 1-3 and 6 April, then increased in size and became more intense.
A strong explosive eruption began at 0820 and lasted for 40 minutes.
Ash fell in Krasny Yar (45 km to the NNW).
KVERT reported that the explosive eruption from Bezymianny also generated a viscous lava flow on the SE flank. Incandescence from the lava flow was visible on 19 April.
KVERT indicated that satellite imagery showed a thermal anomaly 15-22, and a bright thermal anomaly during 22-29 April.
A gas-and-steam plume drifted 27 km NW on 22 April. According to ground-based observations, gas-and-steam activity was noted during 22 and 24-25 April.
An observer in the area noted that lava continued to effuse on the SSE flank.
A thermal anomaly was observed in satellite imagery during 23-25 October

Seismic activity increased on 12 February and remained elevated. 7-19 weak events registered daily during 24 February - 2 March. About 40 seismic events were detected on 1 March. During 2-5 March there were 25-40 weak seismic events detected.

The size and brightness of a thermal anomaly observed in satellite images increased during 12-19 February and was visible daily after that. The size and brightness abruptly increased on 2 March, and continued to be observed on many days.
Blocks possibly extruded from the top of the lava dome.
Short volcanic tremor episodes were reported on 15, 22, and 29 February.
Intermittent gas-and-steam plumes, observed in satellite images, drifted NE.
KVERT reported that a strong explosive eruption was detected by seismic instruments.

Ash plumes rose to altitudes of 3.5-5 km and drifted NE. During the most intense phase of the eruption ash plumes from pyroclastic flows rose to an altitude of 8 km. Satellite imagery showed the plume drifting 700 km NE.

During the most intense phase of the eruption ash plumes from pyroclastic flows rose to an altitude of 8 km. According to visual observations during 15-16 March, the length of the 9 March 2012 pyroclastic deposits was ~4 km.
Ashfall was reported in Ust-Kamchatsk Village (120 km ENE).
A viscous lava flow effused onto the lava-dome flank accompanied by degassing, well into May.
Multiple daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.

KVERT reported that seismic activity at Bezymianny had increased in the middle of August. During 24-31 August levels were moderate; 17 events were recorded on 28 August and 71 events were recorded on 31 August.
A thermal anomaly was detected in satellite imagery on 25 August. A thermal anomaly observed in satellite imagery was very bright before the explosion on 2 September.
Based on seismic data analyses, an explosive eruption occurred from 0716 to 0745.

Ash plumes rose to altitudes of 10-12 km and drifted more than 1,500 km ENE. They rose to an altitude of 4 km and drifted NE later that day, then ash emissions ceased. They continued to be detected in satellite imagery and drifted 450-600 km ENE and SE.

A viscous lava flow effused on the lava-dome flank, and was accompanied by fumarolic activity. Collapse of the lava flow front caused hot avalanches through 4 October 2012. Activity described as effusive by KVERT continued through 17 August 2013, usually also noting that the activity was on the lava dome flank, fumarolic activity, and sometimes thermal anomalies. KVERT terminology changed to noting "moderate" rather than "effusive" activity on 22 August, but the description of the volcanism remained otherwise similar through 2013, including ongoing weak thermal anomalies over the lava dome when cloud cover allowed for satellite observations.

Ongoing weak thermal anomalies were reported by KVERT when the summit was not obscured by clouds. KVERT described "moderate activity of the volcano" from January through mid-June 2014, and "weak" activity for the rest of 2014 and all of 2015. This was characterized by weak or no seismicity, weak or moderate gas-and-steam emissions or fumarolic activity, and weak thermal anomalies observed from satellite data on the uncommon days that the volcano was not obscured by clouds. KVERT reported that weak volcanic activity continued into January 2016, with moderate gas-and-steam activity through 12 December 2016. Satellite data by KVERT showed a weak thermal anomaly over the volcano on most days.
During the first two weeks of May, video data revealed moderate-to-strong gas-and-steam emissions.

Seismic activity increased and 12 shallow seismic events were recorded. This was interpreted by KVERT as an extrusion of lava at the top of the dome. Shallow seismic events were recorded for approximately three weeks.

Seismic activity increased and 12 shallow seismic events were recorded. This was interpreted by KVERT as an extrusion of lava at the top of the dome. Shallow seismic events were recorded for approximately three weeks.
A visual inspection of the volcano revealed incandescence at the summit.
Moderate gas-and-steam activity was observed during the week ending on 23 January, 11-16 April, and from 16 July through 3 September 2015.
Based on information from the Yelizovo Airport (UHPP), the Tokyo VAAC reported that an ash plume from Bezymianny rose to an altitude of 3 km and drifted E.
Based on KBGS RAS (Kamchatka Branch of Geophysical Services, Russian Academy of Sciences) data, KVERT noted that seismicity at Bezymianny began to increase on 18 November.

The temperature of a thermal anomaly detected in satellite images increased on 5 December, and then significantly increased on 13 December, which was likely caused by lava-dome extrusion. Thermal anomalies were observed daily.

The temperature of a thermal anomaly detected in satellite images increased on 5 December, and then significantly increased on 13 December, which was likely caused by lava-dome extrusion. According to KVERT, lava-dome extrusion likely continued into January 2017.
A gas-and-steam plume containing a small amount of ash drifted about 118 km W. The Tokyo VAAC noted that ash plumes rose as high as 6.1 km that same day.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal anomalies were recorded.
KVERT reported strong gas-and-steam emissions at Bezymianny; a gas-and-steam plume drifted about 60 km SW on 18 December.
KVERT reported that the effusive eruption continued and that lava was flowing on the S flank of the lava dome.
KVERT reported that an explosive eruption at Bezymianny began at about 1330.

Based on webcam observations, at 1454 an ash plume rose to altitudes of 6-7 km and drifted 20 km NE. About 30 minutes later, at 1523, an ash plume rose to altitudes of 7-8 km and drifted 60 km NW. Satellite data showed a 14-km-wide ash plume at 7 km altitude. Later that day a 274-km-long ash plume identified in satellite images drifted NW at altitudes of 4-4.5 km; the majority of the leading part of the plume contained a significant amount of ash. Ash plumes drifted as far as 500 km NW.

A lava flow was observed that continued to travel down the NW flank of the lava dome. On 26 May KVERT reported that after an explosive eruption at Bezymianny on 9 March, and the effusion of several lava flows onto the dome flanks, the volcano became quiet.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal anomalies were recorded.
KVERT reported that the temperature of a thermal anomaly identified in satellite images had increased. Hot avalanches of material originated from the lava dome.

KVERT reported that the temperature of a thermal anomaly identified in satellite images had increased, and that the webcam recorded a gas-and-steam plume rising to an altitude of 4 km and drifting SSE.
A powerful explosion began at 1653 (local) that produced an ash cloud that rose to an altitude as high as 12 km and drifted 700 km E and SE.

A powerful explosion began at 1653 (local) that produced an ash cloud that rose to an altitude as high as 12 km and drifted 700 km E and SE. At 2110 (local) the ash cloud was 212 x 115 km in size and drifting E; the leading edge of the cloud was about 245 km E.

Nighttime incandescence from the lava dome was observed afterward a large explosion, and a lava flow emerged from the W flank of the dome. Active lava flows were reported on the W flank of the dome, and incandescence from the dome was usually visible at night through early October.
Strong gas-and-steam emissions and incandescence above the lava dome could be seen.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal anomalies were recorded.
Hot avalanches on the SE flank of the lava dome were recorded by a webcam.
A strong explosion that started at 1555 (local) generated ash plumes that rose to an altitude of 10-15 km.
A strong explosion that started at 1555 (local) generated ash plumes that rose to an altitude of 10-15 km. Ash plumes identified in satellite data drifted at least 320 km NE.
Moderate gas-and-steam emissions continued and a lava flow likely effused onto the N flank of the lava dome.
MIROVA data shows thermal anomaly spike around 20 December, decreasing into early February then dropping off significantly.
KVERT reports moderate gas and steam activity and thermal anomalies intermittently when summit is clear.
A strong explosive eruption at 1610 UTC resulted in an ash plume that rose to 10-11 km and drifted for about 870 km NW.
A strong explosive eruption at 1610 UTC resulted in an ash plume that rose to 10-11 km and drifted for about 870 km NW.

KVERT reported increased activity at Bezymianny characterized by nighttime crater incandescence, hot avalanches originating from the lava dome, and occasionally strong fumarolic activity. The hot avalanches were visible at night intermittently through mid-March. Late on 15 March KVERT reported that activity continued to intensify noting that the number of hot avalanches increased and ash plumes from the avalanches drifted about 100 km SE. KVERT reported that after the powerful explosive eruption on 15 March activity was characterized by growth of the W part of the lava dome. Beginning 15 March and continuing through May 2019, the number of hot avalanches from the lava dome top significantly increased. Incandescent lava dome growth with extruding, viscous lava flows accompanying strong fumarolic activity and thermal anomalies continued from late April to mid-July.
A KVERT report noted that the temperature of the thermal anomaly was gradually increasing, and increased again on 15 March.
Strong gas-and-steam emissions continued to be visible.
Ash plumes from incandescent avalanches drifted about 100 km SE.
Seismic data suggested that a powerful explosive eruption began at 0511 on 16 March. At 0530 webcam images recorded explosions generating ash plumes that rose as high as 15 km and drifted 10 km E.

At 0530 webcam images recorded explosions generating ash plumes that rose as high as 15 km and drifted 10 km E. Thirty minutes later satellite images indicated continuing ash emissions rising to 15 km. An ash plume, 79 x 65 km in dimension, was also identified drifting ENE.  Strong explosions continued to produce ash plumes at lower-altitude (5-6 km) that had a higher concentration of ash. The plumes drifted E. By 0930 ash plumes were rising to altitudes of 4-4.5; ash plumes drifted 100 km E. A large ash plume, 120 x 130 km in dimension, continued to drift E at an altitude of 15 km. By 1307 satellite images showed ash plumes drifting 650 km E. The Volcano Observatory Notice for Aviation (VONA) issued by KVERT for this event described ash clouds to a distance of about 870 km.
KVERT reported that ashfall was reported in Ust-Kamchatsk Village (120 km ENE) during 0650-0730. The report noted that ashfall was likely occurring in Nikolskoye (370 km ESE) on Bering Island.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal anomaly alerts were issued.
Moderate gas-and-steam emissions continued through November.
Infrared satellite imagery often showed thermal anomalies generated by lava flows or dome growth.

Activity began to increase at the beginning of December, characterized by nighttime crater incandescence, strong fumarolic emissions, a lava flow, and gradually increasing temperatures of a satellite-detected thermal anomaly.

Activity began to increase at the beginning of December, characterized by nighttime crater incandescence, strong fumarolic emissions, a lava flow, and gradually increasing temperatures of a satellite-detected thermal anomaly. A lava flow on the W flank of the lava dome was visible during 13-20 December.

Activity began to increase at the beginning of December, characterized by nighttime crater incandescence, strong fumarolic emissions, a lava flow, and gradually increasing temperatures of a satellite-detected thermal anomaly. On 1 January KVERT reported that activity had significantly declined during the previous week; the temperature of the thermal anomaly identified in satellite images decreased and nighttime lava-dome incandescence was no longer visible.
A single MODVOLC thermal alert was recorded.
Moderate gas-and-steam emissions continued frequently during the first seven months of 2020, in addition to a weaker, yet consistent, thermal anomaly over the lava dome.

KVERT reported that a new lava dome began growing in the summit crater around 26 August. Lava dome growth continued through mid-November, coincident with an increase in the strength and size of the thermal anomaly seen in Sentinel-2 thermal satellite imagery. The N flank of the lava dome was active and had possibly advanced during the first half of November.
Sentinel-2 thermal satellite images showed a strong and growing thermal anomaly over the lava dome from late August through October 2020.
Based on Tokyo VAAC notices, KVERT reported that an explosive eruption began at 0822 and produced a large ash cloud that rose as high as 9 km.

Based on Tokyo VAAC notices, KVERT reported that an explosive eruption began at 0822 and produced a large ash cloud that rose as high as 9 km. The ash cloud identified in satellite images was 100 x 200 km in size. By 1519 the eruption was over. A large ash cloud was still visible, though it had dropped to lower altitudes of 5-5.5 km and split into a N part (57 x 105 km) and a S part (36 x 67 km). The clouds shifted direction and drifted as far as 811 km NW and SE.
An active lava flow was observed on the N flank of the lava dome, accompanied by a strong anomaly seen in thermal satellite imagery.
A single MODVOLC thermal alert was issued.
Continuing gas-and-steam emissions and thermal anomalies were reported by KVERT from mid-November through the end of February 2021.
Sentinel-2 thermal satellite images showed a ring-shaped thermal anomaly over the lava dome at Bezymianny?s summit crater.
Occasional white gas and steam emissions were observed.
Weak and occasional ring-like thermal anomalies appeared in Sentinel-2 satellite imagery inside the summit crater.
Satellite and visual observations confirmed minor ashfall on the island.
Researchers camping on the island reported that a trace amount of ash was deposited on their tents from activity through the night.

Steam and gas plumes observed in satellite imagery on many days. Reports from researchers camped on the island, and imagery analyses, suggested that trace amounts of ash were intermittently present in the plumes during 23-26 May.
The Washington VAAC reported that a small cloud of ash mixed with a gas plume was observed in satellite imagery.

Observers working on a boat reported that a low-level ash eruption produced a diffuse, dark-colored ash-and-steam plume. The plume rose to an altitude of 1.5 km and caused minor ashfall on northern Pagan Island and the surrounding ocean. [Correction: further data analysis showed that the ash emission first reported on 15 August actually occurred on 11 August.]
Based on information from JMA, the Tokyo VAAC reported two possible eruptions during the early morning. The eruptions were characterized by gas and steam emissions lacking significant ash content.

Based on information from JMA, the Tokyo VAAC reported that an eruption that produced a plume that rose to an altitude of 1.2 km and drifted E. The eruption was characterized by gas and steam emissions lacking significant ash content.

Based on information from JMA, the Tokyo VAAC reported that an eruption produced a plume that rose to an altitude of 1.2 km and drifted E. The eruption was characterized by gas and steam emissions lacking significant ash content.
Gas and steam emissions rose 100-600 m above the crater rim.
Low seismicity centered just beneath summit crater; no tremor observed.
Dark emissions from the central crater, (BN and VOR), Bocca Nuova and Voragine, were seen a short time after the emissions from the SEC flank pit crater.
Mainly lithic ash fell at distances of up to 6 km from the volcano.
A small pyroclastic density current moved a few hundred meters to the NE from the pit.
Fallout of ash in the Rocca Campana area, between Milo and Fornazzo was noted after the emission from the central crater (BN and VOR).
Intense gas emissions were noted at the pit crater, but without ash emission.

INGV-OE reported a series of landslides from the NW rim of the pit crater located on the lower E side of the SEC. The collapses generated small ash clouds that drifted NE and changed the pit crater's morphology.
Data from a fixed thermal monitoring camera showed thermal anomalies over 180øC, indicating that the landslide material was hot.
A small explosion from the pit crater located at the E base of the Southeast Crater (SEC) widened the crater from ~40 m to ~80 m in diameter.
Small-amplitude tremor activity was accompanied by a plume that rose 400 m above the crater rim; a small amount of ash fell 400 m to the W of the fumarole within the crater.
The webcam on the S rim of the crater captured a grayish plume rising 300 m after a small explosion.
The webcam on the S rim of the crater captured a grayish plume rising 300 m after a small explosion.
Another small explosion produced a grayish-white plume that rose 100 m above the crater rim and resulted in minor ashfall NE in Kobayashi City.
A small explosion produced a grayish-white plume that rose 100 m above the crater rim and resulted in minor ashfall NE in Kobayashi City.
A small explosion produced a grayish-white plume that rose 100 m above the crater rim and resulted in minor ashfall NE in Kobayashi City.
Two explosions resulted in a small amount of ash deposited 10 km E of Shinmoedake.
Two explosions resulted in a small amount of ash deposited 10 km E of Shinmoedake.
A grayish-white plume, observed in the webcam, rose 100 m above the crater rim after an explosion, and a small low-temperature pyroclastic surge flowed 300 m down the SW slope.

A grayish-white plume, observed in the webcam, rose 100 m above the crater rim after an explosion, and a small low-temperature pyroclastic surge flowed 300 m down the SW slope. Based on reports from JMA, the Tokyo VAAC reported a plume that rose to an altitude of 1.8 km.
A grayish-white plume, observed in the webcam, rose 100 m above the crater rim after an explosion, and a small low-temperature pyroclastic surge flowed 300 m down the SW slope.

Lava erupted inside the main caldera from the pit crater (located in the NE part of the caldera) and also along an ENE-WSW-trending fracture in the S part of the caldera. By 3 January, the lava flow had traveled 4.6 km, was 15 m wide, and had burned about 10 hectares of forest. Lava continued to flow S and SW on 6 January, and had traveled 21 km to within 7 km of the road between Goma and Sake. Lava flows also emanated from the region of the spatter cone on the flank and ultimately branched and extended over a large area with the most distal flow front over 10 km from the vent. The main flows were 10.5-11 km long, and covered portions of the flow from the 2006 eruption. According to Karume and others (2010) and Smets and others (2010c), the eruption lasted until 27 January 2010.
Observers noted damage to crops, including green beans, sweet potatoes, cassava and banana groves from ashfall during the first week of the eruption.

Lava fountains reached higher than 300 m during the first days of the eruption. Beginning on 11 January, this height began to decrease irregularly to 50-150 m high.  The lava fountains from the flank fissure built a ~150-m-high spatter cone.

At the lower end of the flank fissure eruption, a volcanic cone grew that was reported by GVO to have been named "Kahinga Kabarinzi" by local people, meaning "customary keeper's cone." GVO reported that the cone emerged 3.2 km SSE of the summit, just to the W of one that erupted in 2000 and at a similar elevation.
According to Tedesco (2010), both tectonic earthquake (fracturing) and volcanic tremors (magma degassing) occurred simultaneously with the appearance of lava at the surface, not before.

OVDAS-SERNAGEOMIN reported that cameras installed around the Puyehue-Cord¢n Caulle volcanic complex recorded eruption plumes that rose no higher than 2 km above the Cord¢n Caulle rift zone and drifted N and NE. On 6 July satellite imagery indicated that the plume drifted 75 km NE. During 7-8 July explosions recorded by the seismic network corresponded to increases in the plume height. Based on analysis of satellite imagery, the Buenos Aires VAAC stated on 9 July that, although ash plumes rose to an altitude of 3 km, activity was weakening. Ash was again detected by satellite during periods of clear weather the next day.
OVDAS-SERNAGEOMIN reported that explosions recorded by the seismic network corresponded to increases in the plume height and caused windows in Ri¤inahue to vibrate.

OVDAS-SERNAGEOMIN reported that on 12 and 14 July cameras installed around the Puyehue-Cord¢n Caulle volcanic complex recorded eruption plumes that rose no higher than 2 km above the Cord¢n Caulle rift zone and drifted E. Seismic activity declined significantly. On 15 July satellite imagery showed a plume drifting 80 km E. A light gray plume on 17 July rose 2 km above the crater and was observed in satellite imagery drifting 240 km E. On 18 July a gray plume rose 5 km above the crater and drifted 150 km NW.

On 15 July satellite imagery indicated that lava started to flow again. The effusion rate increased on 16 July. On 18 July lava flows continued to be active. During 20-21 July seismic signals indicated active lava flows.
Incandescent material observed at night was ejected 500 m above the crater.

OVDAS-SERNAGEOMIN reported that on 20 July cameras installed around the Puyehue-Cord¢n Caulle volcanic complex recorded gray ash plumes that rose 3 km above the Cord¢n Caulle rift zone. Satellite imagery showed that the plume drifted 80 km E, becoming diffuse. Eruption plumes observed in satellite imagery on 22 July drifted 250 km E and SE. The next day plumes rose 1-2 km above the crater; satellite imagery detected plumes that drifted 100 km E and SE. On 25 July gray ash plumes rose as high as 2.5 km and drifted SE and satellite imagery detected the plume drifting 200 km SE.
Seismicity indicated that the lava flow remained active.

On 26 July the camera recorded a plume that rose 2 km above the crater and incandescence up to 500 m above the crater was observed at night. Satellite imagery showed a plume drifting 100 km SE. On 28 July a 150-km-long plume was observed in satellite imagery drifting SE. During 29-31 July plumes rose 2-5 km above the crater and satellite imagery showed plumes drifting 80-400 km SW, N, and NE.

During 3-4 August a video camera recorded plumes rising 2 km above the crater. Satellite imagery showed plumes drifting 1,000 km NE on 3 August and 700 km SE on 4 August.  On 6 August  satellite imagery detected a plume that drifted 250 km E then SE. Plumes that were mostly white rose no higher than 2.5 km above the crater during 7-8 August. Satellite imagery on 7 August detected plumes that drifted 100-200 km SE.

A diffuse plume detected in satellite imagery on 12 August drifted 150 km E. On 14 August a gray plume recorded by the camera rose 2 km above the crater, and satellite imagery showed a plume drifting 100-150 km E and SE. A mostly white plume was observed by an area camera rising 2 km above the crater on 16 August. A plume that was sometimes gray rose 2.5 km above the crater on 18 August. A plume observed in satellite imagery that same day drifted 200 km NW.

On 19 August a camera recorded a mostly white plume that rose 2 km above the crater. Satellite imagery showed a plume drifting 270 km NW. During an overflight, conducted by ONEMI in collaboration with the Air Force, scientists observed a white plume rising 1.4 km that was dark gray for the first few meters above the vent. On 20 August a plume that was mostly white rose 2.5 km above the crater. Two explosive events caused the plume to rise 4 km and contain a higher concentration of ash. Satellite imagery showed a plume drifting 200 km WNW on 20 August, and 500 km SE and NW on 21 August. A white plume that rose 2 km above the crater was observed on 22 August. Satellite imagery showed a very diffuse plume drifting E.
OVDAS-SERNAGEOMIN reported a predominantly white plume observed by an area camera that rose 1 km above the crater. The seismic network detected four explosions that caused the plume to turn gray.
A predominantly white plume observed by an area camera rose 1 km above the crater. The seismic network detected four explosions that caused the plume to turn gray.

Plumes detected in satellite imagery during 31 August-1 September drifted SE and SW. A plume observed by an area camera on 1 September rose 1 km above the crater. On 3 and 5 September plumes observed in satellite imagery drifted 30-80 km SE and E. Plumes detected in satellite imagery during 7-8, 10, and 12 September drifted 10-60 km NE, E, and SE. A plume observed by an area camera on 12 September rose less than 1 km above the crater. The next day a plume rose less than 4 km above the crater and was observed in satellite imagery drifting 35 km NE.

A plume was observed in satellite imagery drifting 60 km E on 14 September, and the next day, a plume observed by an area camera rose 4 km above the crater and drifted SE. Plumes observed in satellite imagery drifted 40-70 km N and NW during 18-20 September and rose 3-4 km above the crater. Plumes observed by an area camera rose 3-5 km above the crater during 21-23 and 25 September and were visible in satellite images drifted 30-300 km NE, E, and SE during 21-26 September.

Plumes visible in satellite images drifted 30-300 km NW, NE, E, and SE during 28 September-3 October and 30-60 km SE, SW, and N during 5-7 October. On 9 October a white plume observed with the camera rose 4 km above the crater. Satellite imagery that day showed a widely dispersed ash plume drifting E. On 10 October a plume that was mostly white, but occasionally gray, rose 3.5 km above the crater.

Plumes visible with an area web camera rose no higher than 4 km above the crater during 11-12 October. On 17 October a white plume rose 4.5 km above the crater and a diffuse ash plume observed in satellite imagery drifted 30 km SE. The next day, a white plume rose 3 km above the crater. Satellite imagery showed a plume drifting 50 km NE, and then later a diffuse ash plume drifting 200 km NE and SE. According to news articles, several domestic and international flights in Argentina, Brazil, Chile and Uruguay were cancelled on 16 October due to re-suspended ash. OVDAS-SERNAGEOMIN also noted that there was not an increase in volcanic activity, but high winds in the region. Plumes visible with an area web camera rose no higher than 2 km above the crater during 19-20 October. A small plume visible in satellite imagery on 19 October drifted 50 km E and a diffuse ash plume drifted 150 km NE and SE. On 20 October a small plume drifted 70 km E.
Incandescence emanated from the crater, possibly from active lava flows reported during the previous few days.
At 0311 an explosion generated a plume that rose 4.5 km above the crater as well as increased incandescence from the crater.

An ash plume observed in satellite imagery drifted 120 km W and NW, and a diffuse ash plume drifted 250 km NE and SE on 22 October. During the day a white plume rose 3 km above the crater. Satellite imagery showed a plume that drifted 125 km NE, then dissipated NE and SE. On 24 October, a plume rose 6 km above the crater. Satellite imagery showed a plume drifting 125 km NE and a diffuse ash plume drifting 280 km in the same direction. The next day white plumes did not rise higher than 7.5 km above the crater and satellite imagery showed a plume that drifted 100 km NW and SW.

During 26-29 October white plumes observed with an area web camera rose 4.5-5 km above the crater. Satellite imagery showed a plume drifting 30 km SW and W on 26 October, and diffuse ash plumes drifting E during 27-28 October. A plume observed in satellite imagery drifted 180 km N and NW on 29 October. On 30 October a mostly white plume rose 7.5 km above the crater and ash plumes observed in satellite imagery drifted 350 km NW and N. A mostly white plume rose as high as 6.5 km above the crater on 31 October and ash plumes observed in satellite imagery drifted 270 km S and SSW. On 1 November satellite imagery showed an ash plume that drifted 300 km SE.
Small incandescent explosions were observed at night.

A plume observed in satellite imagery drifted 180 km N and NW on 29 October, and ashfall was reported in Lonquimay. On 30 October a mostly white plume rose 7.5 km above the crater and ash plumes observed in satellite imagery drifted 350 km NW and N. Ashfall was reported in R¡o Bueno (80 km WNW).
Seismicity possibly indicated minor lava effusion.

During 3-6 November plumes observed with an area web camera rose 5 km above the crater, and satellite imagery showed active plumes drifting 30-120 km N, NE, E, and SE. Ash plumes dispersed as far as 300 km NE and SE. Area cameras showed a plume rising 2 km above the crater on 7 November. On 9 November satellite imagery showed an ash plume that drifted and dissipated to the E. During 11-12 November mostly gray plumes observed with the web camera rose 4-7 km above the crater. Satellite imagery showed ash plumes drifting 90 km NE on 11 November and 400 km SE on 12 November. On 13 November satellite imagery showed a plume drifting 250 km NE. A gray plume rose 6.5 km above the crater on 14 November. That same day a plume identified in satellite imagery drifted 200 km NW and ash clouds drifted from the SE to the NE.
During the night the crater was incandescent and small explosions were observed.
Ash fell in areas on the border of Chile and Argentina at Paso Samore.

On 16 November satellite imagery showed an ash plume drifting 100 km SW and sparse ashfall to the E. During 18-20 November plumes observed with the web camera rose 2.5-3 km above the crater. Satellite imagery showed ash clouds drifting E and SE on 18 November and an ash plume drifting 250 km SE on 19 November.

Satellite imagery showed a discontinuous ash plume drifting E and reaching the Atlantic Ocean on 24 November, and a fan-shaped ash plume spreading NE to SE on 25 November. Plumes observed with the web camera during 26-27 November rose 2.3-2.5 km above the crater. According to a news article, flights out of Uruguay were disrupted or cancelled on 26 November due to ash plumes. A plume observed in satellite imagery drifted 300 km E on 28 November.

During 1-3 and 5 December plumes observed with the web camera rose 1.5-3 km above the crater. On 1 December satellite imagery showed an ash plume drifting 90 km SSE with sparse ashfall to the W and NW and dissipated 100 km to the SE. Satellite imagery showed an ash plume drifting E and SE and reaching the Atlantic Ocean on 2 December. On 5 December satellite imagery showed a plume drifting 100 km NW. Plumes observed with the web camera during 8-9 December rose 3.0-3.5 km above the crater and plumes were identified in satellite imagery drifting 90 km SE on 8 December and 250 km ENE on 9 December.
Ashfall was reported to the E.

Plumes observed with the web camera during 14-15 December rose 2.4-2.5 km above the crater and satellite images showed ash plumes drifting 40-270 km SE, S, and NE during 14-18 December. Plumes observed with a web camera during 22-23 December rose 1-2.5 km above the crater and 5 km above the crater on 26 December. Satellite images showed ash plumes drifting 20-250 km E, SE, SW, NW, and NNE during 21-26 December.
Small incandescent explosions were observed at night.
Ash spread 140 km NW and 200 km NNW on 23 December, ash scattered 55 km SE on 25 December, and 100 km N and 200 km ESE on 26 December. On 28 December ash fell as far away Argentina, up to 580 km SE.
Small incandescent explosions were observed at night.

Plumes observed with a web camera during 28 December-3 January rose 1-5 km above the crater. Satellite images showed ash plumes drifting 20-80 km N, NNE, NE, and SE, dispersing ash to distances of 100-260 km. Plumes observed with a web camera rose 2 km above the crater on 6 January. Satellite images showed ash plumes drifting 50 km S on 6 January and 300-450 km SE during 8-9 January.

Plumes observed with a web camera during the week rose 1-4 km above the crater, and satellite images showed ash plumes drifting 60-300 km N, NE, and SE. According to a news article, an airport cancelled all flights in and out of Bariloche, Patagonia, on 16 January because of ash plumes. An airport in Melbourne, Australia, was also forced to close due to ash from these eruptions.

On 18, 20, and 22-23 January plumes observed with a web camera rose 2.5-7 km above the crater and on 18, 20, and 22-24 January satellite images showed ash plumes drifting 25-110 km NE, E, SE, and W. During 25-28 January plumes observed with a web camera rose 2-4 km above the crater and satellite images showed ash plumes drifting 90-320 km S and SE. During 1-7 February plumes observed with a web camera rose 1-4 km above the crater and satellite images showed ash plumes drifting 90-180 km NE, ENE, E, and SE. On 2 February a plume drifted 32 km NE and then dispersed 100 km N. During 8-11 and 13 February plumes observed with a web camera rose 1-3 km above the crater. Satellite images showed ash plumes drifting 20-90 km N, NE, ENE, E, ESE, and SSE during 8-13 February.

During 14-16 and 20-21 February plumes observed with a web camera rose 1 km above the crater. Satellite images showed ash plumes drifting 12-180 km NE, ENE, SE, and ESE during 14-15 and 18-21 February. During 23-24 February plumes observed with a web camera rose 1 km above the crater. Satellite images showed ash plumes drifting 60-100 km N and E during 22-23 February. During 28-29 February plumes observed with a web camera and satellite images rose 1 km above the crater and drifted 40 km NNE. During 2-3 March plumes rose 0.7-3 km above the crater and drifted SE.
SERNAGEOMIN and ONEMI scientists aboard an overflight reported that lava reached the valley of the Nilahue River, and two lava flows advanced to the N margin of the W crater.
SERNAGEOMIN and ONEMI scientists aboard an overflight reported that some areas were covered in pumice and gray ash deposits.

Plumes observed during 6-13 March in web camera and satellite images rose 0.3-1.2 km above the crater and drifted 30-50 km NNE, E, and SW.  Plumes observed during 13-16 March in web camera and satellite images rose 0.4-1.2 km above the crater, and drifted 30 km E on 14 March, 20 km N on 15 March, and 17 km NNE on 19 March. During 20-27 March plumes were sometimes observed rising no higher than 1 km above the crater.
Incandescence from the crater was observed during 5-8, 10-14, 16-20 and 23-27 March.

OVDAS-SERNAGEOMIN reported that during 27 March-3 April satellite and web camera observations of the Cord¢n Caulle rift zone showed plumes that rose no higher than 1.2 km above the crater. During 9-10 April satellite and web camera observations showed plumes that rose no higher than 450 m above the crater. During 11-17 April, satellite and web camera views showed plumes almost daily that rose no higher than 1 km above the crater.  During 17-22 April, satellite and web camera views  occasionally showed plumes that rose no higher than 400 m above the crater.
Incandescence from the crater was observed daily through 11 April and then during 17-18 and 20-21 April.

A scientist from NOAA's National Environmental Satellite, Data, and Information Service (NESDIS) reported that an ash cloud drifting NNE from the Cord¢n Caulle rift zone, part of the Puyehue-Cord¢n Caulle volcanic complex, was visible in satellite images starting at 0800. The scientist noted that, although it appeared to be a fresh emission, the cloud was likely re-suspended ash from strong southerly winds. In addition, no other evidence of renewed activity was detected.

Based on analyses of satellite images, the Buenos Aires VAAC reported that on 16 January steam-and-gas emissions with minor amounts of ash rose from the Cord¢n Caulle rift zone to an altitude of 2.4 km. The plume quickly dissipated and was determined to likely be resuspended ash from the 2011-2012 eruption.
Based on analyses of satellite images, the Buenos Aires VAAC reported that a diffuse plume possibly containing ash from the Cord¢n Caulle rift zone, was lifted from the surface by the wind.

MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued on 15 and 20 July 2011.

Based on a SIGMET report, the Washington VAAC reported a possible eruption and ash plume. A later notice stated that a pilot reported an ash plume at an altitude of 6.1 km.
A MODVOLC thermal alert was issued.

According to the Washington VAAC, a pilot observed an ash plume on 4 June that rose to an altitude of 7.9 km and drifted E. and an ash plume on 6 June that rose to an altitude of 6.1 km and drifted N. A pilot observed ash drifting E on 10 June.
