According to the USGS Earthquake Hazards Program, an earthquake swarm was detected during the evening of 12 June on the border of Ethiopia and Eritrea, in the vicinity of Nabro, the most prominent of three volcanoes with large summit calderas aligned in a NE-SW direction SW of Dubbi volcano. The swarm began at 1837 with an M 5.1 earthquake. Several more were detected between M 4.3 and 5.1 over the next few hours. Two M 5.7 earthquakes at depths of 10.1 km and 9.9 km were detected at 2332 on 12 June and 0003 on 13 June, respectively.

The eruption plume initially rose to altitudes of 9.1-13.7 km; it was later detected at altitudes of 6.1-10.7 km. Satellite images showed the plume drifting more than 1,000 km NW, over parts of Sudan. On 14 June a detached ash cloud was detected over southern Israel according to news articles. Revised plume heights published in subsequent papers determined plume altitudes above the 16-18 km tropopause and into the stratosphere.

According to the Eritrean Ministry of Information, ashfall covered hundreds of square meters. News articles stated that ash had covered a well-known mine that produces edible salt, and had contaminated food and water sources.
According to the Eritrean Ministry of Information, ashfall covered hundreds of kilometers and the government evacuated area residents.

Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Toulouse VAAC reported that plumes comprised mostly of water and sulfur dioxide rose to altitudes of 6.1-7.9 km. Ash was occasionally detected near the volcano. Satellite imagery posted on MODIS Web showed a dark brown ash plume fanning out to the SW on 19 June.
A satellite image showed a gas-and-ash plume rising from the caldera and drifting W.

Two satellite images showed the erupting vent, plumes and emissions, and lava flows in detail.   A dark ash plume rose from the vent, and at higher altitudes a plume composed of water vapor and sulfur dioxide drifted W and obscured the active lava flow.

Two satellite images show the erupting vent, plumes and emissions, and lava flows in detail. One false-color image highlighted hot areas throughout the lava flow and flow front, as well as hot material above the vent. A natural-color image showed fresh but cooled lava flows in the N part of the caldera.
Black ash deposits covered the landscape to the S and W.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Toulouse VAAC reported that plumes rose to altitudes up to 6.1 km.
A brown ash plume rose from the vent and drifted S.
Lava flows to the W, and within the crater (E and S of the vent), continued to be hot.

Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Toulouse VAAC reported that on 16 July an ash plume from Nabro rose to altitudes below 5.5 km. A weak eruption detected on 17 July decreased through the day then appeared to have stopped.
According to NASA's Earth Observatory, satellite images of Nabro acquired showed heat from the vent in the central crater, and from an area 1.3 km S of the vent that indicated an active lava flow.
A small and diffuse plume rose from the vent.

A region of seemingly thicker black ash (that completely covered the sparse vegetation) was noted S of the crater and thinner layers of ash (with some areas of visible vegetation) flanked either side of the region.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal alerts indicated an active lava flow.

Visitors  to the summit Mckel and Blank observed active spatter cones inside the N Crater. They reported that on the bottom of the active N Crater they saw fresh black natrocarbonatite lava and active vents, and they heard boiling noises from the bottom of the N Crater.
A group of conservation biologists heard a 'whoosh' from two boiling, rolling, lava pools that spilled pitch-black lava into a growing lake flowing E in the crater floor.
N crater floor showed an active vent, flows and spatter. Figures 161-163, BGVN 37:11.
Elias Danner filmed a vigorously boiling and splashing, obviously carbonatitic lava pool at the bottom of the pit of the N crater.
Abigail Church reported that she had flown over Lengai a few times in the last year or so, and that Lengai appeared to have small active vents still emitting lava.
Several flashes within the eruptive cloud.
A dense ash plume rose 10 km and exhibited lightning.
Brilliant white tracks of lightning were photographed at night (BGVN 36:08, figure 24).
Lava fountaining on 8 February 2010 reached 1,000 m above the crater; this activity was visible at night and lightning was observed within the ash plume.
Explosions produced ash, steam, and, at times, lightning within the plume.

At 1500 one large, continuous explosion occurred that lasted 36 minutes. Observers described a plume containing gas, steam, tephra, and small rocks. The largest ballistics did not reach farther than the crater rim and lightning was observed in the plume.
Abundant lightning was seen in photographs of the eruption plume (figures 1 and 2, BGVN 37:03).
Photo showing lightning from the plume by @hilmi_dzi (Twitter).
Ash plumes rose to an altitude of 7.6 km and drifted 200 km NW. Pilot reports through 1230 indicated that the ash plume had risen to an altitude of 9.1 km.
By 8 December about 90% of Bangaeira and 95% of Portela were overtaken by lava flows.
A single MODVOLC thermal alert was issued.
A new island is visible with a 0.8-km-diameter cone at its center in satellite imagery.
The first optical imagery of the eruption, reported by Xu et al. (2015), shows discolored seawater and a plume rising from the sea surface NW of Saba Island.
Height of 5 km above crater rim; highest since recording began in 2006.
Based on analysis of satellite images, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 9.8 km and drifted SE.
Second major explosion; est >20 km altitude plume

Chadwick, Merle, and Anderson (2016) noted "One of the most surprising discoveries during the cruise was finding glassy unsedimented lava flows on the 15.5øN segment, indicating that there had been a recent eruption on this segment." Chadwick and Resing (2016) reported that "The timing of the eruption can be constrained between multibeam sonar surveys on February 14, 2013, by R/V Melville, and December 1, 2015, when we resurveyed the site with the Falkor."
The Darwin VAAC reported that during 1 and 3-7 July ash plumes from Raung rose to altitudes of 3.7-6.1 km and drifted 25-110 km E, ESE, and SE.

A strong explosion was recorded by seismic instruments and observers within the National Park witnessed a blast of gas and ash from Santiago crater. INETER reported the explosion ejected a column of ash, gas, and blocks reaching 1,000 m above the summit and the initial explosion was followed by 24 smaller explosions that reached 500 m.
Due to the explosions, the Plaza de Oviedo, an overlook at the edge of Santiago crater, was covered with sand-sized pink and yellow ash and lapilli.
Due to the explosions, the Plaza de Oviedo, an overlook at the edge of Santiago crater, was covered with sand-sized pink and yellow ash and lapilli with some rocks up to 10 cm in diameter.
The explosion produced ash and volcanic bombs that fell across the NE-SE sectors including the flanks of Nindir¡ cone. The dimensions of the largest blocks were 60 x 50 x 40 cm.
OVSICORI-UNA reported one small phreatic eruption.
Largest of 10 small to moderate phreatic eruptions in October 2015.
Lava flows from Cerro Pomo are visible in satellite imagery

Small explosions were detected from the crater that released gas and ash. There were four explosions during 0725-1605; the largest occurred at 0725 and generated a plume 50 m above the crater rim. The other three explosions were less energetic and did not eject material beyond the crater.
The number of pyroclastic flows decreased substantially during November until 12 December 2010.
Seismic tremor duration and amplitude increased, and signals indicative of explosions were detected on 7 January. Multiple explosions were detected daily.
An ash plume rose to an altitude of 5.9 km and drifted NW.

A small pyroclastic flow seen from Tungurahua Observatory (OVT) in Guadalupe, 11 km N, descended the N and NNW flanks on 11 February and on 21 February small block avalanches on the N flank generated pyroclastic flows.
Lahars descended drainages to the W and NW, causing the road to Ba¤os to close.
Residents from two towns about 8 km NW were evacuated.
Intermittent lava fountains and explosions ejected incandescent blocks that fell onto and rolled down the flanks.
Roaring noises and incandescence from the crater were reported.
Seismic tremor duration and amplitude increased, and signals indicative of explosions were detected.
Pumice blocks fell in local neighborhoods (likely 6-8 km away).
Strong Strombolian activity renewed at the July 25 vent in the evening.
Multiple near-daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
Strombolian activity increased at NSEC and was accompanied by small emissions of black ash that remained within the crater. INGV reported that the eruption at NSEC ended on 15 August.
Strombolian activity increased at NSEC and was accompanied by small emissions of black ash that remained within the crater. Modest emissions of ash continued until 15 August.

At 0645 an effusive vent opened on the high E flank of the NSEC cone, which caused a small landslide and emitted a lava flow that after an hour had reached the E base of the cone. By 12 August two new branches were overlapping the earlier flow. The longest flow changed direction to later descend about 3 km NE toward Monte Simone. INGV reported that the eruption at NSEC had ended on 15 August and that the lava flow activity had ceased by 16 August.
During the first 24 hours of activity, a small pyroclastic cone in the W portion of the NSEC summit appeared, increasing the height of the NSEC structure that began to grow in 2011.

INGV reported that from the afternoon of 7 October through 16 October NSEC produced weak and intermittent explosive activity; small ash puffs were rapidly dispersed by the wind. During some nights small Strombolian explosions ejected incandescent material a few tens of meters above the crater rim.

INGV reported that from the afternoon of 7 October through 16 October NSEC produced weak and intermittent explosive activity; small ash puffs were rapidly dispersed by the wind. During some nights small Strombolian explosions ejected incandescent material a few tens of meters above the crater rim.
Multiple near-daily MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.

Starting at 1850 the NSEC produced a short but intense eruption characterized by lava fountains, lava flows, an ash plume that drifted E, and caused ash and lapilli fall in the nearby towns. Tremor began to decrease at 1930, and indicated that the eruption was over at 2100.
Starting at 1850 the NSEC produced a short but intense eruption characterized by lava fountains, lava flows, an ash plume that drifted E, and caused ash and lapilli fall in the nearby towns.

Starting at 1850 on 28 December the NSEC produced a short but intense eruption characterized by lava fountains, lava flows, an ash plume that drifted E, and ash and lapilli fall in the nearby towns. INGV indicated that this episode occurred at a series of eruptive vents along a NE-SW fissure that cut across the NSEC and the southern flank of the old SEC. From the two extremities of this fissure lava flows emerged, traveling SW toward the area of Milia-Galvarina and NE and E toward the northern part of the Valle del Bove near Monte Simone, reaching lengths of about 4.5 and 3.3 km, respectively.

Starting at 1850 the NSEC produced a short but intense eruption characterized by lava fountains, lava flows, an ash plume that drifted E, and caused ash and lapilli fall in the nearby towns. A day after the short but intense eruption, cameras viewing Etna recorded small ash emissions from NSEC.

Starting at 1850, NSEC produced a short but intense eruption characterized by lava fountains, lava flows, an ash plume, and caused ash and lapilli fall in the nearby towns of Milo, Fornazzo, Sant'Alfio, and Giarre.
A day after a short but intense eruption, cameras viewing Etna recorded persistent glow from the saddle between the SEC and NSEC cones at dusk.
Fifteen MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.
Incandescent material was observed as far as 3 km SE and E.
The village of Payang, about 4.6 km S of Sinabung's summit, was blanketed by ash.
Seismicity remained high, with constant tremor, hybrid earthquakes indicating a growing lava dome, and volcanic earthquakes.
Several villages in the Namanteran district reported ashfall.
Badan Nacional Penanggulangan Bencana (BNPB) reported that between 1200 and 1800 pyroclastic flows traveled 1.5 km down Sinabung's S flank.
The number of displaced people reached 28,715 (9,045 families) in 42 evacuation centers.

Based on webcam views, satellite images, ground reports, and altitude and drift directions derived from wind data, the Darwin VAAC reported that during 22-23 and 25-27 January ash plumes rose to an altitude 5.2 km and drifted 35-185 km N, NE, and E.

Incandescent material was observed 0.2-1.5 km SE of the vent.
Seismicity remained high, with constant tremor, hybrid earthquakes indicating a growing lava dome, and volcanic earthquakes.
An image of the S flank of Sinabung taken on 14 January 2014 shows lava flows erupting from the summit and traveling down the SE flank (figure 13, BGVN 39:01).

An eruption at 0847 on 3 October produced a dense ash plume that rose 4 km above the summit and drifted W and NW. Based on seismic data the event lasted six minutes. Events at 1044, 1112, and 1152 produced ash plumes that rose 2, 2.5, and 5 km above the crater rim, respectively. On 4 October ash plumes rose to an altitude of 4.6 km and drifted W.

An eruption began at 0102 on 16 December, though dark and foggy conditions prevented views of emissions; the event lasted for almost 10 minutes. When conditions improved about two hours later a dense ash plume was visible, rising 3 km above the summit and drifting SE. An event that began at 0540 produced dense gray-to-black ash plumes that rose as high as 7 km above the summit and drifted SE; the event lasted for 6 minutes and 10 seconds. Ash plumes from events at 0743 and 0857 rose as high as 7.5 km and drifted SW.
An eruption at 2120 on 14 July sent a plume to 7.6 km altitude (6.1 km above the summit) that drifted S.
Sinabung continued to effusively erupt viscous lava, further contributing to both the growth of the lava dome and the lava flow that descended the SE flank.
At 1030 a large dome collapse generated pyroclastic flows that traveled 4.5 km S.
Based on satellite data, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes rose as high as 9.1 km or just over 6 km above the crater rim.

Based on analyses of satellite, video, and model data, the Wellington VAAC reported that ash plumes rose 2.1-4.6 km and drifted NW, N, and NE, though a short-lived event generated ash plumes that rose as high as 9.1.
AVO reported that a short-lived explosive eruption, observed and reported by several pilots around 1600, produced an ash plume that rose to 10.3 km.
AVO reported that a short-lived explosive eruption, observed and reported by several pilots around 1600, produced an ash plume that rose to 10.3 km.
SVERT reported that an ash plume was visible in satellite images rising to an altitude of 8.8 km  and drifting 39 km N.
The Toulouse VAAC noted that a cloud observed in satellite images composed mainly of sulfur dioxide drifted over 220 km NW at an altitude of 9.1 km. Ash in the cloud was detected at lower altitudes.
An ash cloud rose 7 km and drifted for about 100 km NE.
At 0140 a strong explosion generated an ash plume that rose to altitudes of 8-9 km  and, by 1428, had drifted over 450 km SW.
At 0140 a strong explosion generated an ash plume that rose to altitudes of 8-9 km and, by 1428, had drifted over 450 km SW.

Strong explosions began at 0315, and generated ash plumes that rose as high as 10.5 km. The ash clouds lingered around Klyuchevskoy and surrounding volcanoes for about eight hours before gradually dissipating.

An eruption at Shindake Crater produced an ash plume that rose 4 km above the crater rim and drifted E, and a pyroclastic flow.

Average of 10 explosions recorded per day during 3-9 July, and the explosions were more energetic. Gas-and-ash plumes rose 5.5 km above the crater rim and drifted more than 50 km NW and S.
The Darwin VAAC observed a large ash plume on 4 December 2021 that reached 15.2 km altitude (11.6 km above the summit).
BNPB reported that an eruption began at 1447. Based on ground reports, the Darwin VAAC reported that a significant eruption generated a plume that rose to an altitude of 8.2 km.

Ash plumes rose to an altitude of 8.2 km and drifted W.
An ash plume from Sinabung rose to an altitude of 8.2 km and drifted N.

During 4-6 December ash plumes rose to altitudes of 3-3.7 km and drifted NW.  PVMBG reported that observers in Ndokum Siroga, about 8.5 km away, noted gray plumes rising 1 km above Sinabung on 6 December. Grayish-white plumes rose as high as 400 m on 7 December.
A few hours after 5.5-km-high plumes, an ash plume rose to an altitude of 11.6 km and drifted over 90 km NW.

Occasional medium-sized explosions and dome collapses produced pyroclastic flows that reached up to 3 km in length at 1350 on 3 February and at 0750 on 4 February.

Based on reports from PVMBG, BNPB reported that seismicity continued to be dominated by hybrid earthquakes, indicating pressure below the crater and a growing lava dome. Earthquakes associated with avalanches increased.

A 9 February report noted that the number of displaced people reached 32,351 (9,991 families) in 42 evacuation centers. Refugees from 17 villages outside the 5-km radius were allowed to return to their homes, starting with four villages during the first phase.

Based on webcam images, Indonesian Met office notices, wind data, and ground reports, the Darwin VAAC reported that during 12-13 and 15-18 February ash plumes rose to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifted 25-95 km N, NE, and E.

In the weeks prior to the eruption, there was rapid deformation at Skogaheidi (SKOG; S of the volcano) and Steinsholt (STE1 and STE2; N of the volcano). Scientists noticed a trend after 4 March at continuous GPS sites installed within 12 km of the eruptive site; all showed deformation at rates of up to a centimeter a day.

Seismic tremor began around 2230 on 4 March, and around that time, signal sources rose slowly towards the surface. Compared to the weeks prior to the eruption, seismicity increased rather slowly immediately prior to the eruption. However, as the eruption onset neared, geophysicists saw both the depth of earthquakes decrease and the locations of earthquakes move from the area under the summit towards the FimmvrÐuh ls site. During 19-20 March earthquakes migrated E and became more shallow, at 4-7 km depth. At 22:30 on 20 March seismicity slightly increased and, within the next two hours, reports of a volcanic eruption were received.
Initially detected visually, the eruption was seen at 2352 as a red cloud above the site.

Lava fountains were ejected from a 500-m-long NE-SW trending fissure on the NE flank of Eyjafjll at an elevation of about 1,000 m. The Institute of Earth Sciences reported that on 7 April the eruption from Eyjafjll ceased from the original eruption craters and was limited to the fissure that had opened on 31 March.
Prevailing E winds led to maximum scoria accumulation on a linear rim W of the NE-trending fissure. By 7 April, The largest scoria cone was 82 m high.

The Icelandic Met Office reported that around 1900 a new fissure at Eyjafjll opened NE of the first fissure that began erupting on 20 March. Activity from the second fissure was not preceded by detectable seismicity. According to a news article, the fissure was about 300 m long, and about 200 m away from the first fissure. The Institute of Earth Sciences reported that on 7 April the eruption from Eyjafjll ceased from the original eruption craters and was limited to the fissure that had opened on 31 March.

By 7 April, the tallest new cone reached an elevation 1,067 m, ~ 82 m above the previous ground surface. Another cone with a rim at 1,032 m elevation was 47 m above the previous surface and the vent area glowed red.
At 2300 a seismic swarm was detected below the central part of Eyjafjll, W of the previous eruption fissures.

An eruption plume rose at least 8 km above the glacier at the summit and remained active at that altitude for several days. E-blown ash began to arrive over mainland Europe closing airspace over the British Isles and large parts of Northern Europe on 15 April. Although on 19 April the plume was only rising 1 km above the summit, it was ascending to altitudes of 5-7 km as it drifted to the S.
Scientists conducting an overflight saw a new 2-km-long, N-S-trending fissure.
Scientists conducting an overflight saw ashfall to the E of the summit. Tephra-fall was reported in SE Iceland.
About 700 people were ordered to evacuate the area.
Tephra deposited next to the craters was 20-30 m thick.
NVC noted that activity had declined in the previous few days by an order of magnitude, though phreatomagmatic explosions were still occurring, sending plumes about 3 km high.

NVC noted that activity had declined in the previous few days by an order of magnitude, though phreatomagmatic explosions were still occurring, sending plumes about 3-5 km high, occasionally higher. On 23 April changes in the wind direction pushed the plume NW, causing airports in SW Iceland to close. Plumes drifted in different directions daily. A report on 2 May stated that during the previous 2-3 days ash plumes had become darker and wider than in the preceding week. On 3 May ash plumes were seen over the village of V¡k, 40 km SE. The eruption plume was seen in satellite imagery as far as 200 km from Eyjafjallajkull both days. On 4 May an eruption plume was seen in satellite imagery as far as 400 km ESE to SE. According to news articles, airports throughout Ireland were temporarily shut down on 4 May due to ash-plume hazards.

The emission of lava flows from the northernmost of two craters in the summit caldera likely began around 1200 evident by the onset of semi-continuous meltwater discharge, steaming from the N edge of the ice cauldron, and changes in tremor amplitude. On 23 April a depression in the ice, formed from lava flows that had advanced 400-500 m N of the crater, was 700 m long and steaming, especially at the edges. On 27 April the lava flow front had advanced 1 km N from the vents. On 28 April steam plumes rose above the lava that advanced N down the G¡gjjkull Glacier. On 2 May the location of the steam plume N of the crater indicated that the lava flow had advanced more than 3 km from the crater. On 4 May lava had traveled 4 km N from the crater. By 6 May the lava flow stopped advancing, and very little steam rose from the edges of the flow.

The Institute of Earth Sciences at the Nordic Volcanological Center (NVC) reported that during 5-22 May the eruption from Eyjafjallajkull continued to produce ash plumes from the summit vent. Based on analyses of imagery from weather satellites, scientific overflights, and pilot reports, ash plumes ranging in color from light gray to black rose to altitudes of 4-9 km and drifted ESE, SE, and S. According to news articles, ash plumes again caused flight disruptions in several European countries, including Scotland, Ireland, Spain, and Portugal. Plumes drifted W and SW during 14-15 May, and NW, NE and N on 18-20 May. Airports in parts of multiple European countries including England, Scotland, and Ireland were closed at times during 16-17 May. During 21-22 May light gray plumes with small amounts of ash rose to altitudes of 3-4 km.

Mild explosive activity ejected spatter 100 m above the crater and shockwaves were detected every few seconds on 24 April. On 27 April spatter was ejected 100-200 m above the vent. On 4 May lava was ejected a few hundred meters from the crater.

Minor ashfall was noted at two farms 10 km NW of the vents on 25 April. On 27 April light ashfall was noted in inhabited areas between 32 and 45 km W. On 28 April ashfall was seen on the W flanks and in an area about 32 km W. The next day ashfall was reported in areas 1.5 km SW and 12 km SSW. On 30 April ash was deposited in areas 10 km away. On 1 May ashfall was noted in areas 22 km SE. On 2 May ashfall was reported in an area 40 km SE. On 3 May ashfall was noted 65-70 km ESE. On 4 May ashfall was reported in areas 65-80 km ESE, cutting visibility to less than a few kilometers. Ashfall was reported in areas 55-70 km away during 5-8 May, and was "considerable" on 6 and 7 May. Ash was reported in a few areas within 12 km E and SSE during 9-10 May. During 12-18 May ashfall was reported in multiple areas, as far away as 40 km SE and SW, over 50 km SSE, and in Reykjav¡k 125 km NW. During 19-20 May ashfall was reported in areas to the S, NW, and N.
Explosions were heard at locations 10-15 km NW on 25 April. Booming sounds in the vicinity of the volcano were often heard during 28 April-4 May.

Radar data showed a tephra crater or cone continuously building on the N crater. The structure was approximately 150 m high and 200 m wide. The cinder cone in the summit crater continued to build and was near the level of the ice on the crater rim on 8 May.
Scientists saw that a new crater had formed in the SW part of the caldera; the rim was about 50 m lower than the surrounding ice surface.
A small ash explosion was seen by scientists visiting the crater.
Scientists measured the tephra deposits around the E half of the craters, and found that they were about 40 m thick closest to the craters.

Bonnie Betts climbed Lengai and is quoted as reporting: "... You could hear the lava sloshing around inside the crater before getting to the top; also dark smoke could be seen coming from the crater while ascending in the night . . . Looking into the crater, you can see the lava sloshing back and forth in the dark, black tunnel, and then some would flow out with a different flowing swishing sound."

Visitor Schachenmann noted sloshing lava sounds from the spatter cone and big cracks on the rim where gases escaped.
Ake Lindstrom observed activity in the crater and on the cracked terrain near the trail to the summit.

A research team visited the volcano. They observed lava fountaining, and cracks near the rim contained sloshing lava and emitted gases. They observed sporadic fountaining from the ~30 m high cone located on the NW side of the N crater. Fountaining lasted about 15 minutes between approximately 10-minute quiescent intervals.

Andersen reported that on 7 April, Krakatau started to produce small eruptions from the S part of the crater, the same side as the growing lava dome. Footage taken by Pierre Fortine showed no sign of any lava dome.
Oystein Anderson reported that the lava dome that people claimed to observe [through] February to April may have been destroyed during the last small eruptions that he reported in [early] April.

Andersen wrote that he had heard continuous booming noises half way from Java, and that large booming sounds could be heard in the villages of Carita and Anyar (or Anyer), neighboring villages on the W coast of Java, about 50 km ESE of the volcano.
As Andersen approached the volcano, he noted a high plume from the main vent and the ejection of lava bombs to heights of up to 300 m.

Strombolian activity started on 20 May and carried through to the end of the month. Tephra ejections rose to 25 m above the crater, and continuous explosions a few minutes apart that ejected bombs and generated rumbles, were heard 4 km away. An explosion on 30 May ejected ash and lapilli 200 m above the crater that was then deposited within 400 m of the crater.

Continuous explosions a few minutes apart ejected bombs and generated rumbles that were heard 4 km away. An explosion on 30 May ejected ash and lapilli 200 m above the crater that was then deposited within 400 m of the crater.
Strombolian activity was observed from MacKenney cone; weak-to-moderate explosions ejected small amounts of tephra 8 m above the crater that were then deposited on the W flank.

On 25 July weak explosions and incandescence from the cone were observed at night. Rumbling was heard. On 29 July incandescence from the crater was observed for a few hours in the morning, and a plume rose at most 100 m and drifted S. An eruption on 30 July included a high-energy phase that lasted for four hours and incandescent material that was ejected 250 m above the cone.

On 25 July weak explosions and incandescence from the cone were observed at night. Rumbling was heard. On 9 August seismicity increased, and Strombolian explosions ejected tephra 200 m above MacKenney Crater and onto the flanks, 400 m away from crater. The next day the number and magnitudes of explosions increased, and seismic signals indicating fluid movement were recorded. Tephra was again ejected 400 m away from MacKenney Crater, causing small avalanches of volcanic material on the flanks.
A Strombolian eruption occurred from 1915 to 2245, producing a 300-m-long lava flow that traveled W from MacKenney Crater.

Tremors and explosions of incandescent material continued through August and the first half of September ejecting material and sending small ash plumes a few kilometers above the cone. INSIVUMEH reported that on 26 August Strombolian explosions from Pacaya's MacKenney Crater ejected incandescent material 50 m above the crater. Seismicity remained high. During 26-27 August explosions were detected at intervals between 10 seconds and 4 minutes. Incandescent material was ejected 75 m high. During 10-11 September explosions at Pacaya generated diffuse ash plumes that rose 150 m and drifted 150 m NW. Explosions during 12-13 September ejected material 50-100 m high. Weak-to-moderate explosions generated rumbling during 14-15 September. An increased number of explosions were detected during 15-16 September. Material was ejected above the crater and ash plumes drifted 3 km W and SW.

INSIVUMEH reported increased activity on 5 December. A series of explosions at MacKenney Crater generated ash plumes that rose 2.7 km and drifted 3-5 km, and ejected pyroclastic material that was deposited around the cone. A mid-day report stated that 38 pyroclastic flows occurred during the first 12 hours of the day. An observer from the Kaliurang post saw 19 of those 38 flows travel 4 km S. Pyroclastic flows traveled down the SW flank.
A small ash plume caused a trace of ashfall in Runt£n (6 km NNE).
Three large explosions ejected incandescent blocks and expelled an ash plume, containing lightning, that rose to 12.2 km altitude (7.2 km above the summit).
Three large explosions ejected incandescent blocks.

Three large explosions expelled an ash plume that containing lightning. The Washington VAAC identified the plume in satellite imagery extending up to 140 km NW at 12.2 km altitude, and 110 km NE at a lower altitude of 7.9 km.
Three large explosions expelled an ash plume, containing lightning, that rose to 12.2 km altitude (7.2 km above the summit).
The soundwaves from the explosion reportedly broke the windows of the church of Cus£a.

Ashfall was reported up to 31 km NW, in Cotal¢ (8 km NW), Pondoa (8 km N), Runt£n, and Pillate (8 km W). Two pyroclastic flows traveled 3-4 km down the flanks and burned vegetation.
Explosions shook structures, were often heard by local residents, and generated ashfall in the neighboring communities for several days.
Strombolian explosions appeared at night; they peaked at over 500 m above the crater, sending blocks more than one kilometer down the W and NW flanks.

Instituto Geogr fico Nacional (IGN) reported an increase in the seismic activity. Hundreds of events were recorded each week, increasing in number. Over 9,000 events were recorded through early October.

The rates of both GPS deformation and seismic energy release had significantly increased during the second half of September. After an event on 8 October the trend of the superficial deformation changed, suggesting deflation of the system.

An increase of the activity could be observed over the submarine emission center, with large circles of light blue color on the sea surface, followed by foam rings and turbulent water with volcanic material. Close to sunset on 5 November, big bubbles rose to the sea surface and ejected sea water and volcanic material a few meters above the water.
Authorities evacuated about 80 residents from areas in Frontera due to landslide risks from seismic activity. Residents of La Restinga were also evacuated.
Many big steaming lava blocks (more than 1 m in diameter) were observed over the submarine emission center.
Minor gas and tephra content was observed in the water along with persistent discoloration.
Large steaming fragments of lava appeared intermittently floating over the emission center. A few hundred fragments could be observed floating, with mean dimensions between 0.5 and 2 m.
Lava balloons were sporadically observed floating on the sea.

Large lava fragments and fine material could be observed over the emission area on many days. Some of the frequent and persistent emissions of large steaming lava fragments observed on the sea surface were about 3 m wide.
Very few emissions of lava fragments were observed over the vent area.
Scientists aboard an overflight observed a white plume with some ash content that rose 1.5 km.

SERNAGEOMIN staff aboard an overflight observed mostly white plumes that rose above the two smaller craters. The larger, southern-most crater emitted a plume with a greater ash content that rose 5 km above the crater. Satellite imagery showed a plume drifting 12 km SE.
ONEMI reported that 128 people were evacuated from areas within a 45-km radius of the volcano. They noted on 30 October that the total number of evacuees had reached 140.
During an overflight scientists observed a gas plume with a very low ash content rise 3-4 km above the craters.
Scientists conducting an overflight noted that a gas plume with some ash rose 1 km above the craters and drifted 5-8 km NE.
During another observation flight, scientists saw plumes with minor ash rising 0.8 km from two of the three craters.
Scientists observed an explosion and an accompanying ash plume that rose 1.5 km above the active craters. They also noted subsequent minor explosions and ash emissions.

During 1-6 November between 16 and 110 earthquakes per day were recorded and satellite images showed drifting plumes daily. During 7-15 November, seismic activity decreased significantly, reaching a low level characterized by no more than four earthquakes per hour and the absence of tremor.
Analysis of ash deposited on the edge of the crater during the eruption indicated the presence of juvenile basalt.
The observers noted that the ground was covered by black pumice.
Lava fountains rose as high as 300 m above a cinder cone.
Lava fountains rose as high as 300 m above a cinder cone.
Reported as many as 66 events during 0722-0859.
Satellite images showed that the lava flow had traveled approximately 11.5 km during the six days of the eruption.

Virunga National Park reported that lava flows from the eruption along a fissure 11-12 km ENE of Nyamuragira's main crater had possibly stalled. An observer aboard an overflight a few days before noted that the lava did not appear to have moved any further N.
A photo taken from the Rumangabo headquarters (7.5 km NE of the eruption site) showed a tall cinder cone with lava fountains rising above the rim.
A photo taken from the Rumangabo headquarters (7.5 km NE of the eruption site) showed a tall cinder cone with lava fountains rising above the rim.

Satellite imagery acquired from the Advanced Land Imager (ALI) on NASA's EO-1 satellite showed an active lava flow to the NE of the central vent over the fissure located 11-12 km ENE of Nyamuragira's main crater.
The second cone was extremely active during the duration of the observations (about 15 hours) with fire fountains over twice the height of the cone.

The initial scoria cone appeared inactive and second cone formed to the N of the first cone. Both cones were about 300 m high. The observers, about 1.5 km away, felt the heat from the eruption as well as lapilli fall.

A Volcano Discovery Team observed the fissure eruption about 10 km E of the summit crater. Lava flows from the vent extended several kilometers N. Numerous small breakouts formed secondary flows, and a large breakout about 2 km N of the cone fed a large lava flow about 20 m wide.
A lava lake was present within the eastern cone during February 2012 through the end of the eruption in April 2012.

A report by Dario Tedesco stated that in March 2012, a series of explosion earthquakes were recorded by the seismic network of the Goma Volcano Observatory. Following this activity, the fissure eruptions suddenly stopped.
CVGHM raised the Alert Level from 2 to 3 (on a scale of 1-4) on 4 December based on seismicity and visual observations during 1-4 December.
Based on information from CVGHM, the Darwin VAAC reported that ash plumes from Gamalama rose to altitudes of 2.1-6.1 km and drifted E and SE.
Based on a SIGMET and information from the Ujung Pandang City MWO, the Darwin VAAC reported an ash plume from Gamalama rose to an altitude of 3 km and drifted 140 km S.
Ash fell in the Tubo district (3-4 km from the summit) and was remobilized by rain after an eruption.
According to the Jakarta Post, most residents living on Gamalama's slopes evacuated.
The Jakarta Post reported that up to 3,490 people were still being housed in ten different emergency shelters.
The Jakarta Globe reported that thousands of farmers had their crops destroyed by ash erupted during December 2011.
An explosion produced ashfall in nearby villages.
Two M 3 earthquakes occurred in the region.

According to local news, fishermen from the port city of Salif on the western Red Sea coast of Yemen reported an off shore eruption from the island of Jebel Zubair, about 60 km SW, with lava fountains rising 20-30 m above the summit.
MODIS imagery showed a plume rising from a submarine eruption about 1.5 km SW of Haycock and N of Rugged (near the N end of the Az-Zubair island group), and about 12 km NE of Jebel Zubair island.
The island had grown to about 530 x 710 m, and a gas-and-steam plume containing ash rose from a distinct cone.
High-resolution optical satellite image showed faint ash emissions.

Direct observation of the crater was made, and revealed incandescence in solfataras, a weak sulfur smell, and hissing sounds in both the N and S side of the crater.

OVSICORI-UNA reported that while conducting field work at Turrialba scientists observed incandescence with temperatures between 600-700 degrees Celsius from the three main vents of the W crater. The vents are comprised of the 2010 vent (on the SW rim), the 2011 vent (on the N side at the bottom of the crater), and the 2012 vent (on the SE flank).
Eruption and local area ashfall in areas to the SW. New vent suspected in main crater.
Eruption and local area ashfall in areas to the SW including areas near Iraz£ volcano (11 km SW). A new vent was suspected in main crater.
A dramatic increase in seismicity occurred, 155 seismic events were recorded.
Event frequency in early January 2012 showed a steady increase from 40 events per day reaching about 80-100 events per day.

After midnight residents of the Central Valley heard booming and crashing sounds. Investigators at OVSICORI-UNA reviewed the seismic records but did not find associated seismic or volcanic activity.
The seismogram showed strong tremor coincident with the tephra and gas emissions.
Two large steam-and-gas emissions (~90% water vapor) rose above the volcano. The two gas columns rose ~1 km in height and drifted towards the N face of the volcano.
A small phreatic eruption was noted.
Following an increase in seismic and degassing activity with vigorous steaming, there were occasional phreatic explosions that produced ash.

According to field surveys on 14 and 15 February, three major ejection sites were aligned in the N-S direction, the deepest being about 13 m. Mud was ejected to distances of up to 100 m NE of the main vent. No seismicity was observed to be associated with this event, but JMA believed a very small phreatic explosion probably occurred during early February.

A mud ejection occurred in the same area as previously, and mud was ejected up to 60 m WNW. During a field survey from 7 to 9 March 2012, additional mud ejections were noted from the same area as the previous events on the island's W side.

A very small phreatic eruption was noted, with tremor (90-minute duration) and intermittent ejections of steam plumes, mud, and small rocks. Emissions rose 20 m above the crater, and small amounts of ash rose more than 10 m and scattered within 20 m in every direction.
Volcanic tremor and intermittent earthquakes were recorded, and two apparently very small phreatic eruptions were reported.
Volcanic tremor and intermittent earthquakes were recorded, and two apparently very small phreatic eruptions were reported.
Volcanic tremor detected during 0623-0627 was followed by about an hour of numerous small seismic events.
Volcanic tremor detected during 0623-0627 was followed by about an hour of numerous small seismic events. Elevated seismic activity continued on 19 February.

A radar image (figure 5 BGVN 38:03) collected on 5 March 2012 shows an E-trending fissure crossing the S crater rim and continuing part way down the W flank. Total length of the fissure was estimated at ~600 m. It developed sometime after October 2011.
The Red Sismologica Nacional (RSN) reported two small eruptions when explosions were heard in Guachipelin (11 km SW) between 0400 and 0430, although these events were not recorded seismically.

Observers from nearby communities N of the volcano reported some sediment deposition along the outer N flanks of the main active crater and a white steam plume rising to a considerable height above the crater.

OVSICORI-UNA reported that a small phreatic eruption occurred within and around the hot acidic lake of Rincon de la Vieja at 1400.  The explosion generated a column of vapor and sediments visible from Buenos Aires and Aguas Claras de Upala, ~7 km N of the crater.
An eruption occurred at 1400 which was clearly recorded by the nearby seismic equipment.

INETER reported that at approximately 0500 volcanic tremor appeared in Masaya's seismic records. Tremor slowly increased to 70 RSAM. RSAM reached 100 units the next day with spectral analysis indicating frequencies oscillating between ~1.26 Hz and ~18.84 Hz. It continued at similar levels through 29 April. Tremor dramatically decreased early on 30 April before a significant explosion seven hours later.

A strong explosion was recorded by seismic instruments and observers within the National Park witnessed a blast of gas and ash from Santiago crater. The initial explosion was followed by 24 smaller explosions that reached 500 m.
Some of the clasts were incandescent.  Small brush fires were ignited on the N flank of the volcano due to hot blocks falling onto the dry plants.
Some of the clasts were incandescent and damaged the roofs of structures near the crater and also burned the asphalt of the plaza.
Ballistic ejecta covered an area with a 300 m radius to the SSE of the crater.  Blocks measured from this area had maximum dimensions of 50 x 40 x 30 cm.
Ash fell as far as 3 km to the SE of the crater. Ash fell to a thickness of 2 mm in some areas and INETER calculated a total volume of 736 cubic meters of ejecta.
At 0223 a small explosion was recorded by the INETER seismic network.

There were two small explosions at 0008 and 0022 with abundant gas and ash emissions on 3 May. On 4 May explosions of gas and light ash were observed. On 5 May ash and gas explosions were reported by National Park staff. Sporadic explosions continued until mid-May.

There were two small explosions at 0008 and 0022 with abundant gas and ash emissions on 3 May. On 4 May explosions of gas and light ash were observed. On 5 May ash and gas explosions were reported by National Park staff.
INETER staff observed two small explosions from the crater.

Officials from Parque Nacional Volc n Masaya (PNVM) conducted daily monitoring during much of June, reporting gray and white gas plumes rising generally 200-300 m above the crater, and occasionally as high as 600 m, with variable wind directions. CVGHM reported that a three-hour long ash eruption from Sirung was accompanied by loud sounds and incandescence that reached 10 m above the crater.

Ash was deposited on the NW flanks.
INGEOMINAS reported that seismicity at Galeras had increased in both magnitude and frequency since the previous week-long period, and indicated continuing ash and gas emissions.

On 5, 6, and 12-19 June cameras recorded gas-and-ash emissions; an ash plume rose 1.4 and 2.4 km above the crater on 14 and 17 June, respectively. During 19-22 and 24 June cameras recorded gas-and-ash emissions that drifted NW.
Ashfall was reported in Sandona (13 km NW), Samaniego (32 km NW), Mapachico (8 km NW), and Genoy (5 km NE).
Emissions, observed by a network of video cameras, contained some ash.
Gas emissions, observed by a network of video cameras, contained ash almost daily.

Observatory staff working near the crater reported a strong sulfur odor and fine ash falling on the upper N flank. Ashfall was also reported to the N in the Quebrada Maragato area (municipality of Nari¤o).
Ash emissions were observed in the morning, and at 1519 a seven-minute-long episode of tremor was accompanied by a gas-and-ash plume that rose 1.4 km above the crater and drifted N.
At 1519 a seven-minute-long episode of tremor was accompanied by a gas-and-ash plume that rose 1.4 km above the crater and drifted N.
Ashfall was reported in Genoy, 6 km NE.
During 7-9 and 11 August gas-and-ash plumes rose 0.9-1.3 km above the crater and drifted W and S.
An ash plume rose from the crater.
On 18, 24, 27, and 28 September the emissions contained ash.
INGEOMINAS reported that cameras around Galeras recorded daily emissions that drifted NW and often contained ash.

A gas-and-ash plume rose 1 km above the crater on 12 October, and on 19 and 21 October the plumes contained ash and rose 1.8 km above the crater. During 24-30 October cameras around Galeras recorded daily emissions, including pulsating ash emissions. Multiple gas-and-ash plumes rose 500 m above the crater on 25 and 27 October. Gas-and-ash plumes rose from the crater on 30 October and 1 November.
Observatory staff reported fine ashfall on the NE flank.

SGC noted a change in volcanic activity when tremor occurred associated with gas and ash emissions. Ash rose in small pulses and was deposited at high elevations on the edifice and toward the NW in prevailing winds.

SGC noted a change in volcanic activity when tremor occurred associated with gas and ash emissions. Ash rose in small pulses and was deposited at high elevations on the edifice and toward the NW in prevailing winds.
According to the Cruz Roja Departamento Nari¤o, ashfall was reported in Santa B rbara (~8 km NNW).

Gas-and-ash emissions were recorded by the network of video cameras during 1, 7, 14, 22-23, and 29-30 November. Plumes rose to less than 1 km above the summit and ash was deposited at the highest elevations, primarily within the N and W sectors.
Six gas-and-ash emissions were observed with plume heights less than 1.3 km on 17, 19, 21, 26, 27 and 29 December.
Ashfall occurred on the N and W sectors of the volcano.

Nine gas-and-ash plumes were detected with the video monitoring system. Plumes rose less than 1 km above the summit and deposited ash at the highest elevations within the N and W sectors of the edifice.
Civil Defense reported ashfall in the area of Sandon ; the timing of that ashfall event suggested a correlation with an episode of tremor detected at 1309.
Gas-and-ash plumes occurred throughout February 2013. During more than 10 of these events, plumes rose to less than 1.5 km above the summit.
A significant ash event occurred in the morning; Civil Defense reported ashfall in the region of San Isidro (~14 km NW).
The SGC reported gas-and-ash plumes throughout March; on five separate days (6, 7, 11, 22 and 25), the tallest plumes reached 1 km above the summit.
Cameras recorded ash emissions all week, especially on 9, 11, 12, and 14 April, when pulsating activity produced plumes that drifted W. Plumes rose no more than 1 km above the crater.

The first eruption occurred at 1702, an event characterized by explosions and multiple pyroclastic flows that traveled S about 8 km down the Gendol and Kuning drainages, and to some extent WSW down the Bedog drainage.

Traveling 8 km S, WSW, SE, CVGHM reported that multiple pyroclastic flows occurred until 1854, when the pyroclastic flow activity started to subside. Most of the pyroclastic flows lasted 2 to 9 minutes, except for two that lasted 33 minutes each.
According to the Darwin Volcanic Ash Advisory Center (VAAC), an ash plume rose to an altitude of 18.2 km.

According to a news article, ash fell in Yogyakarta, 30 km SSW.
An explosion began mid-morning with a low-frequency earthquake, and avalanches occurred.

A lava dome grew rapidly within Merapi's summit crater. Collapses from the S side of the dome fed minor pyroclastic flows that extended several hundred meters into the upper part of the Gendol valley.
Ash fell in Yogyakarta (30 km SSW), and residents in towns up to 240 km away reported that 'heavy gray ash' blanketed trees, cars, and roads.

Throughout the day, ashfall was heavy on Merapi's flanks, and was observed in surrounding areas including Selo (6 km NNW) and Magelang (26 km WNW). In Muntilan (18 km WSW) tephra and ash depths reached 4 cm.
Tephra fall, Muntilan (18 km WSW) reaching 4 cm depth

According to local geologists, this explosion was the most violent one at Merapi since the 1870's. They noted that, by some estimates, it was five times more intense than the one on 26 October 2010.
Flashes from the lava dome were reported from observations posts and incandescent material was ejected above the crater.
Incandescent avalanches traveled 2 km down multiple drainages to the SSE, S, and SSW.

Observations shortly after the 5 November eruption showed that the large lava dome of the previous week had been destroyed, and the summit crater had enlarged to a diameter of 300-400 m. However, by 6 November, another lava dome had grown, amassing, according to RADARSAT images 11 hours apart, at a rate of ~35 m3 per second. A new dome formed that was ~240 m in a NW-SE orientation, 140 m wide, and 40-50 m high.
Multiple ash plumes reported rising 3.7-18 km altitude.
About seven pyroclastic flows occurred, traveling SSE a maximum runout distance of 4 km, and in another case later that day, 9 km.
Lahars traveling S carried material up to 100 cm in diameter.

Lahars and high water damaged infrastructure and caused temporary road closures.

The major highway between Magelang and Yogyakarta was cut off when a 60 m wide section of blacktop was torn away by torrential mudflows along the eroded banks of the Putih river. As a result, hundreds of homes within 12 different villages near the river were inundated forcing 5,000 people to flee. There were three fatalities.

According to news articles a lahar traveled through the village of Sleman, approximately 20 km SW of Merapi, burying 21 homes in addition to vehicles and livestock. At least 200 residents were evacuated.

Several minor avalanches occurred, with noted incidents on 2, 7, and 15 August.

Ash plumes rose to 2.4 km altitude and drifted 65-75 km E.

Ash plumes rose to 2.4 km altitude and drifted 20 km E.
