Ashfall was reported in areas to the NW.
A cauliflower-shaped, dark gray ash plume rose about 1 km and drifted E.
Ashfall was reported in areas SE from Etna to Catania (27 km S).
The W wall of the BN-1 crater of Bocca Nuova collapsed
The western depression at the Bocca Nuova was the source of an explosive event that occurred at 1127 and generated a small ash emission.
The western depression at the Bocca Nuova was the source of an explosive event that occurred at 1127 and generated a small ash emission.
Ashfall was observed at the Rifugio Sapienza, on the high southern flank of the volcano at ~1,900 m.
On the morning of 14 November there was a significant increase in both the frequency and the volume of ash emissions.
Ashfall deposits were 1 cm thick on the crater rim.
A strong explosion from the W vent of Bocca Nuova crater at 0446 produced an ash plume that rose a few hundred meters above the summit and drifted NE.
An ash plume rose a few hundred meters above the summit and drifted NE after a strong explosion from the W vent of Bocca Nuova crater at 0446.
Minor ashfall affected areas as far as Linguaglossa (18 km NE).
Extremely small amounts of incandescent material emitted from the pit crater were observed.

During the late afternoon strong incandescence at the pit crater evolved into vigorous Strombolian activity. Frequent Strombolian explosions (1-3 per minute) ejected coarse-grained incandescent material a few tens of meters above the rim of the pit.
Weak emissions of incandescent material were observed.
Weak Strombolian activity from the pit crater gradually became more intense the next day.
Lava breached the E crater rim and traveled to the W wall of the Valle del Bove. They descended to about 1,630 m elevation (about 4.2 km from the vent).

The lava fountains were sustained initially and rose 300-500 m high, then pulsated and became less vigorous, and eventually formed one single jet that rose less than 100 m. Fountaining ceased at 0055 on 13 January.
Ash plumes drifted S causing ashfall.
Ashfall on Etna's S flank and in population centers such as Nicolosi.
Scoria fell in Rifugio Sapienza, at 1,910 m elevation during the night.
Collapses in the crater occurred, producing ash emissions.
Sporadic explosions within the crater generated ash emissions.
Gray-brown ash plumes were produced due to small landslides.
An explosive sequence, presumably from NEC, was detected during the late evening.
Strombolian activity was observed by a visible-light camera.
This eruptive episode lasted about 11 hours and produced pulsating lava fountains.
Lava flows traveled E, following the same path as that of the 12-13 January event, in the direction of the Valle del Bove.
Light ashfall occurred on the SW flank of the volcano.
An ash plume rose to an altitude of 2.4-3.4 km.
A series of gas-and-ash emissions, rarely with minor incandescent material, rose from the pit crater.
Strombolian activity detected from two vents located in the W portion of the crater.
Explosions were associated with Strombolian activity.
Explosive activity commenced from two vents before lava flows covered the crater floor.
A lava flow advanced from the base of the SE Crater cone toward the W headwall of the Valle del Bove, as far as 1 km.
Tremor amplitude significantly increased and culminated with vigorous lava fountaining.
Ashfall affected areas downwind to the SE.

The lava-flow emission rate increased dramatically. A second lava flow covered the first and traveled down into the Valle del Bove, essentially following the same path as the lava flows of 12-13 January and 18 February.
The lava flow encountered thick snow cover, leading to violent explosive interactions that generated pyroclastic flows, and resulted in spectacular vapor-and-ash plumes.
The lava flow encountered thick snow cover, leading to violent explosive interactions that generated pyroclastic flows, and resulted in spectacular vapor-and-ash plumes.
Incandescent bombs were ejected tens of m above the crater rim.
Strombolian activity observed at the pit crater on the E flank of the SE Crater.
Explosions were associated with Strombolian activity (continuing to 9 May 2011).
Lava overflowed the E crater rim.
Explosions occurred in the pit crater located on the E flank of Etna's SE Crater cone.
Strombolian eruptions were recorded by a camera.
Small pyroclastic cones began to grow on the crater floor.
Lava flow traveled to the upper W part of the Valle del Bove.
Explosions were associated with Strombolian eruptions.
Strombolian explosions turned into a continuous lava fountain.
A dense eruptive plume rose several kilometers high and drifted S and SE.

Ash and lapilli fell in populated areas including Trecastagni, Viagrande, and Acireale (SE), and between Nicolosi and Catania towards the S, forcing the closure of the Fontanarossa international airport in Catania.
A series of ash emissions from the pit crater located on the E flank of the SE Crater cone marked the resumption of explosive activity within the crater.
Strombolian activity increased and culminated into a new eruptive episode.

Lava flows traveled down the steep W slope of the Valle del Bove, following the same path as the lavas emitted during the preceding eruptive episodes, and stopped at the base near Monte Centenari. The largest lava flow descended the S flank of the cone reaching the base.
Lava fountains rose 200-250 m and produced heavy fallout of fluid spatter, forming several lava flows.
A dense plume of gas and ash drifted E.

Vigorous Strombolian activity started within the crater and gradually increased through the night. Strombolian activity gradually turned into a pulsating lava fountain, accompanied by increasingly voluminous ash emissions.
Plumes drifted E causing ashfall between the villages of Fornazzo and Milo on the flank (10 km E), and the Ionian coast near Riposto (18 km E).
A pulsating lava fountain was accompanied by increasingly voluminous ash emissions. The fountain fluctuated between 250 and 300 m above the crater with a few jets rising 350 m.
Lava flowed through a breach on the E crater rim and divided into multiple parallel flows that reached the base of the steep W slope of the Valle del Bove near Monte Centenari.
Ash fell between the villages of Fornazzo and Milo on the flank (10 km E), and the Ionian coast near Riposto (18 km E).
The final phase of the event was characterized by a series of violent explosions that produced loud detonations heard in the E and SE sectors of the volcano.
Strombolian explosions from the active vent on the E flank of Etna's SE Crater cone were weak and sporadic, then ceased during the night.
Sporadic explosions associated with Strombolian activity occurred at the E flank of the SE Crater cone.
Intermittent incandescence from the crater gradually intensified and became more frequent, then was followed by intense Strombolian activity accompanied by loud detonations.
Lava bombs ejected several tens of meters fell back into the crater or around the rim.
A diffuse ash plume drifted E.

A small lava flow on the E flank descended about 100 m then rapidly chilled. Later in the day lava flowed E and the effusion rate rapidly increased; lava flowed 3 km down the W slope of the Valle del Bove.
Ashfall was reported in the Ionian area (18 km E).

Strombolian activity intensified and incandescent jets became continuous. During the most intense period, fragments of fluid lava were ejected 450-500 m above the crater and fell onto the flanks of the pyroclastic cone to distances of 200-300 m. Lava fountains jetted from at least two vents located within the crater and on the upper E flank, roughly aligned WNW and ESE.
Weak Strombolian explosions occurred in the crater during the afternoon and gradually increased over the next few hours. The activity ended early the next day.
Explosions were associated with the Strombolian eruptions.
Lava flowed over the E rim of the crater and towards the W slope of the Valle del Bove.
An eruption plume laden with ash and lapilli rose a few kilometers above the crater and drifted SE.

Strombolian activity rapidly increased and formed a lava fountain that rose 100 m above the crater rim. Activity intensified and jets of lava rose several hundred meters high. At the climax of the eruption lava fountains exceeded 500 m in height.

Ash-and-lapilli fall were observed in the SE sector of the volcano, between Zafferana (10 km SE) and Viagrande (16 km SSE) and between Acitrezza (23 km SE) and Pozzillo (19 km SE) along the Ionian coast.
Initially sporadic ash emissions from Etna's New SE Crater produced small grayish-brown ash plumes. The next morninng Strombolian explosions produced dark ash clouds.

In the evening and throughout the night small Strombolian explosions were observed at intervals of a few tens of minutes. The next morning the Strombolian activity intensified and was accompanied by an increase in volcanic tremor amplitude.
Explosions were associated with the Strombolian eruptions.

Lava overflowed the E rim of the crater through a deep breach formed during previous eruptions. The lava descended the W slope of the Valle del Bove in numerous lobes; the most advanced lava fronts reached the base of the steep slope above Monte Centenari.
Strombolian activity rapidly intensified, and formed a pulsating lava fountain about 100 m tall.
Ejected bombs fell onto the cone surrounding the New SE Crater.
Ash- and lapilli-fall affected a relatively narrow area between Zafferana (10 km SE), and the coastal area between Giarre and Acireale, on the SE flank.

Lava overflowed the rim through a breach in the E crater rim traveling towards the Valle del Bove. The lower portion of the E flank of the NSEC cone began to slide and collapse under the push of lava from within the channel. A new lava flow issued from the collapsed area, taking a more southerly path than the lava emitted until then, and divided into numerous branches.

Dense plumes of gas and tephra rose 5-6 km from the crater and drifted SW, causing ash- and lapilli-fall in areas such as Patern (22 km SSW), Ragalna (13 km SSW), and Biancavilla (16 km SW). Closer to the crater, in the Torre del Filosofo area to the S, clasts up to several tens of centimeters in diameter landed on the ground.
A powerful explosion ejected incandescent bombs and produced a small ash plume.
Small-amplitude tremor activity was accompanied by a plume that rose 400 m above the crater rim; a small amount of ash fell 400 m to the W of the fumarole within the crater.
short but explosive event captured on video
The eruption began with discharge of diffuse white plumes, followed by pink-gray fumes with low ash content. Billowing gray clouds were accompanied by roaring and rumbling noises.
The series began with a few small hybrid earthquakes, followed by small low-frequency earthquakes, then continuous volcanic tremor starting at 1034.
After the eruption of 23-25 July, GPS data showed deflation of Tavurvur cone.
Event was "Partial collapse at end of eruption"
MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued on 29 and 31 July 2013.
A photo showed minor Strombolian activity at the inner crater.

When Google Earth imagery from 14 March 2011 created by Maxar Technologies is compared with imagery from 29 July 2013 captured by Landsat/Copernicus, dark tephra is filling the inner crater in the 2013 image; it was not present in 2011 (figure 12, BGVN 45:09).

When Google Earth imagery from 14 March 2011 created by Maxar Technologies is compared with imagery from 29 July 2013 captured by Landsat/Copernicus, dark tephra is filling the inner crater in the 2013 image; it was not present in 2011 (figure 12, BGVN 45:09).
RVO reported that emissions from the summit crater were gray during 17-31 August 2013. Emissions were more energetic on 24 August, rising 200 m.
RVO reported that a single booming noise and weak incandescence was reported.
RVO reported that small volumes of white vapor and gray and gray-brown ash plumes rose 100 m above the crater and drifted S.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifted 30 km NW.
RVO reported that small volumes of gray to gray-brown ash plumes rose 100 m from the crater on most days and drifted S.
Ashfall was reported in Navo on the SW flank.
Pale gray ash plumes rose from the crater.
People between Sena Estate and Noau on the N flank reported ashfall in early December.
RVO reported that diffuse ash plumes rose from the crater.

Based on seismic data from the Kamchatka Branch of Geophysical Services (KBGS; Russian Academy of Sciences), KVERT reported that a Strombolian eruption began at 1830, and continued to be reported each week.
Multiple MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued most days.
A large thermal anomaly from the lava dome was detected in satellite images.

A lava flow effused onto the SW flank, producing a thermal anomaly detected in satellite images. On 14 September, KVERT noted four lava flows on the NW, W, and SW flanks. Ongoing flow activity was reported through 30 October. Satellite images continued to detect thermal anomalies over the summit and the lava flow on the SW flank as late as 27 December that were attributed to cooling flows.
KVERT reported that a strong explosion from a new cinder cone low on Kliuchevskoi?s SW flank occurred between 2020 and 2030.
KVERT reported that a strong explosion from a new cinder cone low on Kliuchevskoi?s SW flank occurred between 2020 and 2030.
An ash plume rose to altitudes of 6-7 km and drifted E.

Ash plumes rose to altitudes of 7-8 km and drifted 140 km SSW. Phreatic explosions on the SW flank generated ash plumes that rose 3-4 km. Satellite images showed an ash plume rising to an altitude of 7.5 km at 1419 and drifting 103 km SSW. Activity increased again; ash plumes rose to altitudes of 9 km at 1655 and 10 km afterwards. Ash plumes drifted SSW and S. That evening ash plumes rose 8 km and drifted ENE.

At 0815 satellite images detected ash plumes that rose to altitudes of 2-3 km and drifted 480 km NNW. Seismic data indicated that ash plumes rose to an altitude of 10 km later in the morning. Clouds prevented direct observations but satellite images showed ash plumes drifting NW. At 1624 satellite images showed ash plumes drifting WSW at altitudes of 7-7.5 km.

Ash plumes rose to altitudes of 8-9 km and drifted 20-100 km SE.  At 0559 on 19 October ash plumes observed in satellite images drifted 630 km SE at altitudes of 8-9 km. Ash plume altitudes fluctuated between 7-8 km later that day. A large amount of ash continued to drift 600 km SE.

KVERT reported that at 1235 an ash plume from Kliuchevskoi, detected in satellite images, rose to an altitude of 6.5 km and drifted 160 km NE. At 1322 an ash plume rose to an altitude of 7 km and drifted 130 km NE.
At 1416 seismicity indicated a strong explosion, and observers reported that ash plumes rose to altitudes of 10-12 km and drifted SE.

At 1416 seismicity indicated a strong explosion, and observers reported that ash plumes rose to altitudes of 10-12 km and drifted SE. Later that day the altitudes of the ash plumes were lower; video images showed ash plumes rising to altitudes of 5-5.5 km and drifting NE.
On 3 December KVERT noted that since 19 November ash-plume altitudes had been decreasing. Gas-and-steam plumes containing small amounts of ash were visible drifting 90 km SE on 25 November.

During this period video images showed ash plumes rising to altitudes of 5-6 km. Satellite images detected ash plumes that drifted 1,200 km E during 6-8 December, NW during 9-10 December, and E and SE during 10-11 December.
The last strong explosion was detected.
Phreatic explosions on the SW flank generated ash plumes that rose 3-4 km.
Minor ashfall was reported in Mayskoe Village.
Video data showed a high-intensity explosion and Strombolian activity.
Satellite remote sensing detected a thermal anomaly over the volcano caused by the continuation of the flank eruption.
Satellite images recorded a daily thermal anomaly on the volcano.
Satellite images detected a weak thermal anomaly over the summit and the SW flank.
CVGHM reported that observers at a post 6 km away reported that diffuse fumarolic emissions from the crater were visible during the mornings.
Seismicity fluctuated during the month, but 81 shallow volcanic earthquakes were detected between 1606 and 1741 on 19 August, compared to a total of 30 the previous 18 days.

At 0714 an eruption from the submarine SE flank vent, Hobal, ejected dense white plumes 2 km high that drifted S. Incandescence at sea level was observed at 0746, and the water around the eruption site turned yellow.
CVGHM reported that observers at a post 6 km away from Iliwerung reported that diffuse fumarolic emissions from the crater were visible during the mornings.

IGP reported an increase in the seismic energy liberated from about 24-58 megajoules during 1-3 July to 74 megajoules before decreasing to 37 on 5 July. It remained between 5 and 22 megajoules through 15 July 2013.

IGP reported nine phreatic explosions from Ubinas. The series of explosions decreased in both energy and length of the tremor signal associated with each explosion. Most of the explosions generated ash plumes that rose 1.5-2 km above the crater.  The first explosion occurred at 2246 on 1 September, lasted 110 seconds, ejected ballistics up to 2 m in diameter, and caused ashfall 2 km ENE. The second explosion, at 1552 on 2 September, lasted 292 seconds and ejected fewer ballistics. Details for the 3rd through the 6th explosions are as follows: the 3rd occurred at 2350 on 2 September and lasted 279 seconds; the 4th occurred at 0809 on 3 September and lasted 296 seconds; the 5th occurred at 1021 on 3 September and lasted 288 seconds; the 6th occurred at 1029 on 3 September and lasted 74 seconds.  The seventh phreatic explosion occurred just after 1800 on 4 September. The eighth explosion occurred on 5 September and lasted 321 seconds, and the ninth explosions occurred on 7 September.

IGP reported nine phreatic explosions from Ubinas. The series of explosions decreased in both energy and length of the tremor signal associated with each explosion; tremor lasted 75 minutes for the first explosion and 5-10 minutes for later explosions.
The first explosion at 2246 on 1 September ejected ballistics up to 2 m in diameter. The second explosion, at 1552 on 2 September ejected fewer ballistics.
The first explosion occurred at 2246, lasted 110 seconds, ejected ballistics up to 2 m in diameter, and caused ashfall 2 km ENE.
IGP reported that a 2-minute-long non-explosive seismic signal indicated gas-and-ash emissions at Ubinas.
IGP reported that a 2-minute-long non-explosive seismic signal indicated gas-and-ash emissions at Ubinas.
IGP reported that two earthquake swarms at Ubinas were detected: the first during 8-9 January and the second on 25 January. Seismicity increased again during 30-31 January.

Activity picked up in January 2014 with an abrupt increase in the number of LP (long-period) seismic events to 44 in the first days of January and an increase in "tornillo"-type seismic events with an emission on 23 January.
IGP-OVS reported that ash plumes rose to 2 km above the crater (7.6 km altitude) and drifted E and SE.
The towns of Querapi and Ubinas (4-6 km SE) received very light ashfall.
IGP reported that a phreatic explosion occurred at 1445 and generated a water vapor, gas, and ash plume that rose 1 km above the crater.
IGP reported that a phreatic explosion occurred at 1445 and generated a water vapor, gas, and ash plume that rose 1 km above the crater.

Volcanologists visited the crater during 1-2 March and observed a new 30-40 m elongated body of incandescent lava emitting bluish gas. On another visit on 19 March 2014, the lava was photographed covering the 120 m wide crater floor. Seismic signals detected during 20-21 and 23 March indicated increased lava emissions.
A MODVOLC thermal alert was issued.

Buenos Aires VAAC reports of ash emissions increased significantly in March 2014, with reports of emissions on 13 different days. Diffuse plumes were repeatedly observed drifting in many directions up to 1.7 km above the crater.
Ashfall was reported on 25, 27, and 31 March in nearby villages including Ubinas, Querapi, and Tonohaya (7 km SSE).
Nearly continuous explosive activity characterized events during April 2014, with tens of explosions reported daily and increasing amounts of energy released from seismic events.

Early in the month ash plumes were rising almost daily 2-3 km above the volcano, but the height increased to 4.5 km by 15 April and then 5 km above the crater (10.6 km altitude) in the largest explosion on 19 April.
Seven MODVOLC thermal alerts were issued.

Ashfall occurred in local communities many times in April. The towns of Ubinas and Querapi (4-6 km SE) reported ash every week. During the largest explosions from 15-22 April, ash in Querapi was reported up to 1 mm thick, and a trace was recorded in Ubinas. Ash also fell in multiple areas in almost all directions, but was most concentrated to the SE, S, and SW; additional towns affected included Escacha (7 km SE), Tonohaya (8 km SE), San Miguel (10 km SE), Huatagua (14 km SE), Matalaque (17 km SE), Chojata (19 km ESE), Omate, (37 km SSW) and even Quinistaquillas (44 km S).

On 18 April a significant gas-and-ash emission was accompanied by the ejection of incandescent bombs that landed up to 2 km from the crater. Explosions on 19 and 22 April also ejected incandescent tephra, 20-30 cm in diameter, up to 2.5 km away from the crater.
According to a news article, an evacuation of 4,000 residents was underway, along with nearly 30,000 livestock.

During 7-8 April explosions ejected incandescent fragments, up to 20 cm in diameter, up to 1 km away. On 13 April a significant explosion occurred that possibly removed the body of recently erupted lava on the crater floor; incandescent tephra was ejected from the crater. On 14 April an explosion ejected incandescent tephra from the crater that was deposited on the W flank.

Explosions on 30 April and 1 May generated ash plumes that rose 0.2-3 km above the crater and drifted in multiple directions, especially to the S, SE, E, and NE. An explosion at 1902 on 14 May ejected fragments around the crater and caused thick ashfall in Chojata and Escacha. A moderate explosion at 1915 on 18 May was followed by nine hours of continuous emissions.

Explosions during 30 April-1 May generated ash plumes that rose 0.2-3 km above the crater and drifted in multiple directions, especially to the S, SE, E, and NE. IGP's Observatorio Volcanologico de Arequipa (IGP-OVA) and Observatorio Vulcanol¢gico del INGEMMET (OVI) reported that during 7-12 May gas-and-ash plumes, sometimes with only minor amounts of ash, rose 0.6-3 km above the crater. On 14 May emissions with minor amounts of ash rose 0.6-1.8 km above the crater. Water vapor and ash plumes rose 0.7-3.5 km on 15 May, and gas, steam, and ash plumes rose 500-800 m on 16 May. A moderate explosion at 1915 on 18 May was followed by nine hours of continuous emissions. Later that day gas-and-ash plumes rose 0.4-1.1 km. During 21-23 and 25-27 May gas-and-ash plumes rose 0.7-3.8 km above the crater and drifted W, N, E, and SE. During 28-29 May gas-and-ash plumes rose 0.6-2.5 km above the crater and drifted ESE.

Ash fell every week of May in Querapi, Ubinas, Chojata, Escacha, Anascapa, San Miguel, Tonohaya and Lloque. On 4 May minor amounts of ash fell throughout the Ubinas valley, more than 15 km away. Significant ashfall was reported in Santa Rosa de Phara on 8 May. An explosion at 1902 on 14 May caused thick ashfall in Chojata and Escacha.
An explosion at 1902 on ejected fragments around the crater.

Satellite and webcam images as well as pilot observations during 1-3 June 2014 indicated continuous emission of gas and ash that rose to altitudes of 6.7-10.7 km and drifted NE, E, and SE. Gas-and-ash plumes observed during 5-7 June rose 0.2-2 km above the crater. In a 12 June press release, IGP's Observatorio Volcanologico de Arequipa (IGP-OVA) reported that periods of intense tremor mainly associated with ash emissions continued to be detected. An IGP update on 17 June noted a small explosion at 1335 that day that sent ash 1,800 m above the crater, to an altitude of about 7,400 m. Two explosions were noted on 18 June, as were six gas-and-ash emissions that generated diffuse plumes 400-700 m above the summit. On 19 June gas-and-ash emissions were observed nine times, reaching 300-1,200 m above the crater. On 20 June seven gas-and-ash emissions were observed (200-500 m above the crater) with the webcamera. On 21 June gas-and-ash plumes were seen nine times to heights of 500-1,200 m above the crater. On 22 June the webcamera captured views of eight gas-and-ash plumes that reached 300-1,000 m above the crater. On 23 June six gas-and-ash plumes were observed with plume heights as high as 1,300 m above the crater. The Buenos Aires VAAC reported that during 25-28 June there was continuous steam and possible ash emission. In a press release from 30 June, IGP noted minimal releases of ash and gas emissions had been observed during the previous days. Gas-and-ash plumes observed on 30 June rose 1.8 km above the crater.
Residents of Querapi and Tonohaya remained evacuated.

Minor ashfall was reported in Lloque and Yungas during 6-7 June. In a 12 June press release, IGP's Observatorio Volcanologico de Arequipa (IGP-OVA) reported that ashfall affected areas within 6 km E and SSW. On 18 June, ashfall was reported in Querapi. On 19 June ashfall was reported in the areas of Querapi, Ubinas, Escacha, Tonohaya, and San Miguel. On 21 June, light ashfall was reported in the towns of Ubinas, Lloque, and Yunga. On 30 June minor ashfall was reported SE.

In a 12 June 2014 press release, IGP's Observatorio Volcanologico de Arequipa (IGP-OVA) reported that activity had decreased since April, however periods of intense tremor mainly associated with ash emissions continued to be detected. Volcanic tremor was associated with ash emissions during 12-21, 25, and 26 June. After more than 50 hours of tremor, a moderate explosion occurred at 0858 on 30 June.

During 12-30 June six explosions generated plumes 1,400-3,600 m above the crater. An IGP update on 17 June noted a small explosion at 1335 that sent ash 1,800 m above the crater. Two explosions were noted on 18 June. On 19 June the seismic network detected two explosions. On 21 June, six explosions were recorded. Seismicity on 22 June included one explosion signature. After more than 50 hours of tremor, a moderate explosion occurred at 0858 on 30 June.
A moderate explosion generated an incandescent plume that reached 1,800 m above the crater and ejected tephra 1,500 m down the NW flank.

During 30 June-10 July IGP detected five, small-sized explosions that generated plumes 400-1,500 m above the crater. An explosion on 17 July, preceded by several days of banded tremor, generated an eruption column that rose 5 km above the summit and expelled incandescent blocks onto the flanks. More explosions on 19 and 21 produced eruption columns of gas-and-ash.

During 30 June-10 July 2014 IGP detected five, small-sized explosions that generated plumes 400-1,500 m above the crater. During 16-22 July INGEMMET and IGP reported gas-and-ash emissions most days. An explosion on 17 July, preceded by several days of banded tremor, generated an eruption column that rose 5 km above the summit and expelled incandescent blocks onto the flanks. More explosions on 19 and 21 produced eruption columns of gas-and-ash; the column on 19 July rose 2.8 km above the summit. Emissions and exhalations on 16, 18, and 22 July of gas-and-ash rose to 200-1,800 m above the summit. Eruption columns and emissions drifted mostly E, NE, and SE. On 23 July the Buenos Aires VAAC reported a weak emission of light ash. On 23-24 July mild gas-and-ash emissions rose 200-550 m above the summit and drifted E and NE. On 25 July minor gas and ash emissions drifted E.  On 30 July INGEMMET reported steam-and-gas plumes that rose 500-1100 m above the summit. On 31 July INGEMMET reported an eruption column rose to 3 km and drifted NW. On 31 July the Buenos Aires VAAC reported continuous emission of light ash.
An explosion, preceded by several days of banded tremor, generated an eruption column that rose 5 km above the summit and expelled incandescent blocks onto the flanks.

Ashfall was reported in various towns downwind of the plumes, in the areas of Querapi (4 km S), Ubinas (6.5 km SSE), Tonohaya (7 km SSE), San Miguel (10 km SE), Escacha, Yalahua, Lloque, and Sacuhaya.

On 1 and 3 August gas-and-ash emissions rose 200-1,200 m above the crater and drifted W. During 3-5 August the Buenos Aires VAAC reported continuous emission of light ash. On 6-7 August gas-and-minor ash emissions rose 300-1,200 m above the crater and drifted NE and S. On 6 August Buenos Aires VAAC reported intermittent diffuse volcanic ash and emission puffs to 6.7 km; they reported continuous emissions of gases and light ash on 7 August. During 20-25 August water vapor, gas, and minor ash plumes rose 200-1,800 m above the crater and drifted E, NE, and S. On 21 August an explosion was followed by an ash plume that rose 4.2 km above the summit and drifted S, and expelled incandescent blocks up to 2 km from the crater, primarily on the S flank. On 22 August an ash plume rose 1.8 km above the summit and drifted E and NE. During 27-31 August gas and ash plumes rose 200-1100 m above the crater and drifted E, NE, SE, and S.

An explosion was followed by an ash plume that rose 4.2 km above the summit and drifted S, and expelled incandescent blocks up to 2 km from the crater, primarily on the S flank. The explosion was heard up to 10 km from the volcano.
An explosion was followed by an ash plume that rose 4.2 km above the summit and drifted S and expelled incandescent blocks up to 2 km from the crater, primarily on the S flank.

On 21 August an explosion was followed by an ash plume that rose 4.2 km above the summit and drifted S and expelled incandescent blocks up to 2 km from the crater, primarily on the S flank. The explosion was heard up to 10 km from the volcano.
Ashfall was reported in the towns of Querapi, Ubinas, Escacha, Tonohaya, and Yalahua.

Two exhalations of ash were observed on 5 September, the first at 0858 generated an ash plume up to 1,000 m above the summit which dispersed S. The second plume occurred at 1327 and dispersed ash 500 m above the summit that drifted N. Five explosions were detected on 8 September, the strongest occurred at 0850 and produced a 1,200 m plume; the second explosion expelled ash to heights between 1,300 and 1,900 m; ashfall was noted in areas S. On 8 and 9 September visible images revealed a narrow plume of steam and ash drifting SE. By 0400 on 9 September, the emissions contained water vapor, gas, and light ash, and reached an altitude of 7,300 m. On 10 September there were 15 explosions with plumes 900-1,700 m above the crater and 10 exhalation events; on 11 September there was one explosion with a plume 3,000 m above the crater and 8 exhalation events. Explosions on 21 and 22 September sent ash columns to 1,300 m above the crater. In the last week of September, small intermittent ash-and-gas emissions rose less than 400 m above the crater.

Five explosions were detected on 8 September 2014, the strongest occurred at 0850 and produced a 1,200 m plume; the second explosion expelled ash to heights between 1,300 and 1,900 m; ashfall was noted in areas S. On 10 September there were 15 explosions with plumes 900-1,700 m above the crater and 10 exhalation events; on 11 September there was one explosion with a plume 3,000 m above the crater and 8 exhalation events (600-900 m above the crater). Explosions on 21 and 22 September sent ash columns to 1,300 m above the crater.

A total of five explosions were detected, the strongest occurred at 0850 and produced a 1,200 m plume; the second explosion expelled ash to heights between 1,300 and 1,900 m; ashfall was noted in areas S.
Event was "Partial collapse at end of eruption"
VEI 3. IG reported the ash plume rose to 11-12 km altitude. The VAAC reported the ash plume rising 7.6 km and drifting 37 km SW.
Observers noted intermittent lava fountains rising to 500 m.

Explosions, but no ash, were recorded.
A column of steam and gas with very low ash content rose less than 1 km and drifted W and SW after reported explosions.

A series of large explosions began on 27 April. During the next week, these explosions sent steam-and-ash plumes up to 4.7 km above the summit (9.7 km altitude) which drifted at least 100 km SW and W.

A series of large explosions began on 27 April. During the next week, these explosions sent steam-and-ash plumes up to 4.7 km above the summit (9.7 km altitude) which drifted at least 100 km SW and W.
Ash plumes reported daily by the Washington VAAC rose 1-3 km above the summit.
Ash fell in communities across the region up to 30 km away in many directions.
Lahars traveled down drainages on the S, N, and NW flanks.
A pyroclastic flow traveled 2 km down the NW flank.
Strombolian activity was visible on most nights.
Lava fountains rose 700 m above the crater.
After a slight amount of ash was reported in Choglontus (SW), there were no more reports of ash plumes for two months.
Two large explosions occurred in the morning; the first was heard in areas as far away as Guayaquil (about 180 km SW).
Two large explosions occurred in the morning; the first was heard in areas as far away as Guayaquil (about 180 km SW).

The Washington VAAC reported the plume from the explosions at 13.7 km altitude (8.7 km above the summit) around midday. They noted that satellite imagery showed a dense ash plume expanding in all directions from the summit, but moving generally N and W.

Significant amounts of tephra fell in areas near the volcano including Bilbao (4-cm-diameter), Chacauco (5-cm-diameter), Cotal¢, Cahuaj¡, Choglontus, El Manzano, Puela, and Penipe (15 km SW). Thinner deposits were reported in towns including Pelileo, Ambato, Cevallos, Colta (45 km SW), Guanujo (65 km WSW), and Guaranda (65 km WSW), and in the cantons of Guano (30 km SW), Valencia, Empalme, Buena F, and areas in the province of Manabi (180 km NW).

Several significant pyroclastic flows descended drainages on the NW flanks, including the Achupashal and Juive Grande drainages, during the explosions. The pyroclastic flows at Juive Grande reached a distance of 6.3 km and stopped a kilometer above the road. The temperature measured in the deposit with a thermal camera the next day was 95øC. In the Achupashal stream, the pyroclastic flows reached 6.5 km and crossed the Chambo River. The temperature measured in this deposit was 65øC.
According to USA Today, over 200 people were evacuated from Cusua, Chacauco, and Juive.
Volcanic ash advisories were issued daily by the Washington VAAC.
Ash fell in communities up to 30 km away several times during the period, including after large plumes that rose to 9.6 and 9.9 km altitude on 21 and 24 July.
Ash fell in communities up to 30 km away after large plumes that rose to 9.6 and 9.9 km altitude on 21 and 24 July.
Minor amounts of ash were reported in the Guaranda, Salinas, and Guanujo (65 km WSW) areas after explosions.
Minor amounts of ash were reported in the Guaranda, Salinas, and Guanujo (65 km WSW) areas after explosions.
An explosion generated a small pyroclastic flow.
Strombolian activity occurred throughout the period, with activity including incandescent blocks rolling up to 500 m down the flanks several times.
An ash plume that rose 2 km above the summit and drifted W caused minor ashfall in Choglontus (SW).
An ash plume that rose 2 km above the summit and drifted W caused minor ashfall in Choglontus (SW).

A small explosion produced ashfall in nearby areas.

Ashfall spread to nearby towns from a large ash plume.
Daily VAAC reports were issued. The near-continuous ash emissions during this time generally rose 2-4 km above the crater, and deposited ash in communities within 30 km.
The near-continuous ash emissions during this time generally rose 2-4 km above the crater, and deposited ash in communities within 30 km.

The last reports of ashfall during this episode  came from plumes that rose 1.5 km from the summit and drifted W, with ashfall reported in El Manzano.
The last reports of ashfall during this episode  came from plumes that rose 1.5 km from the summit and drifted W, with ashfall reported in El Manzano.
The community of Pungal, 40 km SSW, received ashfall from a series of explosions that began after two and a half months of quiet.
The community of Pungal, 40 km SSW of Tungurahua, received ashfall from a series of explosions that began after two and a half months of quiet.
The Washington VAAC reported the ash plume visible at 8.2 km altitude extending 11 km ESE from the summit.

Pyroclastic flows traveled 500 m down the NE and NW flanks after the small explosions. IG noted that pyroclastic flows traveled 7-8 km down the SW, W, NW, and NE flanks, reaching the base of the volcano and crossing over the Achupashal Ba¤os- Penipe highway after the large explosion.

Based on reports from IG, satellite images, pilot observations, web-camera images, and the Guayaquil MWO, the Washington VAAC reported that the ash plume rose to an estimated altitude of 13.7 km, and drifted S at high altitudes and SW at lower altitudes.

Explosions continued every minute and vibrated structures in local towns after the large explosion.
Strombolian explosions ejected incandescent blocks 800 m above the crater that fell and rolled 500 m down the flanks.
An ash plume rose 4 km above the summit and drifted N, reaching Quito (130 km N) as a mist of suspended very fine material that lingered most of the day.
The Washington VAAC issued multiple daily reports of ash plumes.
Ash plumes rose to altitudes between 9 and 10 km, dispersing ash to the W and NW.
Fewer ash plumes were reported, at generally lower heights of 1-3 km above the crater.

On 11 and 21 March rains caused major lahars in the Achupashal drainage which led to traffic disruption on the Ba¤os- Penipe highway. Lahars on 31 March traveled down the Vasc£n (N) and Mapayacu (SW) drainages, carrying blocks up to 1 m in diameter in the latter drainage.
Explosions and substantial ash plumes increased, with multiple daily VAAC reports issued.
Explosions and substantial ash plumes increased, with multiple daily VAAC reports issued.
A large explosion lasted for five minutes, and produced pyroclastic flows and a large ash plume.
The large explosion generated pyroclastic flows that descended the NW and N flanks.
The explosion caused an ash plume that rose over 10 km above the crater, reported at 15.2 km altitude by the Washington VAAC, the highest reported in many years.

A significant explosion produced an infrasound signal that was detected at 150 decibels 5.5 km away.

A significant explosion produced an infrasound signal that was detected at 150 decibels 5.5 km away. Unconfirmed reports indicated that windows in Chacauco and Cus£a shattered. The shock wave was also detected in other locations, including Ambato and Riobamba (30 km S).
Although IG reported an ash plume rising to over 5 km above the crater (10 km altitude), the Washington VAAC only reported the plume to 8.5 km.
A lahar in the Achupashal drainage affected traffic on the main highway.
Repeated ashfall was reported in communities within 30 km of the volcano.
OVT reported a gas-and-ash emission to an estimated 9 km altitude.
Three explosions generated ash emissions that rose an estimated 5 km above the crater, with ashfall reported in the communities to the SW.
Three explosions generated ash emissions that rose an estimated 5 km above the crater, with ashfall reported in the communities to the SW.

A small plume on contained minor amounts of ash.
Intense rains caused lahars to flow down most drainages, and roads crossing the Chontapamba and Romero gorges were washed out.
Seasonal rains generated numerous lahars, some causing major damage to roads.
Seismicity was accompanied by a small ash plume that rose 1 km above the crater and drifted NW.
A small explosion with an ash plume rose 1 km above the crater and drifted NW with ashfall reported in the Chontapamba area.
The Washington VAAC issued multiple daily reports of ash plumes.  They were generally reported at 1-4 km above the summit, or to altitudes of 6-9 km.
Ashfall was reported a number of times in communities within 30 km.
Strombolian activity sent incandescent blocks as high as 1 km above the crater and up to 1.5 km down the flanks. Incandescence appeared on most clear nights.
Lahars occurred after rainy episodes during 8-9 and 13 August.
Pyroclastic flows traveled 1,500 m down the NW flank. The pyroclastic flows surrounded the lava flow from April 2014, in the La Hacienda, Achupashal, and Mandur drainages.
A pyroclastic flow descended 500 m from the crater.
Intermittent ash plumes were reported as high as 2.5 km above the crater. LP seismic events increased slightly at the end of September along with several low-level ash plumes.
Ashfall was recorded in communities up to 25 km away, generally to the W.
Rains resulted in lahars within the NW drainages of Achupashal and La Pampa.
Emissions with low to moderate ash content were noted most days in early October.

Trace amounts of ashfall appeared on the SW flank.

Residents in Choglontus reported a steam-and-ash plume drifting S.

Low ash content was reported in plumes rising to 500 m above the crater each day.
Slight incandescence was seen at night.

Numerous lahars descended the Ulba, Vazc£n, Juive, Hacienda, Achupashal, Pingullo, Chontapamba, Romero and Rea quebradas (ravines). Most of the lahars consisted of only muddy water, but three carried debris up to 30 cm in diameter in flows several feet wide, moving material at several cubic meters per second (Palmahurco (Juive), Achupashal, and Rea quebradas).
Incandescence was noted at the crater on clear nights.
A lahar in the Yuibug sector, reported by an observer in Bilbao, briefly closed the Penipe-Ba¤os road.
IG reported a gradual increase in seismicity. They noted an increase in the number of long-period (LP) earthquakes associated with fluid movement near the summit.
The Washington VAAC issued a report of a small burst of possible ash and gas seen by the volcano observatory (OVT) mid-day at 5.2 km altitude drifting slowly W.
Rainfall led to a lahar that carried 30-cm-diameter blocks down the Quebrada de Juive.
Moderate amplitude tremors began during the early morning.
Nearby residents reported noises from the volcano starting around 0730 local time.
Minor ashfall was reported in Chacauco, Manzano, and Punzupal Alto.
Residents of Palitahua reported a gray ash plume drifting W up to 2 km above the crater.

Ashfall was reported from 6 to 9 April SW and W of the volcano, primarily in the Choglontus sector. On 8 April, ashfall was reported in Manzano, Choglontus, Bilbao, Chacauco, Pillate, and Quero, with accumulation rates of 135-200 grams per square meter per day (g/m2/day). Ashfall increased in Choglontus, reaching 1000 g/m2 during 8 and 9 April.
OVT reported dense ash emissions to 5.9 km altitude, drifting NW.
Local aircraft indicated ash present at 6.7 km altitude.

A swarm of "drumbeat" LP earthquakes on 10-11 April was followed by moderate ash emissions on 12 April. On 11 April, IG reported an ash cloud moving W and NW from the summit at 5.5 km altitude. An emission on 14 April with moderate amounts of ash rose 500 m above the summit and drifted WSW.
An explosion generated an ash plume that reached 3 km above the summit crater.

An explosion on 15 April generated an ash plume that reached 3 km above the summit crater. Later in the day ash emissions rose to 2 km above the crater and drifted W. The Washington VAAC reported a continuous ash plume visible in satellite imagery on 15 April moving W from the summit at 6.1 km altitude (1 km above the summit).

Although the plume appeared to be almost 100 km long, ashfall reports were limited to areas within 15 km of the summit. Collected ash was mainly composed of dense lithic fragments, euhedral crystals, and oxidized particles, and was not considered juvenile material (from fresh magma). Additional ashfall was reported up through 17 April in Palictahua, El Guanto, El Mirador, El Santuario, Mapayacu, Puela, Chontapamba, and Saba¤ag.

Plumes with moderate ash content were observed rising to 1 or 2 km above the summit on clear days. Ash emissions continued at a lower level of frequency and energy after 17 April, and seismic activity notably decreased. There were minor emissions coincident with seismic tremors that produced gray to black fine-grained ashfall mainly to the W of the volcano in Bilbao and Chontapamba through 27 April.
There were minor emissions coincident with seismic tremors that produced gray to black fine-grained ashfall mainly to the W of the volcano in Bilbao and Chontapamba.
Deformation changed from inflation to deflation beginning on 21 April, but after five days, switched back to inflation on 26 April.
An emission contained modest amounts of ash and drifted NW.

Intense rains occurred that were large enough to generate significant lahars. On 25 April, lahars were reported in the Chontapamba and Romero ravines moving blocks up to 1 m in diameter. Muddy water was observed in the Achupashal ravine. On 26 April, lahars were reported in the Juive, Mapayacu, Romero, and Chontapamba drainages. Lahars caused a high-frequency seismic signal from the Pondoa ravine during the late morning. The flow rates doubled in Vazc£n and Puela ravines, which filled with muddy water. A large lahar was also reported in the Quebrada del Pingullo, and debris was reported in the Clementina, Juive Chico, and La Pampa creeks.
Constant steam emissions rose 1 km above the summit crater mostly drifting W and SW. The vapor was characterized by very low amounts of ash.
Ash falls were reported in Manzano, Choglont£s, Yuibug and Bilbao.

On 10 and 11 May, intense and prolonged rains led to significant lahars in Q. Romero, Ingapirca, Chontapamba, Achupashal, and Ulba, and smaller lahars in several other ravines. Small mudflows and lahars also occurred in the ravines on the W flank on 12, 14, and 15 May.
Fine-grained gray ashfall was reported in Choglontus on 15 and 20 May.
Lahars descended ravines on the W flank.
Persistent steam plumes rose up to 500 m above the summit crater and drifted generally W, often carrying small quantities of ash.

Several lookout stations in communities located within 20 km NW and SW reported ashfall almost every day, including Choglont£s (13 km WSW), Bilbao, and El Manzano (8 km SW). Other stations that reported ashfall during the month included Palitahua, Mocha, Chacauco, and Pillate.
IG-EPN reported explosions with larger ash plumes on 3, 12, and 14 July that rose as high as 7.5 km.

IG-EPN reported explosions with larger ash plumes on 3, 12, and 14 July that rose as high as 7.5 km.  The Washington VAAC reported the ash plume on 3 July extending 25 km WSW from the summit at 5.2 km altitude. An ash plume extended 35 km WSW late in the day at 6.4 km on 14 July.
Increased seismicity was associated with emissions that caused ashfall in most of the reporting locations.
An ash plume reported by the Washington VAAC was moving SW at 6.7 km altitude.

Lahars were reported during 5-7, 18-19, 22-23, and 29-30 July in the Chontapamba, Rea, Achupashal, Juive, Pondoa and Puela river drainages. Heavy rain on 18 and 19 July generated mudflows in the Juive, Pondoa and La Pampa ravines. Blocks 40 cm in diameter were reported in the Puela River on 22 July, and blocks 1 meter in diameter were reported in the Chontapamba river on 29 July.
A lahar sent 40-cm-diameter blocks down the Mapayacu ravine.
Two explosions caused ashfall in Choglontus, Manzano, and Chontapamba.

Two explosions caused ashfall in Choglontus, Manzano, and Chontapamba. A pilot report of an ash plume rising to 7 km altitude and drifting W was not detected in satellite imagery due to weather clouds, although ashfall was reported within 15 km of the summit.
Small lahars from the Rea and Romero drainages blocked the Ba¤os-Penipe road.

An explosion on 18 August sent an ash plume WSW and caused ashfall in Choglontus; the next day reddish ash and steam emissions around 1000 local time caused ashfall again in Choglontus. Black ashfall was reported there on 22 August.
An explosion on sent an ash plume WSW and caused ashfall in Choglontus; the next day reddish ash and steam emissions around 1000 local time caused ashfall again in Choglontus.

Increased seismic activity with several explosions on 25 August was accompanied by ash plumes that caused ashfall in Chontapamba, Pillate, Bilbao, and Juive Grande. Gray ash was reported in Chinchicoto and Yanayacu, and thick black ash was reported in Rumipamba, Pingili and Mocha. Fine-grained gray ash was reported in Mocha on 27 August.
Increased seismic activity accompanied several explosions.

Explosions caused windows to vibrate and sounds resembling "cannon shots" were noted.
A sudden increase in tremor detected by the seismic network was followed by intense roaring noises, an increase in the number and intensity of explosions, and window and ground vibrations.
Multiple explosions with ash emissions were reported.
At 0647, SERNAGEOMIN recorded an M 5.2 earthquake at 13.4 km depth, located ~15 km SE of the volcano.
SERNAGEOMIN reported that the explosions were probably phreatomagmatic (caused by the interaction of water with magma at depth inside the volcano).
Ash-bearing emissions were reported on at least 16 days during July with reports of ashfall in Maragato, Chorillo (18 km W) and Genoy.
Ash-bearing emissions were reported on at least 16 days during July with reports of ashfall in Maragato, Chorillo (18 km W) and Genoy.
Ash plumes rose to 2,500 m above the summit during at least nine different days of August, and ashfall was reported again in the Genoy area.
Ash-bearing emissions were reported during at least seven days of the month, and reached 2,000 m above the crater.
During at least 16 days of October, tremors were associated with ash emissions that rose as high as 1,800 m.
Ash plumes rose to 1,200 m and seismic tremors associated with ash and gas emissions were reported on at least 13 days.
Tremor signals associated with ash and gas emissions were noted on at least eight occasions. The pulsating ash plumes were small, and deposited material mostly on the NW flank.
Emissions during June 2013 were mostly steam that rose to 1,300 m, but ash plumes were reported on seven days.
Ash and gas plumes were noted on 6, 12, 13, 17 and 22 July rising as high as 1,500 m.
Tremors associated with ash emissions were reported on five days of August.

During the early hours of 11, 13, and 23 January, incandescence was observed at the crater.

Based on analyses of satellite imagery, the Darwin VAAC reported that on 14 May an ash plume from Karangetang rose to an altitude of 3.7 km and drifted 130 km SE. On 16 May an ash plume again rose to an altitude of 3.7 km then drifted about 110 km SE.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery and wind data, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume from Karangetang rose to an altitude of 3 km and drifted 110 km SW.
Based on analyses of satellite imagery and wind data, the Darwin VAAC reported that an ash plume rose to an altitude of 4.3 km and drifted over 45 km WNW.
According to a news article, rock avalanches traveled 2 km down the flanks.

Maggie de Grauw, resident of Paeroa, New Zealand, took photographs from a commercial airplane of a "peculiar large mass floating on the ocean between Tonga and Auckland."
A short seismic swarm was reported. According to Olivier Hyvernaud (2012), between 0733 on 17 July 2012 UTC and 0300 on 18 July 2012 UTC, 157 hydroacoustic events from Kermadec ridge were measured.
A MODIS hot spot was detected at 1050 UTC; band 22, 3.959 æm
A vapor plume was detected by MODIS satellite at 2150 UTC; band 20, 3.75 æm; plume image "pointing to the source of the eruption"
A satellite image shows the pumice floating in cuniform elongate rafts over a wide area of the sea to the NW and NE of Havre seamount.
NIWA ocean geology scientist Joshu Mountjoy announced finding a new volcanic cone which has formed on the edge of the volcano, towering 240 m above the crater rim that was first mapped in 2002.

On 31 July GeoNet reported that seismicity at Tongariro had declined the previous week but increased again during 28-29 July, and as of 31 July, between 3 and 10 events were being recorded daily. The earthquakes were clustered in a zone between Tongariro and the E side of Lake Rotoaira, at 2-7 km depth. On 6 August GeoNet reported that volcanic earthquakes continued beneath Tongariro but the size and number had decreased; there were fewer than five events each day.
About 5 cm of ash fell on State Highway 46, to the N.
According to a news article, a GNS Science volcanologist noted that there were reports of "red hot rocks being thrown out of the crater", explosions, and lighting.
According to a news article, a GNS Science volcanologist noted that there were reports of "red hot rocks being thrown out of the crater", explosions, and lighting.
A news article stated that some people in the Tongariro area had self-evacuated following the eruption.
GeoNet reported on 8 August 2012 on actively steaming vents that were visible at a new crater area formed below the Upper Te Mari crater.
During an overflight scientists observed minor ash emissions from the vents.

A minor flood/lahar crossed State Highway 46 near the S tip of Lake Rotoaira (at a location ~6 km W of Rangipo). According to the New Zealand Herald, a driver described 13-cm-deep mud crossing the road at 0830.
An ash plume rose 3-4 km above the Upper Te Maari crater and produced ashfall across part of State Highway 46 and NE towards Turangi (21 km NE).
Since early July there had been intermittent periods of volcanic tremor, including several hours early on 28 July and during 30-31 July.
Web camera images from between 0454 and 0457 showed an eruption from Crater Lake.
The GeoNet Data Centre reported that scientists visited White Island and observed an ash plume rising as high as 300 m from a new vent in the SW corner of the 1978/1990 Crater Complex.
Black ash was depositing on the wall of the Main Crater to the W of the vent.

During 9-14 August volcanic tremor remained at low levels and a weak ash-and-steam plume rose a few hundred meters from the vent. The plume color changed between white and gray as the ash content varied.
An eruption plume rose from the lake after the earthquake at 0454.
Impact craters around the tuff cone were the result of falling ejecta from explosions. The impact craters were confined to the 1978/90 Crater Complex.

A volcanologist visiting the area observed that hydrothermal activity in the small "hot lake" had increased. The lake surface "domed up" from rising steam and gas, that also brought large amounts of sediment to the surface, often with a vivid white steam-and-gas "flashing" from around the base. Stronger events periodically occurred.
GNS reported that small phreatic explosions with minor ash occurred intermittently throughout December 2012.
The scientists observed vigorous mud geysering in the crater lake.

Frequent bursts of mud, steam, and gas were vigorous; mud and rock were ejected tens of meters out of the lake area. Steam-and-gas plumes that rose from the crater were visible from the Bay of Plenty coastline. Intermittent bursts of mud, rock, steam, and gas rose 50-100 m high.
Seismicity changed to continuous tremor and remained at a high level.
A volcanologist that visited the lake area noted that water had again filled the lake and small geysering was the only activity that he observed.
GeoNet Data Centre reported that ash venting from White island occurred at about 1130 and 1330.

GeoNet Data Centre reported that a pattern of repeating minor activity at White Island had become established over the last month. Periods of passive steaming and degassing were accompanied by very low levels of volcanic tremor. This activity alternated with minor mud-and-steam explosions from the active crater when there was strong volcanic tremor.
GeoNet Data Centre reported that activity at White Island remained at a persistently low level, characterized by tremor and degassing. No mud or ash eruptions had been observed since early April.
Volcanologists noted audible jets of gas venting through the small lake, broader expanding ?bubbles? of dark lake sediments, and debris ejected 20-30 m vertically.

The GeoNet Data Centre reported that a small eruption from White Island occurred at 1023 on 20 August and continued for about 10 minutes. The eruption ejected mud and rocks short distances, and generated a voluminous steam plume (visible from the Bay of Plenty coast), that rose 4 km and then slowly dispersed. The eruption originated in the active crater area that had been ejecting small amounts of mud in recent weeks.
Weather radar observations showed that a minor amount of ash was present in the plume.
An eruption ejected material over 350 m from the active vent and caused a wet surge cloud that enveloped the Main Crater.
According to news reports, Ivan Grozny, one of two volcanoes comprising the Grozny Group, erupted after increased gas emissions from the NE flank were observed the day before.
An ash plume rose 1.2 km and caused ashfall in Goryachiye Klyuchi (9 km W) and Kurilsk (25 km away).

Observers reported that an ash plume rose to 5 km on 25 August. That same day the Tokyo VAAC reported that a possible eruption from Etorofu-Yake-yama, a lava dome of the Grozny Group, may have produced a plume that rose to an altitude of 4 km and drifted E.

Based on analysis of satellite images, the Tokyo VAAC reported that a possible eruption from Grozny Group may have produced a plume that rose 2.1 km and drifted E. A later VAAC notice stated that ash had dissipated.
SVERT reported that on at 0755 ash from Grozny Group fell in Kurilsk (23 km N) and Kitovy, producing deposits 2-3 mm thick.
Satellite images showed an ash plume that rose 3 km and drifted W and NW.
Episodes of volcanic tremor were detected.
Strombolian activity was observed at night.
KVERT reported that video footage and satellite imagery showed Strombolian explosions at Kliuchevskoi, along with crater incandescence and gas-and-steam emissions.

A weak thermal anomaly was detected in satellite images.

According to NASA Earth Observatory (EO) an image acquired from the Advanced Land Imager (ALI) on NASA's EO-1 satellite showed that Mawson's Peak crater on Heard Island had filled and a lava flow had traveled down the SW flank.
The lava flow was visible in an image acquired on 20 April 2013 and had slightly widened just below the summit.

According to a NOAA National Environmental Satellite, Data, and Information Service (NESDIS) scientist, thermal anomalies seemingly on the E flank were detected in Visible Infrared Imaging Radiometer Suite (VIIRS) satellite images.
A plume from Heard was visible in a U.S. Air Force satellite image drifting SSW.

Scientists and engineers from the 2016 Cordell Expedition photographed the usually cloud-covered Mawson Peak, the summit of Big Ben. Steam was visible above the flat upper surface, possibly a crater rim or fissure.
Landsat 8 captured a rare clear view that showed fresh lava and debris flows emanating from the summit on top of the snow. The longest flow is estimated to be 1,300 m long.
Two thermal anomalies were present at the summit in Landsat 8 OLI/TIRS false-color infrared imagery of Mawson Peak. The two anomalies were separated by about 250 m.

Lava fountaining generated heavy fallout of large pyroclastics onto the flanks of the cone.  The continuous, intense ejection of pyroclastics onto the flanks of the cone generated avalanches resembling pyroclastic flows, which descended a few hundred meters beyond the base of the cone, mainly towards the S.
Incandescent bombs were ejected due to an explosion.
Gas and tephra rose 5-6 km from the crater and drifted SW.
A series of ash emissions from the New SE Crater took place.

Two vents within the crater emitted pulsating lava fountains up to 100 m high. At 0220 the SE flank of the cone fractured and exposed a line of new eruptive vents down to the base of the cone that produced lava fountains.

Lava overflowed the rim through a breach in the E crater rim and traveled towards the Valle del Bove.  A small lava flow issued from the area affected by the collapse of a portion of the cone's ESE flank during the 20 August event. A broad lava flow fed by new vents descended into the Valle del Bove, somewhat to the S of the lava flow emitted earlier during the episode.
Throughout the day small dilute ash was emitted.
During the evening weak Strombolian activity commenced, with small explosions occurring about every 30 minutes. Strombolian activity intensified the next day causing lava flows and lava jets.
Explosions were associated with Strombolian activity.
Emissions of ash from the New SE Crater occurred.
A series of ash explosions lasted for five minutes in the early morning.
A series of ash explosions lasted for five minutes in the early morning.
Weak Strombolian activity was visible during the evening and intensified during the night.
A dense plume rose a few kilometers above the summit before drifting toward the SSE. The lava fountaining from the vents within the crater turned into ash emissions towards the end of the event.

Sporadic, very weak Strombolian explosions from the crater started during the late evening and then continued in a subdued manner through the night. A rapid increase both in the intensity and frequency of Strombolian explosions occurred the next day.
Ash emissions were vigorous. Brief periods of repeated emissions of brown ash mixed with white water vapor occurred from two or three vents on the N flank of the New SE Crater cone.
Explosions were associated with Strombolian activity.
The Strombolian activity turned into a pulsating lava fountain.

Lava flowed through a deep breach in the E crater rim and along the fracture that had opened on the SE side of the cone during 29 August. The lava overflow was accompanied by repeated collapse and rockfalls from unstable portions of the cone in that area. Lava flows descended on the W slope of the Valle del Bove; expansion of the most advanced lava fronts continued for some time after feeding of the lava had ceased. Small active lava flows were observed for many hours after the cessation of activity, remaining confined to the immediate vicinity of the crater.
Repeated collapse and rockfalls occurred from unstable portions of the cone.
Lava fountains rose from multiple vents within the crater. Weak spattering continued from a vent at the SE base of the SE Crater cone.
Lava flows descended the W slope of the Valle del Bove
At 2133 and 2134 two powerful explosions originating from a vent on the E rim of the crater created shock waves visible in the clouds above the crater and ejected large bombs hundreds of meters away.
Ash and lapilli fell in an area to the N of Giarre (16 km E).
Strombolian activity progressively increased both in the intensity and frequency of explosions, and eventually became continuous.
Bombs and scoria were ejected well beyond the crater rim. Two powerful explosions ejected large bombs hundreds of meters away.
Bombs and scoria were ejected well beyond the crater rim.

A small amount of lava flowed through the notch in the SE flank of the volcano. The lava flow emitted from the SE flank of the cone reached the lower portion of the W slope of the Valle del Bove, somewhat SW of Monte Centenari.
A sustained lava fountain rose as high as 800 m. Lava fountains 100-150 m high commenced from a vent on the N base of the New SE Crater cone at 2136.
Rhythmic ash emissions rose from a vent located within the crater. Ash plumes drifted SW.
Ash fell on the S flank of Etna, Nicolosi (14 km S), and Catania (27 km S).

At about 1300 weak and discontinuous Strombolian explosions were recorded by surveillance cameras. At around 1545 vigorous Strombolian activity was observed from numerous vents along a short fissure on the SE flank of the cone, which had first been active during 29 August.
Explosions were associated with the Strombolian activity.

Lava flowed from a deep notch in the SE rim of the crater. Lava flows descended on the W slope of the Valle del Bove. Eruptive vents opened on the NE flank of the cone, approximately along the fracture that first opened during 8 September, and two small lava flows were emitted. The more voluminous lava flow traveled a few hundred meters downslope.
The change from Strombolian activity to lava fountaining and ash emissions was audible around 1630.
A dense ash-and-vapor plume rapidly rose above the weather clouds and drifted E. Ash emissions continued until 1945. The ash cloud drifted ENE.
Ash and lapilli fell from the Ripe della Naca area and Puntalazzo (13 km E) to the town of Mascali (18 km E).
Weak explosive activity was recorded at 1913. Explosive activity rapidly intensified at 1940 and by 2007 the crater was completely filled with lava.
Explosive activity rapidly intensified at 1940 and by 2007 that crater was completely filled with lava.

At 2026, Strombolian activity transitioned to continuous lava fountains that rose a few tens of meters above the crater rim. At 2036, a vent opened on the SE flank of the cone, producing a second lava fountain, leading to a significant increase in the lava effusion rate. The height of the lava fountains significantly increased after 2100, reaching 300 m above the crater.

Lava overflowed through a breach in the E crater rim and traveled towards the Valle del Bove. The lava flow continued to advance towards the Valle del Bove until about 0040 on 24 October and stagnated just upslope of Monte Centenari (at 1,900 m a.s.l.)
Abundant amounts of tephra fell on the E flank of the cone, forming a dense curtain, while large incandescent blocks rolled to the base of the cone on more gently sloping terrain.
Tephra affected the N portion of Zafferana (E), Milo (ESE), Fornazzo (E), downslope across Santa Venerina (SE), Dagala del Re (ESE) to Giarre (E), and Riposto (km E).

Just after 1200 lava fountains and ash emissions rose from the crater. At 1230 ash emissions significantly increased, especially from a vent located in the SE portion of the New SEC, and a plume of ash and gas rose several kilometers above the summit and drifted SE. Passive ash emissions lasted until just after 1400.
Ashfall affected Zafferana Etnea (SE) and Acireale (SE).

Pyroclastic material fell onto the New SEC cone, areas well beyond the base, and the nearby old SEC cone. The New SEC grew in height by 10 m on the S side, bringing the total height of the cone to about 180-200 m above its base.
Several hours of Strombolian activity were observed on the SE and NE slopes starting at 2230. This activity continued into the early morning of 5 January.

Around 0515 lava fountains generated a continuous eruption of ash-and-gas plumes that rose to an altitude of 2.1-2.4 km. A strong explosion opened a vent on the top side of the SE cone and generated ash plumes. Passive ash emissions that lasted until 0830.
Small pyroclastic flows went a few hundred meters down the NE, E, and S flanks of the cone.
Lahars traveled down the NE, E, and S flanks of the cone.
The most intense phase of the eruption occurred around 0620 when a strong explosion opened a vent on the top side of the SE cone, removed a portion of the SE crater rim, and generated ash plumes.

An explosion generated an ash plume at that rose 400 m above the crater at 1906. An explosive ash emission at 1124 from the vent on the W portion of the crater floor was followed by others that were less intense. Sporadic ash emissions continued the next day.
Small ash emissions continued from Etna's New Southeast Crater (New SEC).
A cloud with a small amount of tephra rose 6 km above the summit and then drifted W, producing some pyroclastic fallout that was on the upper portion of the volcano.

Around 2100 and the Strombolian activity slowly increased, turning into a discontinuous lava fountain around 2330. The next day the pulsating lava fountain rose 100-500 m above the crater before becoming a continuous jet rising 300-400 m above the crater. Around 0200 and 0400, lava fountains from the two vents within the crater rose as high as 500 m above the crater. The fountain from the E vent caused abundant fallout on the crater rim and E flank. Lava fountaining started to diminish around 0530, and then around 0545 sporadic jets rose as high as 300 m above the crater.
A third vent, located in the breach cutting the SE crater rim, produced sporadic violent explosions that ejected bombs many meters in diameter all over the E portion of the cone.
Pyroclastic fallout was on the upper part of the volcano.

At about 0850 small pyroclastic flows generated by the partial collapse of the eruption column mainly descended the NE flank, and somewhat down the S flank. The lava interacted with snow, causing powerful explosions and small pyroclastic flows.

The lava interacted with snow, causing powerful explosions and small pyroclastic flows. These phreatic explosions generated jets of vapor and launched rock fragments to distances of several tens of meters.

Phreatic explosions from the lava interacting with snow resulted in a lahar which traveled toward the "Belvedere" monitoring station, on the W rim of the Valle del Bove, and passed a few tens of meters to the N of the monitoring instruments.
Ash and lapilli were carried NE by the wind, affecting the areas around Piedimonte, Etneo, and Taormina. Fine ash fell as far as the Messina area and southern Calabria.

Just after 0800 lava overflowed the deep breach in the SE rim of the crater and reached the SE base of the cone within 15 minutes, then advanced towards the W rim of the Valle del Bove. A lava flow was emitted from a new eruptive vent on the upper SW flank of the New SEC cone and descended into the saddle between the old and new SEC cones. A lava flow also issued from an eruptive fissure on the upper N flank of the cone and descended a few hundred meters to the NE, surrounding the N base of the cone. After descending the steep W slope of the Valle del Bove, the flow split into several branches on the more gently sloping terrain. These branches exceeded in length those of 9 February, reaching a total distance of about 3.5 km from the crater. The lava flow emitted from the fissure on the SW flank of the cone continued advancing for a few hours after the cessation of the activity.
Large pyroclasts fell on the steep flanks of the cone, causing avalanches. The pyroclastic cone of the New SEC had grown in height, mainly on its N rim.

At about 0825 the ash content in the gas plume rising from the crater became more significant. A plume rose 4-5 km above Etna and drifted E.  Strong ash emission continued without significant variations until about 1040. The last ash clouds were observed around 1110.

Several lava lobes took a northerly path to areas covered with thick snow. The interaction of the lava and snow led to strong explosions that produced ground-hugging vapor-and-ash clouds resembling pyroclastic flows, which repeatedly descended on the floor of the Valle del Bove. The vapor-and-ash clouds rose 1-1.5 km above the floor of the Valle del Bove. This phenomenon continued intermittently for some time after the cessation of the lava fountaining and ash emission, until about 1130.
Ash and lapilli fell mainly in the area between the villages of Zafferana Etnea and Sant'Alfio, extending toward the Ionian Sea between Riposto and Pozzillo.
Several lava lobes, took a northerly path to areas covered with thick snow. The interaction of the lava and snow led to rapid melting of the snow, generating small lahars.
Minor ash content rose from New SE Crater.

Just before 0700 lava flowed through the deep breach in the SE crater rim. The main lava flow descended the steep W slope of the Valle del Bove. Several lava lobes, however, took a more northerly path to areas covered with thick snow. Similar to the previous episodes, the lava that flowed through the breach in the SE crater rim advanced for several hours after the cessation of the paroxysmal activity into the upper part of the Valle del Bove. The lava reached a distance of about 4 km from the source, stagnating S of Monte Centenari. A small lava flow, emitted from a fracture on the N flank of the cone, followed the same path as a flow emitted from the same fracture during the 4 March paroxysm, and traveled a few hundred meters.
A gas-and-tephra plume rose from NSEC.
Ash and lapilli fell over the SE sector of the volcano, affecting mainly the area between Monterosso and Zafferana Etnea, but also the area between Acireale and Giarre.
A plume with a heavy load of ash and lapilli rose a few kilometers and drifted NE.
A plume with a heavy load of ash and lapilli rose a few kilometers, drifted NE, and produced ashfall 15-17 km NE in Linguaglossa, Piedimonte, and Presa.
The upper part of the plume drifted E and produced pea-sized lapilli fall in the area between Fornazzo (10 km E) and Giarre (17 km E).
Bombs were ejected as high as 100 m above the crater rim.
Tephra was deposited on the flanks of the NSE crater.
In the early hours of the day incandescent bombs were ejected just higher than the crater rim.
Tephra was deposited on the entire NSEC cone.
Lava fountains rose 300-500 m above the crater.
A small pyroclastic flow expanded a few hundred meters first S and then E.
A lahar originated near the Belvedere area.
Tephra was deposited in Milo and Fornazzo (10 km E), Giarre (16 km E) and Riposto (18 km E).
Ashfall to the NE traveling as far as Lipari (more than 80 km N).
Scoria up to 15 cm in diameter also fell in Linguaglossa.
Two lava flows traveled 2.5 km down to the base of the steep W slope of the Valle del Bove.
There was pronounced cone growth at NSEC during 19-20 Feb 2013.
Ashfall was on the SE flank between Zafferana and Santa Venerina.
There was a collapse of nearly all of the SW flank of the NSEC cone and parts of the E flank of the old SEC cone.
Ash and scoria fell in the Milo-Fornazzo and Giarre-Riposto areas.
Lava fountains rose up to 200-800 m above the crater.
Bombs fell in Valle del Leone, Pizzi Deneri, and Serra delle Concazze.
Scoria fell in Valle del Leone, Pizzi Deneri, and Serra delle Concazze.
Ash was observed in Piedimonte Etneo, Fiumefreddo, Taormina.
Lava fountain rose up to 600-800 m above the crater rim.
Lapilli fell on the SE flank and affected Zafferana Etnea, Santa Venerina, and a number of villages to the N of Acireale.
Numerous car windshields, skylights, and roof tiles were broken

Lapilli affected Zafferana Etnea, Santa Venerina, the N part of Acireale and smaller villages to the N and S margin of Giarre.
A pyroclastic flow moved from the NE flank of the NSEC cone.

Ash and lapilli affected Fleri, Zafferana Etnea, Milo and S. Maria la Scala.

The collapses generated avalanches and ash clouds.
Ash and lapilli affected Ragalna, Belper, and Paterno, as well as the tourist area "Etna Sud."
Ash and lapilli fell over a wide area to the E.
Lava fountains reached heights of 800-1000 m above the crater.

Lava fountains rose 300-500 m above the crater.
Ashfall was reported in areas to the NW and NNW.
An ash plume rose 1.8 km altitude, drifting SSE.
The flanks had been blanketed by a layer of fine ash with a thickness exceeding 5 cm in the vicinity of the vent when observed on 24 August 2010.
A light gray plume reached 2 km altitude.
An ash plume rose 3 km altitude and drifted 115 km WNW.
An explosion from the summit crater released a low-altitude plume of ash (described as a "mushroom cloud" in news reports) that drifted over villages located W of the volcano.
The explosion released incandescent blocks that burned the vegetation to the SW of the crater covering an area of more than 300 square meters.
Ash fell within a 10 km radius of the crater: Las Grecias, El Piloto, El Chonco, Mokor¢n, and Villa.
An ash plume rose 3 km altitude and drifted over 35 km N.

Lava flowed S of the fissure into a canyon causing steam to rise from where the lava interacted with snow and ice. A'a lava flowed over the steep Hrunagil canyon rim creating spectacular 'lava falls.' Lava advanced N into the Hrunagil and Hvann rgil valleys. Lava flows covered an estimated area of 1.3 square kilometers and were on average 10-20 m thick by 7 April. When activity stopped on April 12 the fissure had issued about 0.025 km3 of magma, giving a mean discharge of 13 m3/s.
