Multiple thermal alerts consistent with a lava flow on the N flank were issued. Satellite imagery from September 2010 indicate a larger lava field than when observed in March 2009.
Media reported two fatalities from respiratory and cardiac problems.
Authorities relocated people living within a 6 km radius of the volcano; 20,000-30,000 residents were evacuated.
Continuous tremor with amplitudes of 3-8 mm.
Explosions of ash and tephra were referred to have begun "a week earlier" from Sunday 31 October 2010. They were reported intermittently through 15 January 2011.
JMA 2013 catalog says VEI 5. Previously entered as 4? due to conflicting volume reports.

An ash plume reached 3 km above the crater and drifted NW, causing ashfall in Pillate, Quero, Santuario, La Galera and El Rosario. The Washington VAAC reported the ash plume at 8 km altitude; the satellite imagery showed it extending 15 km WNW.

An ash plume reached 3 km above the crater and drifted NW, causing ashfall in Pillate, Quero, Santuario, La Galera and El Rosario. Ashfall was reported the next day in El Manzano and Choglontus. The Washington VAAC reported the ash plume at 8 km altitude; the satellite imagery showed it extending 15 km WNW.

Moderate to high amounts of ash characterized ash emissions. The plumes rose 2 km above the crater, drifted W and caused slight ashfall in Chonglontus and El Manzano. Only Chonglontus reported additional ashfall the next day. The Washington VAAC initially reported the ash plume at 7.3 km altitude extending 40 km SW. About 6 hours later, the leading edge of the plume was dissipating about 170 km SW. This was followed by a new ash plume late in the day that rose to 5.8 km altitude and drifted 15 km WSW from the summit.

Moderate to high amounts of ash characterized ash emissions. The plumes rose 2 km above the crater, drifted W and caused slight ashfall in Chonglontus and El Manzano. Only Chonglontus reported additional ashfall the next day. The Washington VAAC initially reported the ash plume at 7.3 km altitude extending 40 km SW. About 6 hours later, the leading edge of the plume was dissipating about 170 km SW. This was followed by a new ash plume late in the day that rose to 5.8 km altitude and drifted 15 km WSW from the summit.
Slight incandescence was reported along with minor ash and steam emissions that were moving W at 7.6 km altitude.
Constant emission of moderate amounts of ash on created an ash plume that rose to 2 km above the crater and drifted NW.
Ashfall was reported in El Manzano and Pillate.
An explosion late in the day rattled structures in Pondoa, and was followed by observations of incandescence at the crater shortly after midnight.
Ashfall was reported to the W in Pillate, El Manzano, Bilbao, Motilones, Chontapamba, and Choglontus.
A sudden deflation in the deformation data was recorded. Similar deflation events preceded major explosions in July 2013 and February 2014.
Several hours of seismic tremor produced an ash-rich plume and incandescent blocks which descended the W flank.

Several hours of seismic tremor produced an ash-rich plume and incandescent blocks which descended the W flank. This was followed by additional explosions and periods of tremor, some lasting for more than an hour, that produced ash plumes drifting SW. The Washington VAAC spotted a faint ash plume moving W in multispectral imagery.
Several hours of seismic tremor produced an ash-rich plume and incandescent blocks which descended the W flank.
Ashfall was reported in the towns of Manzano, Choglontus, Cahuaj¡, and Palictahua. Additional ashfall was reported the next day in Choglontus and Manzano.
A plume at 6.7 km altitude was moving slowly NW around noon.
New fumaroles not previously observed below the W flank of the crater were observed for the first time.
Tremors were followed by a significant explosion that produced ash emissions and block avalanches that traveled down the W flank.
Tremors were followed by a significant explosion that produced ash emissions and block avalanches that traveled down the W flank.

Tremors were followed by a significant explosion that produced ash emissions and block avalanches that traveled down the W flank. The Washington VAAC reported the ash plume 35 km WSW of the summit at 9.1 km altitude.
Tremors were followed by a significant explosion on that produced ash emissions and block avalanches that traveled down the W flank.
Ashfall reports were issued from the communities of Manzano, Choglontus, and Cahuaj¡, all located to the SW.

Four explosions produced Strombolian-style activity with incandescent blocks.  There were numerous reports of incandescent blocks and explosions heard on the N and E flanks during the evening and overnight into the next morning.

Four explosions produced Strombolian-style activity with incandescent blocks traveling down the Chomtapamba and Achupashal ravines. There were numerous reports of incandescent blocks and explosions heard on the N and E flanks during the evening and overnight into the next morning.

Four explosions produced an ash plume rising 2 km above the crater. The Washington  VAAC reported the ash plume extending W from the summit at 7.9 km altitude. Around 2000 local time, the ash plume resembled a large mushroom cloud.
Four explosions produced an ash plume rising 2 km above the crater, and ashfall in regions to the NW and SW including Manzano, Choglontus, Puela and Mocha.
An explosion in the early morning hours was heard at all of the stations around the volcano.
An explosion in the early morning hours was heard at all of the stations around the volcano.
An explosion was followed by ashfall in Choglontus.
An ash emission rose 1 km above the crater and drifted W and SW. The Washington VAAC reported the plume extending 55 km NW of the summit at 6.7 km altitude.

Dome #1. AVO reported the formation of a 40-m-wide lava dome in the summit crater that was observed on 29 July. Observations on 6 September indicated lava dome growth, reaching 120 m in diameter and filling the floor of the crater. A report on 20 September noted that recent observations revealed the lava dome had grown to ~165 m in diameter. The dome remained contained within the ~ 200-m-diameter crater at Cleveland's summit, having advanced to ~ 20 m below the E crater rim. AVO reported that a radar image from 23 October indicated a lowering of the lava dome surface in Cleveland's summit crater.
Ground-coupled airwaves from an explosion were detected at the distant Okmok seismic network, placing the time of explosion at 1312 (UTC).

Dome #2. A new 40-m-wide lava dome in the summit crater was observed in satellite imagery on 30 January. On 17 February, AVO reported that partly-cloudy satellite observations over the past week revealed that the current lava dome had grown to about 60 m in diameter and occupied a small portion of the approximately 200-m diameter summit crater. AVO reported that satellite observations of Cleveland during 22-28 February revealed that the growth of the lava dome continued at a slow rate.

AVO reported that a small explosion was detected at 1905 on 7 March by distant seismic stations and infrasound arrays. Another small explosion was detected at 1605 on 9 March. AVO reported that a small explosion was detected at 1455 on 13 March by distant seismic stations and infrasound arrays.

Dome #3. AVO reported the formation of a new lava dome, observed in satellite imagery on 28 March, which extruded in the summit crater during the previous week. Observations on 5 April revealed that the 70-m-diameter lava dome had been destroyed by an explosion.
AVO reported that a small explosion was detected at 0112 by distant seismic stations and infrasound arrays.

Dome #4. AVO reported that elevated surface temperatures were detected over Cleveland in satellite imagery during 25-29 April and possibly on 30 April. Observations showed that a small lava dome, 25 m across, had recently been emplaced.  Based on analyses of satellite images, AVO reported on 4 May that the small lava dome recently emplaced in Cleveland's summit crater had been destroyed late in the previous week, but the explosion was too small to be detected by distant infrasound and seismic networks.

Based on analyses of satellite images, AVO reported on 4 May that the small lava dome recently emplaced in Cleveland's summit crater had been destroyed late in the previous week, but the explosion was too small to be detected by distant infrasound and seismic networks.

Dome #5. A small new dome was extruded following the explosion. AVO reported that satellite images from 17 August showed that the summit crater was tephra-covered, funnel-shaped, and contained no lava dome.

Dome #6 On 6 February AVO reported that satellite imagery acquired on 30 January indicated that a lava dome had grown in Cleveland's summit crater. The dome was about 100 m in diameter and may have begun forming as early as 24 January when elevated surface temperatures were observed in satellite images. The size and shape of the dome appeared to be unchanged based on satellite data acquired on 2 February. On 8 March AVO noted that the lava dome had remained unchanged since 6 February. Although cloud cover often prevents observations of the dome, clear views between 1 and 5 March verified no changes.

Precursors included two moderate earthquakes and many smaller shocks; an earthquake of ~ M 4.8 accompanied the eruption. A U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service research crew camped on Sarigan Island reported many felt earthquakes prior to the eruption.
Jokulhlaups (floods of meltwater) reached the lowlands around the volcano with peak flow around noon, damaging roads, infrastructure, and farmlands.

Meltwater flowed to the N and S. News outlets reported that a circular ice-free area about 200 m in diameter was seen near the summit. Jokulhlaups (floods of meltwater) reached the lowlands around the volcano with peak flow around noon, damaging roads, infrastructure, and farmlands. A second jokulhlaup/lahar traveled down the Markarfljot valley that evening. Debris-charged jokulhlaups were seen in the evening on 16 April.
